<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pacific-AIDS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government inaction may lead to AIDS explosion in Pacific
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT KEITH-REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SUVA, Fiji (AP) _ Widespread complacency and ignorance among
many Pacific Island leaders could result in an explosion of AIDS in
the region, two of Oceania's leading anti-AIDS workers said
Thursday.
	   Steven Vete, the Tongan director of the Suva-based AIDS project
run by the U.N. Development Program, said many political leaders
``can't grasp or get to grips with the problem'' of emerging
infection in island communities.
	   He said governments had been inactive or ineffective in
following up on the establishment of AIDS task force committees
formed in the region in recent years.
	   Jane Tyler, director of an Australian-funded non-government
organization AIDS Task Force in Fiji, said: ``There is enormous
complacency, there is no political will and throughout the region
there is no true understanding of the nature and treatment of
HIV-AIDs.''
	   She said the small number of reported AIDS cases in the Pacific
Islands compared to other nations belies the extent of the inroads
the disease has made in the region.
	   According to the Pacific Community, a regional economic and
social development agency, the number of reported cases in a region
of 7 million people in 22 Pacific countries rose from 26 HIV and
three AIDS cases in 1986 to 1,757 HIV and 584 AIDS cases in October
1998.
	   ``From the time of infection to the time the disease becomes
evident is about eight years, and this in a region where the level
of sexual activity involving young people is very, very high,''
Tyler said.
	   Vete said governments were claiming there was no money to combat
AIDS, and that awareness propaganda couldn't be printed or
broadcast without violating strong cultural taboos against
discussion of sexual matters.
	   But experience with anti-AIDS projects in Samoa, the Solomon
Islands and Tonga had shown people there were highly receptive to
explicit information, Vete said.
	   ``For leaders to say `It is against our tradition' is just an
excuse for inaction,'' he said.
	   Tyler, whose task force fostered strong regional interest
through its previous work with prostitutes and homosexuals, said it
was still seeking funding for work planned for 1999 on building a
network of regional non-government organizations alerted to the
AIDS menace.
	   Kiribati, a country of 34 atolls inhabited by 84,000
Micronesians, is rated by AIDS experts as being exceptionally
exposed to the AIDS threat due to infection carried home by
thousands of Kiribati seamen employed aboard foreign cargoships.
	   President Teburoro Tito told The Associated Press: ``I don't
know what to do with this AIDS. I don't know how it is coming.
	   ``Maybe it is the wind that brings it, or whatever, or maybe the
seamen, or maybe the visitors coming in, the visitors or guests.'' 	   
</TEXT>
