<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Australia-England </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No Christmas morning sleep-in for English
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Santa Claus has arrived early for
the English cricket team, bringing wives and girlfriends to join
the players on their beleagured tour of Australia.
	   Otherwise, England will be sweating through fielding training on
Christmas morning at the Melbourne Cricket Ground in preparation
for Saturday's fourth Ashes test against Australia.
	   The holiday marks another day on the touring calendar for
England, although morale has been lifted by the arrival of wives
and girlfriends for the festive season.
	   From England's point of view, Friday also happens to be the eve
of one of cricket's biggest days, the opening of the Dec. 26 test.
	   More than 70,000 people are expected to follow tradition and
flock to cricket's oldest test venue on Saturday regardless of the
Ashes already having been decided in Australia's favor after three
tests.
	   Australia's test squad will gather at the team hotel Saturday
before a low-key training session in the afternoon to run off the
Christmas lunch.
	   One man certain not to over-indulge is fast bowler Glenn
McGrath, who will be required to prove his fitness after missing
training Thursday with a virus.
	   England will name its team after the Christmas Day fielding
session.
	   The Australian team: Mark Taylor (captain), Steve Waugh, Michael
Slater, Justin Langer, Mark Waugh, Darren Lehmann, Ian Healy,
Damien Fleming, Stuart MacGill, Matthew Nicholson, Glenn McGrath,
Colin Miller (12th man to be named). (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
