w1864 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-US-CubanChristmas     12-24 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Cuban Christmas,0695 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Legal or not, relatives head to Cuba to celebrate Christmas
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRIS HAWLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Cuban exiles call it the
``Christmas disease'' _ a wave of ``serious'' illnesses that
relatives cite each year in requesting U.S. government permission
to visit loved ones in Cuba during the holidays.
	   Since Cuban President Fidel Castro decided to reinstate
Christmas, the epidemic has only become worse.
	   ``It's amazing how everyone gets sick around this time _ there
are more serious cases of sickness in Cuba than there are hospital
beds,'' said Raul Alzaga, one of three travel agents in Puerto Rico
licensed to arrange trips to Cuba.
	   The phenomenon seemed to intensify last year, after Castro
granted a one-time Christmas holiday as a favor to Pope John Paul
II and the United States moved to loosen travel restrictions,
Alzaga said.
	   This year, Castro decided to make the holiday permanent on the
communist island, and the number of Alzaga's customers traveling in
December to visit their supposedly sick relatives has risen by
about a third to 160, he said.
	   The U.S. Treasury Department, which regulates travel to Cuba,
does not track individual passengers visiting sick relatives unless
they make more than one trip per year. That makes it difficult to
estimate the number of travelers, an agency spokeswoman said.
	   However, Cuba claims about 70,000 emigrants in the United States
and elsewhere visited the island last year. It is unclear how many
entered to visit relatives.
	   The yuletide disease is well-known in Miami, where thousands of
Cuban emigrants live, said Ramon Saul Sanchez, a delegate of the
exile group Democracy Movement.
	   ``I know it goes on,'' he said. ``What's unfortunate is that a
government exists in our country that forces its citizens into
exile for having different views than the government _ and that in
the United States there exists a policy that turns the genuine
practice of returning to one's country into a covert action.''
	   Joaquin Lima, 67, a Cuban now living in Puerto Rico, said he was
leaving Thursday to visit a sister with hypertension. But he said
he was loaded down with Christmas gifts _ ``Things they can't
afford there, like clothing and shoes and towels.''
	   He said hundreds more are probably heading to Cuba illegally,
buying tickets to Havana in the Dominican Republic or Panama City.
	   The United States declared an economic embargo of Cuba in 1963,
and since then has barred Americans from traveling to Cuba, with
only a few exceptions.
	   This year, about 800 people in Puerto Rico traveled legally
through travel agencies, Alzaga estimated.
	   There have never been enough travelers from Puerto Rico to
warrant direct flights like the periodic charters in Miami, Alzaga
said. Most trips he arranges have connections in other countries.
	   Lima, who waited 10 years for permission to leave Cuba and
finally emigrated with his 70-year-old wife, Magda, in 1994, said
an easing of U.S. travel laws _ not Castro's announcement _ has
caused the surge in travel.
	   It was the reason he decided to return home for the first time.
	   ``People have always gotten together around Christmas _ before
the revolution and after,'' he said. ``The tradition is stronger
than that.''
	   Earlier this year, the U.S. government allowed the resumption of
direct flights to Cuba, banned in 1996 after Cuban jets shot down
two light airplanes flown by the Miami exile group Brothers to the
Rescue.
	   Since the pope's visit to Cuba in 1997, the U.S. restrictions
have eased somewhat, Alzaga said. Charter flights to Cuba from
Miami were allowed to resume in May, wire transfers to family
members of dlrs 300 every three months were allowed to resume in
March, and pharmaceutical and medical companies can send executives
to Cuba in connection with sales there.
	   And as long as U.S. officials do not require proof of a
relative's illness, Christmas illness may continue unchecked,
Alzaga said.
	   ``I have a lot of regular customers,'' he said. ``People whose
relatives get sick every year'' _ around Christmas. 	   
</TEXT>
