<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shares close higher on U.S., European gains
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Share prices in Hong Kong ended higher, with
the key index gaining 1.3 percent in a shortened pre-Christmas
trading session Thursday following gains in U.S. and European
markets.
	   The blue-chip Hang Seng Index ended up 133.45 points at
10,292.20. It fell 1.6 percent Wednesday. But a holiday mood kept
trading volume among the lowest levels in more than two years.
	   Turnover at the midday close was a mere 1.51 billion Hong Kong
dollars (U.S. dlrs 193.6 million), compared with 1.36 billion Hong
Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 174.4 million) at midday Wednesday, and
2.23 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 285.9 million) for all of
Wednesday.
	   ``We're just marking up on the back of overseas markets,'' said
Miles Remington, a trader at SG Securities Ltd.
	   The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 157.57 points to
9,202.03 Wednesday, and several European markets were up strongly.
	   There was no local news to trade on, and with markets thin, it
was hard to spot clear trends, traders said.
	   The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong was closed at midday for
Christmas. Financial markets reopen on Monday.
	   On the Hang Seng Index, the top performers included Hutchison
Whampoa Ltd. and Cheung Kong (Holdings) Ltd., controlled by tycoon
Li Ka-shing.
	   Both stocks were battered Wednesday in response to comments Li
made that the political environment in Hong Kong discouraged him
from investing in the city, a criticism apparently aimed at
pro-democracy legislators.
	   Hutchison ended up 1.75 Hong Kong dollars, or 3.2 percent, to
55.75. Cheung Kong gained 1.3 percent, or 75 Hong Kong cents, to
close at 58.0.
	   China Telecom (Hong Kong) Ltd. also rose slightly, after
dropping more than 10 percent since Tuesday, after the company's
mobile phone calling rates were cut. It gained 10 Hong Kong cents
to 13.10.
	   HSBC Holdings PLC., which dominates the Hang Seng Index, gained
1 percent, or 2.0, to end at 199.0 Hong Kong dollars. 	   
</TEXT>
