<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Anwar Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense calls for playing tape in court to prove conspiracy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with court comment
 &UR; By R. MAGESWARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Lawyers defending Malaysia's
ousted deputy prime minister in a sex and corruption trial failed
Thursday to win permission to play a tape-recording of a
conversation they say will show a conspiracy against him.
	   But the trial judge, Augustine Paul said he would allow the tape
to be played if defense lawyers could point to inconsistencies in
the weeklong testimony of Ummi Hafilda Ali, the prosecution's star
witness.
	   Excerpts of the recording were read Wednesday but Paul barred
the press from reporting the conversation that the defense claimed
involved Ummi.
	   Paul had said initially he would rule Thursday on whether the
transcript of the conversation was admissible as evidence. But the
decision was put off when the court adjourned until Monday at the
defense's request.
	   Anwar turned to reporters during a court recess and said
smilingly: ``Be optimistic against all odds.''
	   ``Have confidence in the system,'' he said quietly.
	   As the court convened Thursday, defense lawyer Gurbachan Singh
sought permission to play the tape so that he could get Ummi to
agree to having made all the statements contained in the recording.
	   Later, Anwar's chief defense attorney, Raja Aziz Addruse, said
the defense could produce proof of Ummi's inconsistent testimony if
granted time to interview her alleged partner in the taped
conversation, Malaysian businessman Sng Chee Hua.
	   Ummi, a 31-year-old advertising executive, is the prime mover of
all the charges against Anwar. She wrote a letter to Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and distributed copies of it last year. It
contained allegations that Anwar was sleeping with his secretary's
wife.
	   Much of the prosecution case hinges on Ummi's testimony and her
credibility since she also helped Azizan Abu Bakar, a former driver
in Anwar's household, write out a declaration that Anwar repeatedly
sodomized him.
	   Anwar's lawyers have accused Ummi of acting out of jealousy
because of her unreciprocated love for the 51-year-old politician.
She denied that she was crazy about Anwar and kept a photograph of
him under her pillow.
	   Singh had read out bits of a conversation that Ummi was alleged
to have had in June with Malaysian businessman Sng. It was unclear
if Ummi knew their conversation had been recorded.
	   Raja Aziz informed the court that Sng had been summoned to
police headquarters Wednesday evening for questioning.
	   ``While this case is going on and he is a relevant witness in
this matter, the police cannot do such a thing,'' Raja Aziz told
the court. The judge rejected a request to restrain the police.
	   The defense hoped to use the conversation to prove its theory of
a government conspiracy involving several senior cabinet ministers
to destroy Anwar's career.
	   Anwar has denied all 10 charges of illegal sex and corruption,
saying they were fabricated. 	   
</TEXT>
