<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo shares down after bank sell-off, dollar lower against yen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing stocks, mid-afternoon bond and dollar
rates &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Tokyo stocks fell moderately Thursday amid worries
about the strength of the country's banks. The dollar moved lower
against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 72.72 points,
or 0.53 percent, to close at 13,706.73. On Tuesday, the average
finished down 373.50 points, or 2.64 percent.
	   The dollar bought 116.28 yen in mid-afternoon trading, down 0.80
yen from its level of 117.08 late in Tokyo on Tuesday but above
115.96 yen late in New York on Wednesday.
	   Tokyo markets were closed Wednesday for a national holiday.
	   Investors sold bank shares on fears that a recent drop in bond
prices would hurt profits, analysts said.
	   Bond prices tumbled, and interest rates rose Tuesday following
the Japanese government's announcement that it would issue new
bonds to pay for massive stimulus spending next fiscal year.
	   The government has been going deeper into debt as it spends more
to kickstart economic growth.
	   The bond market was also hurt buy an announcement from the
Finance Ministry that it would stop buying back some bonds itself,
a practice that has supported prices by limiting supply.
	   ``Until bond prices settle down, the stock market is going to
remain unstable,'' said Sachio Ishikawa, manager at Chuo
Securities.
	   Profits from bond trading and investments have been one of the
only bright spots for many of Japan's debt-plagued banks and
traders worry that a fall in bond prices will wipe out many of
those gains.
	   Bank shares were also lower after U.S. ratings agency Standard
and Poor's said it lowered certain ratings on Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank,
Daiwa Bank, the Industrial Bank of Japan, Sakura Bank, Sanwa Bank,
Sumitomo Bank, and Tokai Bank.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section lost 8.28 points, or 0.76 percent, to 1,074.18. On
Tuesday the market closed down 16.66 points, or 1.52 percent, to
1,082.46.
	   Stocks fell despite a strong gain overnight on Wall Street.
	   There, the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 157.57, or 1.7
percent, to close at 9,202.03, extending its gains to 411 points
over the past five sessions and nearing the Nov. 23 record of
9,374.27.
	   In currency trading, the dollar fell from its level Wednesday in
Tokyo as banks sold the U.S. currency, traders said.
	   But with little activity ahead of the Christmas holiday, the
market lacked direction, traders said.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 1.890 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.900 percent,
pushing the price up to 99.27 yen from 99.19 yen.
 &UR; (gp-tz-dj)
</TEXT>
