</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-US-Prisoner's Lawsuit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jailed American files suit in Japan to protest alleged abuse
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Lawyers for a U.S. citizen serving a 6-year prison
sentence said they filed suit Thursday to protest alleged
mistreatment of their client, including physical abuse by prison
guards and more than four years in solitary confinement.
	   The suit, filed with the Tokyo District Court, seeks 10 million
yen (dlrs 86,000) in compensation from the Japanese government for
causing undue mental and physical suffering to Johnny Crittenden, a
39-year old native of Georgia.
	   ``It is a very symbolic case about Japan's prison situation,''
said Yuichi Kaido, an attorney representing the American plaintiff,
adding that the problems highlighted in the case are widespread in
the prison system.
	   Prison officials were unavailable for immediate comment.
	   Crittenden, who is scheduled to be released on January 7, claims
he was subjected to a beating, use of a leather restraining belt
which restricted normal breathing for a 24-hour period and unjust
solitary confinement.
	   All of the alleged mistreatment stemmed from Crittenden's
refusal of a haircut and shave, lawyer Kaido said.
	   Crittenden refused the haircut given to all new Japanese prison
inmates on the basis of his religious beliefs as a Rastafarian and
failed to shave as instructed one day due to a linguistic
misunderstanding, his lawyer said.
	   Practitioners of Rastafarianism, which originated in Jamaica,
are known for their faith's embracement of long, dreadlock-style
hair-braids.
	   As a result, attorney Kaido said his client was unable to speak
with other inmates at Fuchu prison outside Tokyo, one of three
which holds foreign nationals, or participate in any group
activities for more than 4 1/2 years.
	   ``It is not a matter of money. It is a matter of justice and
rights,'' Crittenden was quoted as saying by his attorney, who
declined to specify the crimes for which his client was convicted.
	   Kaido was unable to provide Crittenden's hometown.
	   Earlier this month, a Japanese court ordered the state to pay
150,000 yen (dlrs 1,290) in compensation to an American who was
beaten up by guards at another Japanese prison. Keith Dickerson,
33, of Santa Barbara, Calif., had sought 3.3 million yen (dlrs
28,380).
	   In November, the United Nations Human Rights Committee issued a
report saying it was ``deeply concerned at many aspects of the
prison system in Japan,'' including harsh rules of conduct, severe
punishment measures and the frequent use of restraining devices. 	   
</TEXT>
