r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-HolidaySpending     12-24 0251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Holiday Spending </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Survey: Worries about economy curtail Japanese holiday spending
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ With Japan's economy mired in recession, families
here will likely spend less on travel and gifts this holiday
season, according to a survey released Thursday.
	   More Japanese families plan to spend the New Year's holiday at
home this year, while those that travel will spend less, according
to a poll of 350 households by Sanwa Bank.
	   The people surveyed said their families would spend an average
of 163,000 yen (dlrs 1,405) during the three-day New Year's
holiday, including money for travel and gifts. That amount was
18,000 yen (dlrs 155) less than a year before, the bank said.
	   According to the poll, 37.7 percent of households were planning
to travel an average of just under three days during the holiday
season and spend an average of 110,000 yen, the lowest in five
years.
	   The bank didn't give a margin of error for its survey.
	   New Year's is one of Japan's biggest holidays, and many people
travel to their home towns to spend the first few days of the year
with their families.
	   Many children look forward to the holiday because of the
Japanese custom of giving kids gifts of cash.
	   But some children may be disappointed this year as families were
budgeting less for such gifts.
	   Those surveyed said they planned to give the junior-high kids on
their gift-lists an average of 5,852 yen (dlrs 50), 1,618 yen (dlrs
14) less than last year.
 &UR; (tz)
</TEXT>
