w1898 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Economy     12-24 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Primakov says he will resign if budget isn't passed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said Thursday he
and his government would resign if Russia's parliament doesn't pass
a 1999 budget, a news report said.
	   Russia's lower house of parliament, the State Duma, was to begin
debating the budget Thursday. Primakov has widespread support in
the Duma, and it was expected to pass the document with less
trouble than in previous years.
	   In a meeting with President Boris Yeltsin in the Kremlin,
Primakov said he and his deputies ``would not remain in our posts''
if the Duma doesn't pass the budget, according to the Interfax news
agency.
	   ``The budget must be severe,'' he said. ``We can't lie to
anyone.''
	   ``What do you think, can a country live without a budget in such
a time? Of course not. It must be passed,'' he said.
	   Russia is gripped by its worst economic crisis since the Soviet
collapse. Foreign lenders froze aid to the country after the
government defaulted on some debts and devalued the currency in
August.
	   The proposed budget ran into trouble Wednesday, when a number of
parliamentary factions reversed course and said they would demand
that a vote on the document be postponed.
	   They were responding to a letter from the upper house of
parliament, the Federation Council, which disapproves of the
government's plans to change the way tax revenues are distributed
between the regions and the federal government.
	   The Federation Council, made up of regional governors fiercely
protective of funds to their regions, usually passes the budget
without much debate.
	   Primakov was to hold closed-doors meeting with leaders from both
the upper and lower houses Thursday to determine whether the budget
can be passed in a first reading before next week.
	   The budget must pass four readings by the Duma before going to
the Federation Council.
	   Primakov wants a budget in place as soon as possible so the
government can tackle massive wage debts to state workers and jump
start the economy. Foreign lenders have said they will not resume
aid without a budget.
	   (nw/ren)
</TEXT>
