w1901 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-ForeignReserves     12-24 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Foreign Reserves </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China's foreign reserves inch upward as controls tighten
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China's foreign exchange reserves grew 0.6
percent to dlrs 144.59 billion at the end of November from a month
earlier as the government stepped up efforts to stop illegal
outflows of hard currency, central bank officials said Thursday.
	   A Beijing-based spokesman for the People's Bank of China, the
central bank, said reserves are steadily building again.
	   They had plateaued earlier this year and then began to shrink
this summer as dlrs 10 billion left the country through illicit
channels from July to September, Shanghai's central bank chief, Wu
Xiaoling, told reporters.
	   Chinese bank officials are anxious to show that reserves are not
sliding, a trend that could lead to a weakening of the currency,
the yuan. The government has made a stable yuan the foundation of
policies to counter the economic turmoil that has afflicted the
rest of Asia.
	   The government has launched a sustained campaign against illegal
foreign exchange trading and currency counterfeiting, making many
such activities subject to criminal laws.
	   China's yuan is only convertible for a limited range of uses,
such as trade. But companies and individuals have often
circumvented restrictions through phony trade invoices.
	   Efforts to exploit foreign exchange loopholes increased amid
fears that Beijing would devalue the yuan to support exports.
	   In south China's Guangdong province, fake customs clearance
forms accounted for 55 percent of such declarations above dlrs
200,000 in value, the newspaper People's Daily reported Thursday.
In August, Guangdong police and financial regulators discovered
fake customs clearance forms worth dlrs 370 million, it said.
	   As part of the clampdown, Beijing has ordered stronger scrutiny
of all customs documents and letters of credit from foreign banks.
	   Wu of the People's Bank of China conceded that tighter checks on
foreign exchange have hindered some overseas businesses seeking to
import equipment and repatriate profits. But officials say the
controls are needed to support foreign reserve levels.
	   ``Foreign reserves are a country's strategic resource. They can
ensure overseas payments, stabilize the exchange rate and safeguard
our international reputation,'' the People's Daily said in a
commentary.
</TEXT>
