r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-ChristmasAp     12-24 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Christmas Appeal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesia's Christian churches appeal for religious tolerance
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's Christian leaders, shaken
by recent attacks by Muslim mobs on Christian churches, appealed
for racial and religious harmony in a Christmas Eve message.
	   In a joint statement, the Christian Churches Association and the
Catholic Churches Conference vowed to encourage peaceful relations
among religious groups in predominately Muslim Indonesia.
	   ``We promise... to encourage solidarity among the sufferers
regardless of their racial or group differences,'' read the
statement.
	   The world's fourth most populous nation has endured sporadic
riots in recent months as social and religious tensions rise amid
the worst economic crisis in three decades.
	   Muslim mobs burned or ransacked more than a dozen churches on
Nov. 22 in the capital, Jakarta. Fourteen people were killed and
the violence sparked revenge attacks on mosques in other places.
	   Ninety percent of Indonesia's 200 million people are Muslim.
Most of the rest are Christian, Buddhist or Hindu. Tolerance of
religious diversity is enshrined in the national philosophy,
Pancasila.
	   Many Christians are ethnic Chinese, who have often been targeted
in riots because of their relative wealth and perceived links to
corrupt government officials.
	   In their statement, the church leaders also urged their
followers to fight graft and back political reforms that are being
promoted by President B.J. Habibie.
	   ``We believe God will always be with our society and nation as
it undergoes the period of big reforms,'' the statement said.
	   Habibie has pledged to overhaul the rigid political system left
by his authoritarian predecessor, Suharto, who quit in May after a
nationwide wave of riots and protests.
	   However, students who have staged sometimes violent protests
against security forces say Habibie is not serious about democratic
reform.
	   The students have temporarily halted their protests to mark the
Islamic holy month of Ramadan, which started Dec. 20.
</TEXT>
