w1913 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Bethlehem-ChristmasUn     12-24 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bethlehem-Christmas Under Construction,0697 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No Christmas-card look for Bethlehem this year
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo JRL104 of Dec. 23 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARK LAVIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BETHLEHEM, West Bank (AP) _ Mohammed Abu Radap sells shiny,
fresh apples from cartons atop a meter- (3-feet-) wide cement
cylinder that will one day be part of Bethlehem's new sewage
system.
	   Abu Radap has no complaints about the construction project in
Bethlehem's open-air market. Pointing to an almost-completed
building, he said proudly, ``I'll have a new store inside there.''
	   Like Manger Square half-kilometer (quarter-mile) away,
Bethlehem's market is being rebuilt with funds raised to give the
traditional birthplace of Jesus a facelift in time for millennium
celebrations. Some improvements will be ready for Christmas this
year, but most will not. Bethlehem, hardly picturesque even in the
best of times, is resigned to a messy holiday.
	   A brisk, cold wind swept Manger Square on Wednesday, whipping
sand into people's hair and eyes as workers laid rectangular stone
tiles while others mixed cement. A yellow tractor dumped a load of
sand in the middle of the square, where tourists and pilgrims
gather on Christmas eve in front of the Church of the Nativity.
	   The dreary scene was relieved a little Wednesday evening when
Soha Arafat, wife to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, lit the
Christmas tree in the square. She and her daughter Zahwa were
dressed in matching red outfits.
	   City officials hope the paving will be done in time for
Christmas. But there will be holes filled with sand where lights
and benches are supposed to be.
	   Though Bethlehem's mayors have had detailed renovation plans
ready for 25 years, it took the approach of the millennium to bring
in millions of dollars in contributions from foreign governments to
allow the project to begin.
	   The cost of renovating Manger Square is estimated at dlrs 12
million. The budget for redoing the rest of the city is more than
dlrs 200 million, said Mayor Hanna J. Nasser.
	   The goal is to finish most of it next year in time for the
millennium, when a million tourists are expected to visit the city.
	   Until then, projects like replacing Bethlehem's ancient, leaky
sewage system, repaving main roads, burying electric and telephone
cables and rebuilding the open-air market mean temporary
inconvenience for the 24,000 Palestinian residents.
	   A small woman wearing a brown head scarf picked her way over a
mound of rubble, carefully making her way toward a merchant selling
potatoes from a makeshift stand.
	   Open-air markets with merchants shouting out their prices as
people squeeze the fruit and vegetables are a central feature of
most Middle East cities. Bethlehem's plan is to replace the noisy
but friendly chaos with order and esthetics.
	   ``Of course it will be good to have a civilized market here,''
Mahmoud Rahhab said as he watched the construction from the door of
his small grocery store.
	   When it's completed, the outdoor tables will be replaced by
small, neat stalls facing out from two new stone buildings, a wide
walkway between the rows of shops.
	   Now it's mostly rubble, piles of sand, open trenches and sewer
pipes strewn around.
	   Rahhab, 62, owns the apartment building above his little store
and has been at this location for 50 years. The slim, neatly
dressed merchant was concerned only that the city keeps the place
clean when the renovations are finished.
	   ``Look around the corner, you'll see how dirty it was before,''
he suggested.
	   Around the corner, against the wall of one of the new buildings
going up at the market site, plastic crates were piled high with
live chickens about to be slaughtered.
	   The smell was as noticeable as the squashed vegetables and trash
on the ground. Before construction began, most of the Bethlehem
market looked like that. The plan is to eliminate the mess, if not
the noise and the smell.
	   City officials admit openly that they're taking advantage of the
millennium to remake their city for the benefit of their people,
long after tourists finish celebrating Christmas this week and the
millennium next year.
</TEXT>
