w1932 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-EthnicKoreans     12-24 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Ethnic Koreans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese city hit by atomic bomb makes concession to ethnic Koreans
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Hiroshima, one of two Japanese cities decimated by
atomic bombs in the closing days of World War II, has decided to
allow the relocation of a monument dedicated to Korean victims of
the bombing to a central memorial park, a local official said
Thursday.
	   Hiroshima Mayor Takashi Hiraoka's decision to relocate the
cenotaph was widely seen as a gesture of outreach to Japan's Korean
community, which has long complained of a pervasive bias against
them
	   The stone monument, which was built in 1970, will be moved
inside the city's Peace Memorial Park next summer, said the city
official, who declined to be named. The official was unable to say
who would fund the move, but local media reported a Korean
residents group would pay the expenses.
	   The five-meter-high (16.5-foot) monument was built three years
after the city banned construction of new edifices in the park,
which is located at the epicenter of the blast that killed 140,000
people on Aug. 6, 1945.
	   But Koreans living in Japan have viewed the ban as a slight
because the park is home to many other monuments commemorating
those who died in the bombing of the city.
	   About 640,000 Koreans live in Japan, many of whom are the
descendants of workers and conscripts brought over during Japan's
1910-1945 colonial rule on the Korean peninsula. The Korean
community says it often faces discrimination in hiring and
marriage.
	   Three days after the destruction of Hiroshima, another atomic
bomb was dropped on Nagasaki, killing 70,000 people. Japan
surrendered unconditionally on Aug. 15.
 &UR; (cd)
</TEXT>
