<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Arson Trial,0197 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish appeals court orders retrial for 33 Islamic extremists
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ An appeals court on Thursday ordered a
second retrial for 33 Islamic extremists, sentenced to death for
seeking to impose Islamic rule in this predominantly Muslim but
secular country.
	   The defendants have been on trial for killing 37 left-wing
intellectuals in a 1993 arson attack.
	   Prosecutor Demirel Tavil said the second retrial was ordered on
technical grounds. Private NTV television said the court ruled
there was insufficient documentation on the defendants' identities.
	   The 33 were originally sentenced to 15 years in prison but a
retrial switched the prison terms to capital punishment last year.
	   Despite issuing death penalties, Turkey has not carried out
executions since 1984.
	   The arson attack targeted a hotel in the central city of Sivas
where the victims had gathered to commemorate a 16th century poet
who was hanged for his opposition to religious oppression.
	   The attackers chanted slogans of an illegal radical Islamic
group while the hotel was ablaze. They barred firefighters from
approaching the scene.
</TEXT>
