<HEADER>
w1938 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-DeathPena     12-24 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Death Penalty </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Date set for first Philippine execution in 22 years
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ A poor house painter convicted of
raping his 10-year-old stepdaughter will be executed on Jan. 4, the
first execution in the Philippines in 22 years, according to court
documents Thursday.
	   The documents give the first public announcement of the date of
the execution of Leo Echegaray, who is among 844 inmates on death
row.
	   Judge Thelma Ponferrada of the Quezon City Regional Trial Court
earlier set the date for Echegaray's execution by lethal injection.
	   She had initially ordered prison authorities not to announce the
date in advance, in accordance with government rules. But the
attention attracted by the execution brought pressure to release
the date ahead of time.
	   The planned execution has triggered a debate among Filipinos
over capital punishment.
	   In a resolution Wednesday, at least 35 members of the House of
Representatives urged President Joseph Estrada to declare a
``moratorium'' on the execution of death convicts pending a review
of the death penalty law.
	   Several countries, including the European Union, the Vatican and
Canada, have also appealed to Estrada to cancel Echegaray's
execution and repeal the death penalty.
	   Estrada, however, has refused to pardon Echegaray, saying his
execution will deter similar crimes.
	   In 1987, a new constitution abolished the death penalty but gave
Congress the option to restore it for ``heinous'' crimes such as
murder, ransom kidnapping, rape and drug trafficking.
	   Legislators, alarmed by a rise in crime, brought back the death
penalty in 1994.
	   Many Filipinos believe that the death penalty will deter crime
and that crime remains rampant because no one has been executed.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Philippines-Death Penalty; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
