<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo shares down after bank sell-off, dollar lower against yen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS lede; UPDATES with late-afternoon bond and dollar
rates

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Worries that rising interest rates could deliver
another blow to Japan's ailing banks drove Tokyo stocks lower
Thursday. The dollar sank against the yen in light trading.
	   The dollar bought 116.12 yen in late-afternoon trading, down
0.96 yen from its level of 117.08 late in Tokyo on Tuesday but
slightly above 115.96 yen late in New York on Wednesday.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 72.72 points,
or 0.53 percent, to close at 13,706.73. On Tuesday, the average
finished down 373.50 points, or 2.64 percent.
	   Tokyo markets were closed Wednesday for a national holiday.
	   Stocks fell for a third straight session as investors worried
that the dramatic plunge in the price of Japanese government bonds
this week, and a corresponding jump in interest rates, would hurt
corporate profits, especially at the country's already badly-shaken
banks.
	   Interest rates began rising Tuesday following the Japanese
government's announcement that it would issue a record amount of
new bonds next year to pay for an increase in spending.
	   The government has been going deeper into debt as it spends more
to kickstart economic growth.
	   The bond market was also hurt buy an announcement from the
Finance Ministry that it would stop buying back some of those bonds
itself, a practice that has supported prices by limiting supply.
	   ``Until bond prices settle down, the stock market is going to
remain unstable,'' said Sachio Ishikawa, manager at Chuo Securities
Co.
	   Profits from bond trading have been one of the only bright spots
for many of Japan's debt-plagued banks, and traders worry that a
fall in bond prices will wipe out many of those gains.
	   Bank shares were also lower after U.S. ratings agency Standard
and Poor's said it lowered certain ratings on Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank
Ltd., Daiwa Bank Ltd., the Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd., Sakura
Bank Ltd., Sanwa Bank Ltd., Sumitomo Bank Ltd. and Tokai Bank Ltd.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section lost 8.28 points, or 0.76 percent, to 1,074.18. On
Tuesday the market closed down 16.66 points, or 1.52 percent, to
1,082.46.
	   Trading on the main section of the Tokyo exchange was estimated
at 320.80 million shares, down from 361.73 million shares Tuesday.
	   Declines outnumbered advances 778 to 318, while 208 issues were
unchanged.
	   In currency trading, the dollar fell from its level Wednesday in
Tokyo as banks sold the U.S. currency, traders said.
	   But with little activity ahead of the Christmas holiday, the
market lacked direction.
	   The U.S. currency traded in a range between 115.05 yen and
116.60 yen in Tokyo.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 1.885 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.900 percent,
pushing the price up to 99.31 yen from 99.19 yen.
 &UR; (gp-tz-dj)
</TEXT>
