w1948 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-NewWine     12-24 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-New Wine </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thailand's top brewer set to uncork new wine
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By THAKSINA KHAIKAEW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's biggest brewery is set to
uncork the country's second domestically-produced wine, even though
company executives say an economic crisis has made it anything but
a vintage year for launching new products.
	   The first lot of 100,000 bottles of Boon Rawd Brewery's new Khao
Yai wine is expected to hit the market early next month, Isara
Khaosa-ad, the company's brewery manager, said on Thursday.
	   Red wine dominates the lot, but Boon Rawd, the maker of
Thailand's top-selling Singha beer, will also be offering rose and
white, he said.
	   ``Thais like red wine because of the color,'' said Isara.
	   Drinking wine became fashionable among the Thai middle class
when money was easy and the economy was the fastest growing in the
world from 1985-95.
	   Thailand's Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart has been known
to favor 100,000 baht (dlrs 2,777) bottles of wine, and other
politicians lavish rare wines on their colleagues as gifts.
	   But many Thais have been forced to cut back on expensive habits
since an economic crisis hit the country in July 1997.
	   Unfortunately for Boon Rawd, which began planning Khao Yai six
years ago and has invested 200 million baht (dlrs 5.5 million) in
it, the company could not foresee the coming recession.
	   They have scaled back on how much wine they will release on to
the market, Isara said, but he believes that the economic crisis
may in fact work to Khao Yai's benefit.
	   Most wines are imported and subject to tariffs that make them
fairly expensive by Thai standards. But domestically-produced Khao
Yai won't be subject to those taxes.
	   ``The affordable price will be a good selling point to compete
with imported wines,'' Isara said, while declining to say how much
the wine will sell for.
	   ``We are expecting to do just fine during the hard times when
people are tightening the belt. For future expansion we need to see
the reaction of the market to our product,'' he said.
	   Boon Rawd's vintages are the second domestically-grown wines,
following Chateau d'Loei, launched in 1996 by Ital-Thai, a
construction conglomerate.
	   Boon Rawd's grapes are cultivated on a vineyard in Pak Chong
district of Nakorn Ratchasima Province, 210 kilometers (130 miles)
northeast of Bangkok, where the land and climate is acceptably
cool, Isara said.
	   The company has a small winery equipped with technology imported
from Italy and under the supervision of a winemaker from Germany.
	   ``Our wine tastes as good as imported wines,'' insisted Prayuth
Piangbunta, one of Boonrawd's Thai winemakers.
	   He said the company does not expect strong competition from
Chateau d'Loei, which produces at small scale. Right now, however,
the goal is to become accepted in the market and have the product
survive the current hard times.
	   Prayuth said he also hoped a government-sponsored campaign to
buy Thai products, called the Thai-Help-Thai campaign, will
encourage locals to give Khao Yai a try.
	   ``We hope that the economic crisis will turn attitudes around
and Thais will opt to drink locally produced wines,'' he said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Thailand-New Wine; CT:i; 
