<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Auto Output </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Number of new autos built in Japan falls again
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The number of new cars and trucks to roll off
Japanese assembly lines fell in November, an industry group said
Thursday, as recession at home and in neighboring Asian nations
continued to hurt demand.
	   The number of new vehicles built last month was 848,266, down
1.3 percent from the same time a year ago, the Japan Automobile
Manufacturers Association said.
	   The number has fallen or broken even for 13 of the last 14
months, the association said. It recorded its only rise of the year
in October.
	   While robust exports to the United States helped the number of
passenger cars built in November rise 5.6 percent, the number of
new trucks plunged by a quarter.
	   In total, Japanese carmakers have built 8.5 percent less cars
and trucks so far this year compared to the same 11-month period
the year before.
</TEXT>
