w1989 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-EastTimor     12-24 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Habibie wants to meet East Timor's bishops to discuss peace efforts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ President B.J. Habibie wants to meet
East Timor's Roman Catholic bishops to discuss efforts to make
peace in the troubled territory, an Indonesian official said
Thursday.
	   Talks on how to end the conflict in the former Portuguese colony
have gained ground since the resignation of authoritarian President
Suharto in May after 32 years in power.
	   Suharto ordered the Indonesian military to invade East Timor in
1975, triggering a separatist guerrilla war and widespread human
rights abuses.
	   His successor, President B.J. Habibie, has taken a more
conciliatory approach and soon wants to meet East Timor's bishops,
Carlos Belo and Basilio Do Nascimento.
	   ``If possible, (the meeting) could take place before or just
after the New Year,'' Lopes Da Cruz, Indonesia's ambassador for
East Timor, said after a meeting with the president.
	   Habibie met Belo six months ago in Jakarta.
	   Jakarta has offered greater autonomy to East Timor in exchange
for international recognition of its sovereignty. Pro-independence
activists, however, say any autonomy deal must be transitional and
that a vote on self-determination must eventually take place.
	   The United Nations does not recognize Indonesian rule over the
half-island territory and is sponsoring peace talks between
Indonesia and Portugal, which it considers the administering power.
	   East Timor Gov. Abilio Osorio Soares, who also attended the
meeting with Habibie, said the president wants the bishops and
other public figures to promote the idea of autonomy.
	   Belo, co-winner of the 1996 Nobel peace prize, has been a harsh
critic of Indonesian policy in East Timor but has been supportive
of negotiations.
	   Jamsheed Marker, the U.N. envoy for East Timor, left Indonesia
on Wednesday after meetings with pro- and anti-independence
figures.
</TEXT>
