w2009 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo UPDATE   12-24 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb forces launch new offensive, Kosovo Albanian sources claim
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ethnic Albanian sources claim Serb
forces launched a strong offensive Thursday on a Kosovo rebel
stronghold in the north of the province. The report could not be
immediately confirmed.
	   The Kosovo Albanian Information Center said heavy Serb military
and police forces began a sweeping attack at 9 a.m. (0800 GMT),
targeting six villages near Podujevo, 32 kilometers (20 miles)
north of provincial capital Pristina.
	   The Center said that the focus of the attack was near Lapastica,
a stronghold of the guerrilla secessionist Kosovo Liberation Army,
just west of Podujevo. The report said tanks had already entered
Lapastica.
	   It claimed that Serb army and police, including special police
forces, were shelling the region's villages across a 17-kilometer
(11 miles) stretch of terrain and that several ethnic Albanian
houses were set ablaze.
	   The Center also said that so far, one ethnic Albanian villager
from Sekiraca village was reported killed in the attack but
indicated it had no conclusive casualty toll.
	   An ethnic Albanian spokesman told reporters in Pristina Thursday
that the latest attack was planned in advance by Belgrade
authorities.
	   ``This offensive confirms our worst fears that the Serbian
regime planned to use the Christmas holidays to launch an action
aimed at ethnically cleansing the north of Kosovo,'' spokesman
Xemail Mustafa said.
	   Mustafa called on urgent action by the international community
and Kosovo's verifiers to pressure Belgrade into halting the
offensive.
	   The head of Kosovo Information Center, Enver Maloku, told
reporters that shelling could be heard on the outskirts of
Podujevo.
	   (ih/kk/rr) 	   
</TEXT>
