<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Gays,0262 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police in north Indian city cracking down on gays following
</HEADLINE>
complaints &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LUCKNOW, India (AP) _ Police are preventing gays from going to a
park in the north Indian city of Lucknow following protests from
the public that they were having sex there, an official said
Thursday.
	   Policemen have been posted at the GPO Park, a popular rendezvous
for the city's gays, said police spokesman R.S.Tomar.
	   ``Police will not allow male couples into the park if they know
they are gays. ... Policemen will ask them if they are gay. If they
hold hands or are demonstrative about their affection, we'll
suspect them of being gay,'' he said in an interview.
	   State prosecutor S.K. Saluja said keeping gays out of parks
violates their rights, although police are within their rights to
prosecute those having sex or behaving in an obscene manner in
public. Sodomy is illegal in India, but prosecutions are rare.
	   Despite legal opinion, Tomar said police are determined to
prevent gays from frequenting the park.
	   ``The rights of others are as important as those of the gays,''
Tomar said.
	   Over the last three months, police have arrested five male
prostitutes on charges of soliciting, he said.
	   Anuj Mishra, a spokesman of Dost, an association of gays, said
meeting in the park is not a crime.
	   The group plans to hold demonstrations and sit-ins to protest
the police action, he said.
	   Public displays of affection even between men and women are rare
in India, where many believe homosexuals exists only in Western
nations.
</TEXT>
