<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Railway Threat </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security tight on German rails despite arrest of extortion suspect
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ The German railway plans to keep a
close eye on its tracks through the holidays despite the arrest of
an alleged extortionist who confessed to three acts of sabotage,
officials said Thursday.
	   A court on Thursday ordered the 46-year-old suspect, nabbed at a
highway rest area Tuesday night, to remain jailed pending probable
charges of attempted extortion.
	   Federal agents say the man confessed to trying to extort 10
million marks (dlrs 6 million) from the German railway by
sabotaging rail lines near Berlin.
	   In the most serious incident, a cargo train derailed on Dec. 18
after passing over tracks where the bolts had been loosened. No one
was hurt, but damage was put in the millions.
	   German rail officials said copycat threats continued even after
the arrest of the suspect and an alleged accomplice on Wednesday.
The accomplice, who allegedly provided the main suspect with an
auto, was later released but still faces charges.
	   Spokesman Reiner Latsch said train traffic had returned ``to a
certain normality,'' but that border police or other security
agencies would be called in immediately at the first sign of any
trouble.
	   A stretch of high-speed tracks in western Germany between
Goettingen and Kassel was shut for two and a half hours late
Wednesday after a phoned-in threat. Federal border police searched
the tracks but no problems were discovered.
 &UR; (pfg-tc)
</TEXT>
