r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Ukraine-Currency     12-24 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Currency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine plans to keep currency in trading band in 1999
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's central bank will cut interest
rates and maintain a currency trading band in 1999 if the
government meets its budget targets and keeps inflation under
control, a bank official said Thursday.
	   National Bank deputy chief Oleksandr Kyreyev said a 1999 trading
band for the national currency, the hryvna, should be set for at
least six month periods to help businesses better plan ahead and
prevent unexpected currency devaluations, the independent Ukrainian
News agency said.
	   Kyreyev did not say what range the new trading band should have.
	   The hryvna is trading at 3.42 to the U.S. dollar. It has held
stable for more than a month within the government-set trading band
of 2.5 to 3.5 to the dollar.
	   The currency was sharply devalued in the wake of economic crisis
in neighboring Russia this fall. After the National Bank drained
most of its reserves to defend the currency, some observers said
the hryvna ought to float freely.
	   But the National Bank has since managed to calm down the
markets, and even lowered its key interest rate from 82 percent to
60 percent last week.
	   Kyreyev said the interest rate could come down to 17 percent by
the end of 1999 if the government meets its revenue targets and
does not allow uncontrolled inflation to occur.
	   But the National Bank's optimistic plans could be jeopardized by
the government's chronic inability to implement reforms, which have
resulted in continued economic decline and poor tax collection.
	   With no big improvements forecast for 1999, many analysts have
said the National Bank will have a tough time holding the hryvna
stable if the Cabinet decides to pay off wage arrears by borrowing
or printing money.
	   The former Soviet republic's huge foreign debt presents another
danger. Ukraine's debt obligations for 1999 are now twice as large
as its hard currency reserves, which total dlrs 1 billion.
	   (vl/nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Ukraine-Currency; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
