<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0830 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of news from The Associated Press. Some items have
moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f'' category
codes:
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ After 36 years as a soldier, Israel's
former army chief of staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak left the military
Thursday to enter politics and likely challenge Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu as a centrist candidate. In his first news
conference as a civilian, urged Israelis to ``unite different parts
of our society.'' ``We must make peace among ourselves before we
make peace with our neighbors,'' he said. Shahak was on his way to
a meeting with President Ezer Weizman Thursday, the first of a
marathon of meetings inaugurating his political career. In an
interview in Thursday's editions of the newspaper Haaretz, Shahak
rejected opposition leader Ehud Barak's call to join his left-wing
Labor party. The newspaper quoted Shahak as saying if polls showed
centrist candidate Dan Meridor leading, he would be willing to join
him in the No. 2 slot. Meridor broke away from Netanyahu's
conservative Likud party and announced his candidacy Tuesday after
Israel's parliament voted for early elections. (ISRAEL-POLITICS)
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ State-run newspapers on Thursday said
Iraqis will not be intimidated by U.S. threats of strikes to force
Iraq to allow the resumption of U.N. weapons inspections. The
weapons inspection teams now exist only ``in the sick dreams
entertained by America,'' the official al-Iraq newspaper said in a
front page editorial. The U.N. Special Commission, or UNSCOM, began
work in 1991 to dismantle Iraq's programs to build weapons of mass
destruction. It withdrew its inspectors Dec. 16, saying Iraq was
scuttling their work. That night, the United States and Britain
launched airstrikes, and Iraq this week said UNSCOM will never be
allowed to resume its work. Until UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has
dismantled its programs to build nuclear, chemical and biological
weapons along with long-range missiles, U.N. trade sanctions
imposed on Iraq for its 1990 invasion of Kuwait cannot be lifted.
Iraq says more than 40 civilians and 62 soldiers were killed in the
U.S.-British strikes. (IRAQ)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Any censure deal in the Senate in lieu of
impeachment is unlikely to include an admission by President Bill
Clinton that he committed perjury, Vice President Al Gore says.
With the nation's second presidential impeachment trial looming
next month, key senators acknowledged Wednesday that bipartisan
talks were under way on how to decide the president's fate. Gore,
in comments to CNN on Wednesday, made clear that the president was
unlikely to admit to lying under oath as part of any censure deal
that would avoid his conviction in the Senate and removal from
office. ``The president has said he did not lie under oath. He has
acknowledged that he gave statements that were less than helpful to
his interrogators, and he said that was misleading,'' Gore said.
``But that is a very different proposition.''
(US-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT)
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb forces backed by tanks and
artillery launched a strong attack Thursday on a rebel stronghold
in Kosovo, setting fire to houses and killing at least one person,
ethnic Albanian sources said. The Kosovo Information Center, close
to the province's ethnic Albanian leadership, said Serb police and
military were targeting six villages near Podujevo, 32 kilometers
(20 miles) north of the provincial capital, Pristina. Jorgen
Grunnet, a spokesman for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe which is trying to verify the Oct. 12
cease-fire accord, had no reports of casualties or further details.
Yugoslav authorities described the attack as a ``limited search
operation'' for suspects in Monday's killing of a Serb policeman in
the area, Grunnet said. Nevertheless, the operation marks a
significant setback to the already shaky cease-fire agreement which
ended the worst of the fighting here in October.
(YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   HOUSTON (AP) _ While the world waits for news of improving
health and the public debut of the only living octuplets and their
parents, the Nigerian community in Houston is ready to lend a hand.
At least 300 people have offered to assist in child-rearing when
Nkem Chukwu and father Iyke Louis Ubogi bring home their eight
newborns. ``Now we have the American family _ the African family _
the eight wonders of the world. It cannot be handled by one
family,'' said Chido Nwangwu, a prominent leader of the local
Nigerian community. ``It will take a village to baby-sit eight kids
in the middle of the night.'' All of the infants remained in
critical condition Thursday at Texas Children's Hospital. On
Wednesday, the eight babies received names. The couple said they
named the children in the tradition of the Igbo (EE-boh) tribe, a
major ethnic group in their native Nigeria. (US-OCTUPLETS)
</TEXT>
