w2097 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Kenya-Police     12-24 0301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kenya-Police </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Much-criticized Kenya police force pledges to improve
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ The much-criticized Kenya police has
pledged to improve its image as it turns 101.
	   ``We want to build a force that is friendly and accountable to
the public _ our employers,'' Police Commissioner Duncan Wachira
said in a New Year's statement issued Thursday.
	   ``Fighting crime can only succeed as a joint venture. Let us
face the new year 1999 with a single mind of fighting crime. Help
the police to help you.''
	   Wachira admitted 1998 has been a difficult one for the force
that celebrated its 100th anniversary this year.
	   Many off-duty officers have been implicated in robberies, either
through renting their service weapons to gangs or direct
participation.
	   Motorists complain of constant demands for bribes by police,
particularly at the end of the month.
	   Wachira said police officers who have engaged in unprofessional
activities have been dealt with according to the law, but there has
been no information on wide-ranging arrests or disciplinary action
against offenders.
	   During an anniversary commemoration, Kenyan religious leaders
prayed that the police force stop being brutal and corrupt and
commit itself to service for all.
	   Two senior police officials have apologized for police excesses
over the years and asked the public to forgive the many atrocities
committed by police, ranging from harassment and demanding bribes
to torture and extra-judicial killings.
	   ``As we welcome the dawn of the second century of police service
in Kenya, we look forward to an atmosphere where there is a free
flow of information between the police and members of the public.
This will do away with the suspicions that exist between us,''
Wachira said.
	   (gm/sl	   
</TEXT>
