<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Encroaching Christmas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Western-style Christmas making inroads in Orthodox, Muslim Eritrea
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo available
 &UR; By JULIA STEWART &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ A Christmas tree decked with glowing
lights dominates a traffic island on Asmara's main thoroughfare.
Another adorns the central post office where electronic Christmas
jingles play throughout the day.
	   Christmas cards, colored lights, Italian pannettone, baked ham
for sale in shops and a day off from work on Friday _ all signs
that a western version of Christmas is making inroads in this
half-Muslim, half Orthodox Christian capital of 400,000 in the Horn
of Africa.
	   Eritrea's Orthodox Christians traditionally celebrate the birth
of Christ quietly at home on Jan. 7. The exchange of gifts is rare.
	   And Muslims began fasting last week for the holy month of
Ramadan.
	   Those driving the observance of western-style Christmas on Dec.
25 are minority Roman Catholics and Protestants _ and the many
Eritreans who have returned from years of exile in western nations.
	   ``I lived in Piscataway, New Jersey for 11 years, so I'm used to
celebrating on the 25th,'' said Luz Yosief, an Eritrean who now
works for the U.N. Development Program.
	   Eritrea, which became Africa's newest nation in 1993, lies along
the Red Sea. For centuries, it has been a crossroads between Arabia
and Africa, Christianity and Islam, and for 50 years, it was a
colony under Italian control.
	   But whether Christmas is observed Dec. 25 or Jan. 7, this season
it is overshadowed by fears of war.
	   Some 200,000 Eritrean soldiers and young men and women have been
mobilized for the past seven months since the outbreak of fighting
in May sparked by a border dispute with Ethiopia, Eritrea's larger
neighbor to the south.
	   Troops and conscripts remain dug in along the 1,000-kilometer
(620-mile) border, awaiting news of a negotiated settlement.
	   But so far, peace initiatives by the United States and the
Organization of African Unity have proved fruitless.
	   Another 44,000 Eritreans expelled from Ethiopia have dribbled
back to homes and relatives throughout the country. Nearly every
Eritrean in Asmara tells of a deported relative or friend staying
at his house.
	   Eritrea's relations with its other neighbor, Muslim-ruled Sudan,
are tense with occasional reports off cross-border shelling.
	   Eden Zekarias is simply hoping that the true meaning of
Christmas will triumph, whether on Friday or in two weeks.
	   ``We need peace more than celebrations,'' said the 24-year-old.
	   (js/sl)	   
</TEXT>
