<SLUG> BC-Germany-DaimlerChrysler </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DaimlerChrysler reports sales up for 1998
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Sales at the newly merged automobile
giant DaimlerChrysler AG were 260 billion marks (dlrs 158 billion)
in 1998, a company spokesman said Thursday.
	   That is about 13 percent higher than combined 1997 of
Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler Corp., which were around 229.3 billion
marks.
	   On Sunday, DaimlerChrysler will release sales figures that
should reveal a ``qualitative trend'' for 1998, the spokesman said.
Further earnings details will be published at the Detroit Auto Show
during the first week of January.
	   Analysts expect DaimlerChrysler to post a net profit of between
10 billion and 11 billion marks (dlrs 6 billion to dlrs 6.7
billion) in 1998, after a combined 8.04 billion by the two separate
companies in 1997.
	   According to the German financial news agency VWD, which
obtained an advance copy of the Sunday release, DaimlerChrysler
said its total unit sales in 1998 were around 4.4 million cars, of
which its Mercedes-Benz and Smart models numbered 850,000.
	   Around 3 million of the total were Chrysler, Dodge, Plymouth and
Jeep models, while the company sold about 480,000 commercial
vehicles.
	   Chairmen Juergen Schrempp and Robert Eaton said in that release
that they expect ``the first substantial positive effects of the
merger in 1999,'' VWD reported.
	   ``The integration teams are on the right track,'' they said.
	   The company's total number of employees rose in 1998 by 13,000
to 434,000, with more than half working in Germany, and one third
in the United States.
