<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Christmas Curfew </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kinshasa lifts curfew for Christmas
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Government authorities have lifted a
five-month-old dusk-to-dawn curfew in Kinshasa for Christmas, a
senior official said Thursday.
	   ``There was rejoicing when the announcement was made,'' Cabinet
Director Abdoulaye Yerodia told reporters.
	   Military authorities ordered the curfew in August, when an army
of rebel fighters was approaching the outskirts of Congo's capital
and was threatening to topple President Laurent Kabila's
government.
	   The rebels have since been pushed back to eastern Congo, but the
curfew in Kinshasa has remained as a precaution infiltration.
	   The curfew was lifted specifically to allow Kinshasa's
influential Christian community to attend late night Christmas mass
celebrations on Thursday night and Friday.
	   There was no indication whether the curfew's suspension would
extend beyond Christmas.
	   The move came with a word of caution from Yerodia, who said the
city must keep a watchful eye out for suspicious activities.
	   ``I urge our compatriots to be extra vigilant so that the
festivities can go on, but with prudence and vigilance,'' he said.
	   Former government troops and their ethnic Tutsi allies staged a
massive revolt in early August and have since been waging a rebel
war against Kabila, whom they accuse of corruption, abuse of power
and nepotism.
	   (km/ids)
</TEXT>
