<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Miners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Union, government sign agreement on pension rules
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ The government and the Solidarity trade
union on Thursday signed an agreement promising to preserve early
retirement privileges for miners, who suspended an underground
protest a day earlier.
	   ``We suspended our protest for humanitarian reasons,'' said
Solidarity mining leader Andrzej Kaczkowski in reference to the
observance of Christmas, one of the holiest holidays in
predominantly Catholic Poland.
	   Under the agreement, the government promised to keep the early
retirement rule that allows miners and others employed in dangerous
conditions to retire, with full pension, after 25 years of work, no
matter their age.
	   The deal was signed by Solidarity leader Marian Krzaklewski and
Labor Minister Longin Komolowski in the presence of Prime Minister
Jerzy Buzek. A special bill including the early retirement rule is
to be adopted by parliament within six months.
	   It signified a victory for miners who protested changes in the
pension system that set the retirement age at 65 for men and 60 for
women to get a full pension. Some 50 mines of the southern
industrial region of Silesia took part in the underground protest
that began Dec. 10.
	   Kaczkowski, however, said union leaders would meet after
Christmas to decide if they should continue the protest then.
Miners voted Monday for a general strike at an unspecified date to
defend their early retirement privileges.
	   ``If the agreement is not satisfying, then nothing can be
excluded,'' Kaczkowski said.
	   The Solidarity-led government is working on restructuring the
bloated mining industry as part of Poland's shift from communism to
a market economy. The plan calls for reducing production from 137
million tons last year to 110 million tons in 2002, as well as
cutting jobs by more than 40 percent _ from 245,000 now to 138,000
in three years.
	   (ms-bp-tsc)
</TEXT>
