<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Viagra </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jordan approves Viagra as unions call for U.S. drug boycott
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOHN HALABY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan has approved the sale of the
anti-impotence drug, Viagra, an official said Thursday, a day after
two unions of pharmacists and doctors called for a boycott of U.S.
and British drugs to protest airstrikes on Iraq.
	   A Health Ministry official said the ministry has registered
Viagra, produced by New York-based Pfizer, as a scheduled drug.
	   However, the actual sale will be delayed until the ministry
receives further documentation from Pfizer on the side-effects of
Viagra. This is considered a formality.
	   The drug should be available within eight weeks, the official
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   After initial hesitation, three other Arab countries _ Bahrain,
Kuwait and the United Arab _ approved the sale of Viagra this year.
	   On Wednesday, the Jordanian Pharmacists Association and the
Jordan Medical Association called for a boycott of pharmaceutical
products from the United States and Britain.
	   The boycott is not legally binding and exempts those drugs for
which no substitute is available.
	   Because Viagra is unique, it will be exempt from the boycott,
Abdul Rahim Issa, the chairman of the Jordanian Pharmacists
Association, told The Associated Press.
	   Viagra has been much talked about in Jordan and quantities of
the little blue tablets have already been smuggled into the kingdom
and sold on the black market at high prices.
	   Mohammad Sabbagh, the managing director of Pfizer's local agent,
Sabbagh Drug Company, said Viagra will be sold only on medical
prescription for 36 Jordanian dinars (dlrs 51) for a pack of four
pills, which is similar to the international price.
