<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-University Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
University staff end strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Some 1,500 teachers and 3,000 administrative
workers at a Yemeni university ended a strike after authorities
agreed to give them a 50 percent salary hike, the weekly al-Sahwa
reported Thursday.
	   The San`a University employees in the capital San`a and its
several campuses across the country returned to work on Wednesday
after President Ali Abdullah Saleh asked officials to accept the
strikers' demand for a raise, the Arabic-language paper said.
	   Since the strike began on Dec. 8, some 70,000 students had been
left without classes.
	   The government had agreed to a 50 percent raise after a strike
in June also, but the university employees said the promise was
never fulfilled.
	   University teachers earn between dlrs 300 and dlrs 500 a month
in Yemen.
	   A special government committee had promised a monthly salary
raise of about 170,000 riyals (dlrs 128) in 1995, but that too
never came through.
