<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
stories also moved earlier today as separates.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Japan, South Korea, China. Some of these

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The number of new cars and trucks to roll off
Japanese assembly lines fell in November, an industry group said
Thursday, as recession at home and in neighboring Asian nations
continued to hurt demand.
	   The number of new vehicles built last month was 848,266, down
1.3 percent from the same time a year ago, the Japan Automobile
Manufacturers Association said.
	   The number has fallen or broken even for 13 of the last 14
months, the association said. It recorded its only rise of the year
in October.
	   While robust exports to the United States helped the number of
passenger cars built in November rise 5.6 percent, the number of
new trucks plunged by a quarter.
	   In total, Japanese carmakers have built 8.5 percent less cars
and trucks so far this year compared to the same 11-month period
the year before.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese carmaker Isuzu Motors Ltd. announced
Thursday it will slash 4,000 jobs and reduce interest-bearing debt
as part of a restructuring drive to shore up profitability.
	   Isuzu, an affiliate of U.S.-based General Motors Corp., said the
plan will help it achieve its goal of 710 billion yen (dlrs 6.1
billion) in domestic auto sales and a pretax profit of 10 billion
yen (dlrs 86 million) in fiscal 2000.
	   The announcement comes amid a wave of consolidation within
Japan's auto industry, which has been battered by flagging domestic
demand and Asia's financial crisis.
	   Isuzu, one of the world's leading truck-makers, said the job
reductions will be accomplished through attrition. It said it
hasn't set a time frame for the cuts.
	   The company said it aims to reduce its interest-bearing debt
worth 1 trillion yen (dlrs 8.6 billion) by around 300 billion yen
(dlrs 2.58 billion) by March 2000.
	   Isuzu also said it will scale back its marketing subsidiaries to
30 companies from the current 68 by March 2001.
	   General Motors, the world's biggest automaker, said last week it
will increase its stake in Isuzu to 49 percent from the current
37.5 percent
	   ___
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Ford Motor Co. said Thursday it has
sold part of its stake in South Korea's Kia Motors Corp.
	   ``A business opportunity presented itself and we took it,'' John
Spelich, a spokesman at Ford's headquarters in Dearborn, Mich.
	   Spelich said Ford sold a 9-percent stake in Kia early this week
but still controls 8 percent in the Korean carmaker through Mazda
Motor Corp. of Japan. Ford is Mazda's largest shareholder.
	   Spelich declined to reveal the buyer and price of the sale.
	   The sale came after Ford had failed to take over Kia in an
international auction in October. South Korea's Hyundai Motor Co.
won the bid to acquire Kia and its commercial vehicle arm, Asia
Motors Co.
	   Officials at Hyundai and Kia declined to comment on the sale.
	   ___
	   SHANGHAI, China (AP) _ A dlrs 1 trillion infrastructure spending
plan to stimulate China's economy won't result in troubled banks
being saddled with more bad debt, a top regulator said Thursday.
	   The Finance Ministry will supply most of the money itself and
monitor spending closely to minimize unproductive outlays, said Wu
Xiaoling, head of the Shanghai branch of the Chinese central bank.
	   The three-year spending plan for new highways, bridges and other
projects is meant to boost a slowing economy. At 7.5 percent to 8
percent this year, growth is robust for Asia but not enough to
create jobs for millions of workers laid off in reforms of
state-owned industry.
	   The government also has tried to spur the economy by easing
lending restrictions on state banks, leading to fears that would
increase uncollectible loans.
	   Wu insisted regulators were watching to make sure that didn't
happen and said only about 1 percent of spending on the
infrastructure program was expected to wind up in unproductive
assets.
	   Wu was named head of the Shanghai branch of the People's Bank of
China last month in a restructuring meant to create a regulatory
agency modeled on the U.S. Federal Reserve System.
	   She said the government was gradually reducing bad assets by
injecting capital into the banking system.
	   Uncollectible bank debts or loans on which payments are
temporarily suspended are equal to 25 percent of bank assets
nationwide, Wu said. In Shanghai, she said, that figure stands at
about 10 percent. 	   
</TEXT>
