<SLUG> BC-Angola-Fighting,0379 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Angolan rebels launch nighttime attack on central highland city
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CASIMIRO SIONA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUANDA, Angola (AP) _ Despite a U.N. call for peace in Angola,
UNITA rebels launched an intensive attack Thursday on a central
highland city.
	   Rebel forces lobbed artillery shells through the night into
Kuito, some 500 kilometers (300 miles) southeast of the capital
Luanda, the private Radio Eclesia reported.
	   A local state television employee, who was not identified, was
wounded in the 10-hour attack that began at midnight, the radio
said.
	   When the attack died down, Kuito's 100,000 poeople _ swollen by
people fleeing battles in the surrounding rural highlands _ emerged
to stock up on provisions and water, Radio Eclesia reported.
	   There were no reports Thursday of clashes in the neighboring
Huambo province, where fighting has also flared this month,
undermining a 1994 peace agreement brokered by the United Nations.
	   The U.N. Security Council on Wednesday blamed UNITA for quashing
the 1994 accord, and demanded an end to the clashes that have
brought months of simmering hostility to the surface.
	   In Lisbon, a UNITA spokesman on Thursday accused the United
Nations of bias for failing to denounce government violations of
the peace agreement.
	   ``When the government shelled Andulo and Bailundo, the Security
Council said nothing,'' Carlos Morgado said by phone, referring to
an army attack three weeks ago on UNITA's two central highland
strongholds.
	   Once the rebels, equipped with unforeseen fire power, had
repelled the army from Andulo and Bailundo, they launched a broader
offensive throughout the central highlands.
	   The government has also criticized the United Nations for
failing to guarantee UNITA's compliance with the 1994 agreement,
the latest attempt to end the civil war that broke out after
independence from Portugal in 1975.
	   The pact required UNITA to disband a 70,000-strong guerrilla
army, and hand over control of almost half the country to the
government.
	   UNITA _ the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
_ has an estimated 30,000 guerrilla soldiers hiding in the vast
southwest African nation. The government has 100,000 troops.
</TEXT>
