<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Austria-Border </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Afgan, Iraqi cititzens stopped at border
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) _ Austrian border police stopped a group of
40 illegal aliens trying to cross into the country from Slovakia on
Thursday, media reported.
	   The 12 Afghans and 28 Iraqis caught on the border early Thursday
near the town of Kittsee, 40 kilometers (25 miles) southeast of
Vienna, have all applied for asylum in Austria, the Austria Press
Agency said.
	   The group is reported the largest to date to be caught on
Austria's long, open border shared with Slovakia and Hungary.
	   Since Austria dropped all border controls with European Union
neighbors last April, it is under increased pressure to block
illegal immigration from formerly communist countries to the east.
	   Germany, the destination for many would-be asylum seekers and
economic immigrants, has expressed particular concern about the
influx from the east and urged neighbors to tighten their borders
with non-EU nations.
	   (apa/me) 	   
</TEXT>
