 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Jordan, Kuwait. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordanian weavers have written to the
govement to complain about the competition they are facing from
Syrian and Southeast Asian goods, official said Thursday.
	   Protest Memorandum presented to the Ministry of Industry and
Trade by
	   In a protest letter to the Industry Ministry, the General
Association of Owners of Weaving Industries requested government
help in rectifying trade imbalances.
	   The association said Syrian products pose major competition to
the kingdom's 1,000 weaving industries, which have a total capital
of over 100 million Jordanian dinar (dlrs 140 million) and employ
more than 30,000 workers, the letter said.
	   It complained of widespread smuggling of goods and clothing from
Syria and the importation of cheap southeast Asian goods.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Share prices and turnover sharply dropped
in the Amman stock exchange this week, a market report said
Thursday.
	   Brokers attributed the sluggish activity to political
uncertainty in the region, includig the U.S.-British airstrikes on
Iraq, and the deadlocked Midesat peace process.
	   The market report, reflecting activity for five business days
ending Wednesday, said the 60 major companies' general share prices
index declined by 1.87 percent to 166.54 points.
	   Shares of industrial firms slipped by 3.25 percent, commercial
banks by 1.51 percent and services sector by 1.06 percent.
Insurance sector, however, nudged slightly up by 0.14 percent.
	   Turnover sharply declined by 76.3 percent to 5 million Jordanian
dinars (dlrs 7 million), the report said.
	   It said stocks of 105 firms were traded during the week.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The price index of the Kuwait Stock Exchange
closed at 1,645.7 points at the end of the trading week, up by 16.3
points, or 1 percent, from last week, the National Investments Co.
said Thursday.
	   In a weekly report about the exchange, the company said trading
was ``quiet'' but was expected to pick up next week with investment
companies wanting to close their portfolios higher at the end of
the year.
	   Some 318.21 million shares changed hands this week, up 0.73
percent from the previous one, the National Investments Co. said.
The value of these stocks rose 7.33 percent to 56.7 million dinars
(dlrs 187.74 million).
	   Of the 78 companies listed on the exchange, 71 were traded, with
31 closing higher, 20 closing lower, and the rest unchanged.
 &UR; buros-vj
</TEXT>
