<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-EU Taxes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French Finance Minister skeptical about EU tax alignment
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn
reiterated his government's skepticism Thursday about the merits of
Europe-wide tax harmonization.
	   ``I don't know if it's impossible, but I wonder above all if
it's really desirable'' to achieve a general harmonization of tax
and social security charges in Europe in the medium term,
Strauss-Kahn said in an interview with daily newspaper Les Echos.
	   Strauss-Kahn said the principle of giving E.U. states freedom in
setting their own fiscal policy remained important, particularly
given the different quality of social services they provide.
	   However, he said the E.U. should go ahead with harmonization in
the areas of corporate and capital gains taxation and hoped it
would happen by mid-1999.
	   ``Harmonization should take place wherever (fiscal) differences
are likely to create unfair tax competition,'' he said. ``That's
why minor differences in value-added-tax rates, for example, don't
need to be harmonized.''
	   Strauss-Kahn was echoing the conclusion reached by E.U. leaders
earlier this month to delay decisions on the controversial issue of
tax-rate alignment until December 1999.
	   The leaders had agreed that tax coordination does not have to
mean imposing uniform rates across the 15-nation bloc, but they
said they wanted to agree on E.U. rules for taxation of savings,
interest and royalties by next December.
	   The Finance Ministry issued broad guidelines Wednesday for
French government finances for the years 2000 to 2002, predicting a
decline in the level of tax and social security charges.
	   Strauss-Kahn said the decrease would have to be phased in
slowly, depending on how fast the economy grows.
	   The government also aims to trim the public deficit from 2.3
percent of gross domestic product to between 0.8 and 1.2 percent in
1999.
	   (dj-ly-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
