w2215 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Afghanistan-BinLaden     12-24 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Bin Laden,0570 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bin Laden says he's innocent of U.S. Embassy bombings
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ In his first public denial of
involvement in the U.S. Embassy bombings in Africa, Osama bin Laden
said he is innocent but not sorry the attacks happened, a Pakistani
news agency reported Thursday.
	   The Saudi millionaire has been living in exile in Afghanistan,
and the Taliban religious army, which rules most of the country,
has until now refused to let him make public statements.
	   The United States has accused bin Laden of masterminding the
August embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania that killed 224
people. A U.S. court has indicted bin Laden and Washington has
demanded he be extradited.
	   ``I was not involved in the bomb blasts ... but I don't regret
what happened there,'' the Taliban quoted bin Laden as saying, the
independent News Network International reported Thursday.
	   The Taliban said bin Laden made the comment to a reporter from
the Afghan news agency Bakhtar and a Pakistani journalist, the news
agency reported.
	   There was no immediate Taliban comment Thursday about the NNI
report.
	   The Taliban, which rules roughly 90 percent of Afghanistan, has
refused to hand over bin Laden, saying he is an honored guest and
will be protected in keeping with Afghan tradition.
	   The Taliban's Supreme Court held an inquiry last month into U.S.
charges that bin Laden led an international terrorist organization
targeting American interests worldwide.
	   The inquiry ended after nearly a month, exonerating bin Laden
and berating the United States for failing to provide evidence of
his guilt.
	   But the Taliban promised that no one, including bin Laden, would
use Afghan territory as a base of terrorist activity.
	   They also said that bin Laden gave a written guarantee to the
Taliban's supreme leader Mullah Mohammed Omar that he would not
participate in any terrorist activity while in Afghanistan.
	   NNI quoted bin Laden as saying ``I am leading my life under the
rules and regulations of Mullah Omar.''
	   The Taliban said that means that bin Laden is not training,
financing or encouraging terrorist activity from his base in
southern Afghanistan.
	   Bin Laden's campaign against the United States is aimed at
forcing Washington to withdraw troops from Saudi Arabia, home to
Islam's two holiest sites, Medina and Mecca. Bin Laden also has
criticized Saudi Arabia for allowing the troops there and has vowed
to see the monarchy in his homeland overthrown.
	   The United States also suspects bin Laden of financing the June
1996 bombing of Khobar Towers, a U.S. military apartment complex in
the Saudi Arabian city of Dhahran. Nineteen U.S. servicemen were
killed and about 500 people were injured in the blast.
	   The Saudi government expelled bin Laden nearly a decade ago. He
sought asylum in Sudan before relocating to Afghanistan along with
an estimated 300 followers.
	   In August, the United States fired several missiles at what the
U.S. administration believed were bin Laden's camps for training
terrorists. The Taliban said the 26 people killed were religious
students and not terrorists-in-training.
	   In his interview, bin Laden also praised the Taliban's hard-line
version of Islamic law, which bans women from work, girls from
school and forces everyone to pray five times a day.
</TEXT>
