<DATE_TIME> 12/24/1998 10:07:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2216 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Economy 3rdLd-Writethru   12-24 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian parliament gives initial approval to 1999 budget
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with parliament approving budget on first
reading, new Primakov's quotes, trims to delete outdated material. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos MOSB101-103. &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Parliament's lower house gave quick, initial
approval to an austere budget for 1999 after Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov threatened to resign if the document was rejected.
	   The Communist-dominated legislature, which generally backs
Primakov's government, voted 303-65 to approve the 1999 budget
after its first reading.
	   Primakov rallied lawmakers' support in an emotional speech
before the vote, saying that Russia desperately needs the budget to
deal with the worst economic crisis since the Soviet collapse.
	   ``The question is whether we're ready to undertake
responsibility for overcoming the crisis or will again sink in
debates, mutual recriminations and half-steps,'' Primakov said.
	   The State Duma must still vote several more times on the budget
in coming days, and then send it to the upper house. But the budget
appeared likely to pass with far less commotion than in previous
years, when the process dragged on for months.
	   Russia's coffers are so bare that the entire 1999 budget calls
for government spending of just 575 billion rubles (dlrs 29
billion) and revenues of only 474 billion rubles (dlrs 24 billion).
	   By comparison, the United States government collects and spends
more than dlrs 30 billion in an average week.
	   Before heading into parliament, Primakov met with President
Boris Yeltsin in the Kremlin to discuss the budget, which is
designed to help stabilize an economy that's been contracting
rapidly since the summer.
	   ``If the budget isn't approved, we will not stay on our posts,''
Primakov said.
	   ``The budget must be very severe, we can't lie to anyone,'' he
told Yeltsin, who nodded in agreement.
	   Yeltsin, who has been sidelined by a string of illnesses, has
said little about the country's economic turmoil, leaving Primakov
to deal with the crisis.
	   ``We must gradually arrange things to get rid of foreign (aid)
injections,'' Yeltsin told Primakov.
	   Primakov then told parliament's lower house that a lean budget
was essential for getting new loans from the International Monetary
Fund and other lenders. Russia badly needs the aid to help pay off
its huge debts.
	   ``Quickly passing the budget will strengthen our stance in the
talks with international financial organizations,'' Primakov said.
	   Despite their support for Primakov, some lawmakers criticized
the budget as being too dependent on foreign help.
	   Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov acknowledged that the budget
relies on dlrs 7.2 billion in foreign loans that may not come.
	   Also, the budget earmarks only dlrs 9.5 billion to pay off
Russia's foreign debt, which will total dlrs 17.5 billion next
year. The budget planners are seeking to reschedule the remaining
debts.
	   The draft budget is based on the average ruble rate of 21.5 to
the dollar, and forecasts inflation of 30 percent next year.
	   Alexander Zhukov, the chairman of the Duma's budget committee,
dismissed both targets as overly optimistic now that the ruble has
fallen below 20 rubles to the dollar and inflation this year is
expected to top 70 percent.
	   But Zhukov asked the Duma to approve the plan anyway.
	   ``The budget rejection or a significant delay in its passage
would bring our country to such situation that the economic crisis
of August and September would seem a time of economic prosperity,''
he said.
	   The previous government devalued the ruble and defaulted on some
of its domestic debts in August, triggering Russia's worst economic
crisis since the Soviet collapse and prompting foreign lenders to
freeze further loans.
	   The budget calls for government spending of 575 billion rubles
(dlrs 29 billion) and revenues of just 474 billion rubles (dlrs 24
billion).
	   By comparison, the United States government collects and spends
more than dlrs 30 billion every week on average.
	   (pvs/vi/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Russia-Economy, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
