r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-China     12-24 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-China,0343 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India says talk of strategic triangle premature
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ASHOK SHARMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ It's too early to talk of an
India-Russia-China strategic triangle since New Delhi's relations
with Bejing are still strained, India's new foreign minister said
Thursday.
	   Reviewing India's foreign policy challenges in 1998, Foreign
Minister Jaswant Singh said India was still trying to normalize
relations with China. India set off five nuclear tests in May,
saying it needed a nuclear defense against threats posed by
neighboring China and Pakistan.
	   Any ``strategic relationship with China is a consequence of
improvement of relations,'' Singh said, adding both sides were
still working out ``concerns.''
	   Last week, China rejected the idea of a ``strategic triangle''
that Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov promoted during his
visit to New Delhi. Foreign affairs experts in all three countries
have proposed such an alliance to check U.S. domination after the
disintegration of the Soviet Union.
	   Primakov said he had not formally proposed the alliance to
Indian leaders.
	   Singh said India would not roll back the nuclear program that
angered China, but noted Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee told
the U.N. General Assembly earlier this year he wanted an
international test ban treaty by September.
	   Singh, who took office this month, strongly rejected a
reporter's suggestion that India, one of the poorest countries in
the world, had spent billions of dollars on nuclear weaponry at the
cost of social development.
	   India's nuclear tests also angered the United States, which
urged New Delhi to retreat and imposed economic sanctions. Singh
has led the Indian team in the ongoing talks with U.S. Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott.
	   Singh said differences remained on issues including the test ban
treaty, production of materials needed to make nuclear weapons and
controls on exporting such material. More talks are expected later
this month in New Delhi.
</TEXT>
