<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Octuplets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In troubled Nigeria, eight reasons to smile
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ThisDay in 3rd graf is correct. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Amid otherwise bleak news of fuel
shortages and labor tumult, Nigerians this week had eight reasons
to smile.
	   Newspapers in the commercial capital of Lagos for days have been
carrying stories on the birth of the world's first living octuplets
to a Nigerian couple living in the United States.
	   Squeezed in between news stories on protests and strikes, a
headline earlier this week in Nigeria's popular ThisDay newspaper
modestly announced the birth of the eight new compatriots.
	   ``Nigerian woman sets multiple birth record,'' the paper's front
page headline declared.
	   The influential Lagos Guardian on Thursday wrote of efforts by
Nigeria's ambassador to the United States and the Nigerian
community in Texas to help the young parents.
	   Although an ocean away, Nigerians took pride in the birth of the
world's first living octuplets. Born to Nkem Chukwu and Iyke Louis
Udobi, the infants were named along the traditional lines of their
tribal Ibo ethnic heritage from southeastern Nigeria.
	   ``To read about this reminds you of how precious life is,'' said
Peter Duvbiama as he perused a copy of the daily Vanguard, which
also carried news of the record-breaking brood.
	   For most Nigerians, however, news of the remarkable
multiple-birth was a short-lived diversion from daily trials of
life in Africa's most populous and often troubled nation.
	   On Thursday, a typical day, labor groups threatened strike
action, students groups accused the government of corruption and
cars lined up in impossibly long queues for gasoline _ oil-rich
Nigeria faces chronic fuel shortages.
	   ``We're happy for the couple, but we've got problems enough
here,'' said Henry Nwoko, while waiting in line to fill his taxi
with increasingly scarce gasoline.
	   (str/ids)
</TEXT>
