<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Missiles-UN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cypriot president to visit Greece for talks on missile deployment
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; BY ALEX EFTY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides is to
fly to Athens on Monday for talks on the controversial deployment
of Russian missiles in Cyprus, the government said Thursday.
	   The Cypriot National Council, a body consisting of the leaders
of all the main parties, asked the president to discuss the
deployment with the Greek government after studying Tuesday's U.N.
Security Council resolutions on Cyprus, an official statement said.
	   The Security Council called for the reduction of weapons and
troops in Cyprus and the resumption of talks for the reunification
of the island. Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey
invaded after a short-lived coup by supporters of union with
Greece.
	   The Clerides' government welcomed the U.N. resolutions as
expressing a new impetus toward solving the Cyprus problem. But two
National Council members _ centrist Spyros Kyporianou and socialist
Vassos Lyssarides _ criticized the resolutions as seeking to
prevent the missiles' deployment, expected in the new year.
	   Turkey has warned it will take military action to stop the
anti-aircraft missiles from being deployed in Cyprus. Athens, which
is obliged by treaty to support Cyprus in the event of war, has
indicated that Cyprus should install the missiles on the Greek
island of Crete.
	   The United States and the European Union, to which Greece
belongs, have asked Cyprus to cancel the deployment.
 &UR; ae-jbm-sf
</TEXT>
