<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Fuel Prices </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Unions, students demand reduction in Nigerian fuel prices
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigerian trade unions teamed up Thursday
with student activists to call on the country's military government
to cut gasoline prices or ``face the wrath of workers.''
	   Union members are threatening massive strikes, while the student
groups say they will disrupt next year's world youth soccer
championships in Nigeria.
	   A statement by the Nigeria Labor Congress, issued at the end of
an emergency meeting in Lagos on Wednesday, said unions ``will not
be held responsible for any actions that may be taken by the 29
industrial unions affiliated to the NLC if the government fails to
reverse the price increase of petroleum products by next Jan. 4.''
	   Last Monday, Nigeria's military government announced a sharp
increase in gasoline prices, lifting them from about 12 cents per
liter to almost 30 cents.
	   Prices for diesel and kerosene also went up as the government
deregulated petroleum products in an effort to cut through recent
chronic fuel shortages in the country.
	   The labor congress says the price increase will wipe out gains
from a recent wage increase for government workers and render
irrelevant the government's poverty alleviation programs.
	   The increase in official prices at the pump have pushed up fares
on public transport in Nigeria by at least 200 percent.
	   (str/apdj/ids)
</TEXT>
