<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria-Violence </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ambush kills eight soldiers, wounds 15
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ Muslim militants ambushed an army patrol
in a mountainous region west of Algiers, killing eight soldiers,
wounding 15 and fleeing with a load of weapons, independent
newspapers reported Thursday.
	   The attack overnight Monday came during the holy month of
Ramadan, when militant activity usually intensifies in a nearly
7-year-old insurgency that has left 75,000 people dead.
	   The militants fired on two military vehicles on patrol in the
Zaccar Mountains near the town of Miliana, 145 kms (90 miles) west
of the capital, reported the newspapers Liberte and El Watan.
	   The attackers made off with six Kalashnikov submachine guns, 32
ammunition clips, as well as military uniforms, Liberte said.
	   Security forces scoured the area on Tuesday, looking for the
militants, said a municipal employee in the Miliana, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
	   The insurgency began after the military-backed government
scrapped a January 1992 parliamentary runoff the Islamic Salvation
Front was expected to win. The Front had promised to fight high
unemployment and corruption in this petroleum-rich nation.
	   (cb-parf)
</TEXT>
