<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Missiles-UN,0265 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cypriot president to visit Greece for talks on missile deployment
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; BY ALEX EFTY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ The Cypriot president will travel to
Athens on Monday for talks on the controversial deployment of
Russian missiles in Cyprus, the government said Thursday.
	   The Cypriot National Council, which includes the leaders of all
the main parties, asked the president to discuss the deployment
with the Greek government following U.N. resolutions on Cyprus that
were passed Tuesday, an official statement said.
	   The Security Council urged the reduction of weapons and troops
in Cyprus and the resumption of talks for the reunification of the
island. Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey invaded
after a short-lived coup by supporters of union with Greece.
	   The government of Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides welcomed
the U.N. resolutions as expressing a new impetus toward solving the
Cyprus problem. But two National Council members _ centrist Spyros
Kyporianou and socialist Vassos Lyssarides _ criticized the
resolutions as seeking to prevent the missiles' deployment,
expected in the new year.
	   Turkey has warned it will take military action to stop the
anti-aircraft missiles from being deployed in Cyprus. Athens, which
is obliged by treaty to support Cyprus in the event of war, has
indicated that Cyprus should install the missiles on the Greek
island of Crete.
	   The United States and the European Union, to which Greece
belongs, have asked Cyprus to cancel the deployment.
</TEXT>
