<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Balloon Quest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss say Chinese pique over Branson team blocks other balloonists
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CHATEAU D'OEX, Switzerland (AP) _ Swiss-based challengers to be
the first balloonists to fly nonstop around the world said Thursday
they have to postpone their attempt because of Chinese irritation
over the U.S.-British-Swedish team.
	   ``The Chinese have made it known to Bertrand Piccard that they
demand the postponement of Breitling Orbiter 3 and other
balloons,'' said a statement.
	   It said the Chinese decision was a ``consequence of the attitude
of the team of Richard Branson, which did not respect the
overflight conditions of China.''
	   British tycoon Branson, American millionaire Steve Fossett and
Per Lindstrand of Sweden picked up speed over the Pacific Wednesday
following their passage across China.
	   The statement did not go into detail about what actions had
provoked the Chinese, but Bejing originally gave the balloonists
permission to cross China below 26 degrees north latitude.
	   The trio, however, drifted further north Monday. After
diplomatic communications between Britain and China, the
balloonists were allowed to continue flying as long as they left
China as quickly as possible.
	   The Breitling Orbiter statement quoted a fax from the Chinese
government as saying, ``In view of the behavior of the Virgin
Global Challenger, the competent Chinese authorities find it
necessary to re-examine your overflight and ask you to postpone the
departure of the balloon.''
	   It said Piccard had to accept the Chinese decision.
	   ``I personally went to China to negotiate our passage and those
of the other competitors,'' Piccard said in the statement. ``Today,
the Chinese have the impression that they were abused because the
conditions they set weren't respected by one of the teams.''
	   Piccard and partner Brian Jones of Britain had previously said
they might take off as soon as Sunday.
	   It would be Piccard's third attempt to become the first person
to pilot a balloon around the world nonstop. Three other teams are
in the sweepstakes.
	   Piccard-Jones would take off from Chateau d'Oex, a Swiss Alpine
resort. Branson-Fossett began Dec. 18 from Morocco. The other
takeoff points are Alice Springs, Australia; Chicago; and
Albuquerque, N.M.
 &UR; (acw-agh)
</TEXT>
