<SLUG> BC-Uzbekistan-Military </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Uzbek president announces military to be slimmed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TASHKENT, Uzbekistan (AP) _ Uzbek President Islam Karimov told
parliament on Thursday that the country's armed forces would be
trimmed.
	   The size of the army has never been made public, but unofficial
estimates put its size at 600,000.
	   ``Our armed forces today are extremely necessary, but too
swollen for the economy of the young republic,'' Karimov told
parliament.
	   ``The army must be smaller and more professional. A commission
will decide to what extent the army should be reduced.''
	   Uzbekistan, a former Soviet republic of 23.5 million, borders on
two strife-torn countries: Afghanistan and Tajikistan. Karimov, who
has repeatedly warned of a rise in Islamic extremism in Central
Asia, said Uzbekistan was primarily interested in peace and
stability in its neighbors, as well as within its own borders.
	   (str/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
