r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-FarRight     12-24 0278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Far Right </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Le Pen seeks court order against rebels
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Seeking a new form of punishment against the rebels
he's kicked out of his party, National Front leader Jean-Marie Le
Pen asked a court Thursday to ban them from using the party name or
emblem.
	   Le Pen's complaint targeted nine people _ chief among them Bruno
Megret, the party's former No. 2 man who is leading the rebellion.
	   On Wednesday, Le Pen formally excluded Megret and six others
from the extreme-right party.
	   The bitter feud between Le Pen and Megret has split the party in
two. Megret plans to form his own slate for European Parliament
elections next June, while Le Pen plans to lead the Front's ticket.
	   A hearing on Le Pen's complaint is scheduled for Jan. 12, less
than two weeks before a planned party congress called by Megret. It
was Megret's call for the congress that led a furious Le Pen to
suspend him earlier this month.
	   Le Pen saw the call for a congress as a ploy to oust him, a
claim Megret never directly denied. A Le Pen loyalist, Samuel
Marechal, reiterated those accusations on Thursday.
	   ``The methods of Mr. Megret and his friends are illegal and
violate party statutes,'' Marechal said in a telephone interview.
	   ``It comes from bad faith ... (They are trying) to brainwash
people and spread disinformation,'' Marechal told The Associated
Press.
	   The National Front, which typically wins 15 percent of the
national vote, advocates sending home France's millions of
immigrants and reserving jobs and welfare for French-born citizens.
It is widely accused of racism and anti-Semitism.
	   (ly-jn)
</TEXT>
