<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bolivia-Killings,0239 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bolivian police detain killers of a Colombian nun and priest
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) _ Bolivian police have arrested a teen-ager
who confessed to killing a Roman Catholic nun and priest who were
delivering Christmas gifts and food to a poor highland village,
officials said Thursday. They were still searching for three
accomplices.
	   A 16-year-old youth in custody confessed to shooting Father
Alvaro Lopez, 39, and Sister Maria Celina Posada, 37, both of
Colombia. They were killed Monday evening in Quiquibey, a tropical
region, 450 miles (700 kilometers) north of the capital, La Paz.
	   A third victim was in stable condition.
	   The teen-ager says he and his friends decided to ambush the
priest since he had complained of the youths' drunken rampage
through their small village.
	   Lopez and Celina, who worked with poor farmers and loggers, were
taking Christmas presents and food to a nearby village when they
were ambushed.
	   The killers stole the religious workers' vehicle and abandoned
it after getting into an accident. The suspects then fled into the
forests that surround Quiquibey.
	   A mob tried to lynch the 16-year-old after he was caught, but
police protected him. Area residents were also helping police in
the search for the three suspects still at large.
	   Father Lopez and Sister Posada were buried Wednesday in the
nearby village of Reyes.
</TEXT>
