<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Christmas in Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Christmas in Iraq amid deprivation, sorrow
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Available
 &UR; By LOUIS MEIXLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ A golden star of Bethlehem twinkles from
atop Yousif Habboush's Christmas tree and silver and blue streamers
hang from his dining room chandelier, but once again there will be
no turkey on the holiday table.
	   In a nearby poorer Baghdad neighborhood, Faris Boutros Mehdi
shops for presents to put beneath his small, bare, plastic
Christmas tree. A bottle of perfume for his girlfriend costs about
25,000 dinars (dlrs 14), about half of his monthly salary.
	   The rich and poor of Iraq's 500,000-member Christian community
are struggling to celebrate the season of peace on earth in a
society devastated by eight years of U.N. sanctions.
	   Recent airstrikes have only increased the misery.
	   ``People are celebrating Christmas Day, but inside they are not
joyful,'' said Matti Shaba Matoka, the Syrian Catholic archbishop
of Baghdad. ``We hope that this year we will have a Christmas of
peace.''
	   This year, Matoka will again urge his flock to stay in Iraq and
preserve a community that traces its roots to the first century,
when St. Thomas converted the initial Christians.
	   He is fighting an uphill battle.
	   About one-third of Iraq's Christians have left the country since
sanctions were imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
Priests say there are some traditionally Christian villages in
mostly Kurdish areas of the north that are virtually abandoned.
	   Although Muslims have also fled, many Christians have relatives
in the West from earlier migrations and have found it easier to
leave.
	   ``If everybody leaves, who will remain?'' Matoka asked. On one
side of his office wall was a picture of Matoka greeting Pope John
Paul II. On the opposite wall was a picture of him meeting with
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, who wore an olive green military
uniform.
	   Iraq is officially a secular state, and most Christians say they
face little discrimination. Christians, however, make up only about
5 percent of Iraq's 22 million people and many feel alienated
within the overwhelmingly Muslim society.
	   ``There are some people who are narrow-minded but generally
no,'' Mehdi said when asked about discrimination.
	   In the streets of Baghdad there are Christmas decorations in
many stores and restaurants. In one neighborhood, a man in the
traditional Santa suit _ Baba Noel in Arabic _ danced in one of the
main streets.
	   Most Iraqi Christians are members of the Chaldean and Nestorian
sects, but there are also Syrian Catholics and Armenian Orthodox.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz _ a Chaldean _ is one of
several prominent Christians in the government, army and the
security forces.
	   For the Habboush family, which lives in a luxurious two-story
white villa, there is much to be thankful for this year.
	   Although the four children huddled in their parent's bedroom for
four nights as U.S. missiles slammed into the city, no one was
hurt.
	   And although sanctions have crippled the economy, Habboush owned
a construction company before the war and has been able to slowly
sell off his equipment to help make ends meet.
	   ``We are living at 25 percent of our earlier standard of
living,'' he said. ``I don't want it to fall much more.''
	   His traditional Christmas lunch _ the main holiday meal in Iraq
_ will consist of lamb soup, fish and chicken.
	   Missing will be the turkey, which can cost up to a month's
salary for an average family and that is only when it can be found.
	   Christmas will be far more austere for Mehdi, a 27-year-old lab
technician who helps support his mother, his sick father and his
three siblings.
	   His holiday meal will consist of pacha _ lamb stomach stuffed
with rice and meat topped with the lamb's head _ and date pastries.
	   ``We try our best to save money for the whole year for
Christmas,'' said Mehdi, who earns about 50,000 dinar (dlrs 28) a
month.
	   He said his salary is enough to help pay for the Christmas meal
``but I'm in really big trouble with my girlfriend.''
	   He said he doesn't have enough money for the bottle of perfume
he wants to buy for her and may have to settle for cheap imitation
perfume that sells on the streets of Baghdad for about 5,000 dinar
(about dlrs 3).
	   Above his black steel-framed bed with a sagging mattress is a
map of the United States with a picture of the Lebanese singer
Fairouz.
	   ``This is where I dream to go,'' he said smacking his hand
against the map.
 &UR; lm-emf-sf
</TEXT>
