<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Belarus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Belarus' Lukashenko arrives for meeting with Yeltsin
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko vowed
Thursday to continue pressing for a closer union between his
country and Russia, beginning in a meeting Friday with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin.
	   Lukashenko arrived in Moscow on Thursday evening. He said the
two countries were ready to sign two treaties and an agreement, and
that he was prepared to sign a political declaration setting out
the two partners' responsibilities in the proposed union.
	   The authoritarian Belarusian leader, openly nostalgic for the
Soviet Union, has urged closer political integration and dual
citizenship since Russia and Belarus signed a union treaty in 1996.
The move strengthened ties, but stopped well short of merging the
two nations.
	   Russia has been less enthusiastic. The nation of nearly 150
million people has a multitude of economic and social problems,
while Belarus, with about 10 million people, is even poorer.
	   Belarus has been suffering from food shortages, and has
introduced food rationing in some regions.
	   Still, Russia views Belarus as an important ally. Both countries
are adamantly opposed to NATO's expansion into East Europe.
	   Lukashenko promised Thursday that he would visit Moscow
frequently ``because the conversation taking place in the Kremlin
will define the future of two countries and fraternal peoples,''
the Interfax news agency reported.
	   During a trip to Moscow last week, Lukashenko pushed for
establishing a single currency _ a tacit way of asking for Russian
subsidies. The cash-strapped Russian government hasn't given an
immediate answer.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
