<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nicaragua-Christmas-Mitch,0474 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Grim Christmas for survivors of Hurricane Mitch
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By FILADELFO ALEMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   POSOLTEGA, Nicaragua (AP) _ There are outward signs of Christmas
in Posoltega: A radio station has sent toys and the city says it
will swing donated pinatas loaded with candy from the poles of
refugee camps.
	   But there is little joy.
	   In the shadow of the Casitas volcano _ and in hundreds of other
towns across Central America _ Christmas comes too hard on the tail
of Hurricane Mitch.
	   ``What Christmas?'' asked Gregorio Sanchez, a 42-year-old farmer
and evangelical preacher who, along with his wife and five
children, lives among hundreds of other refugees in a black plastic
shelter with a dirt floor.
	   Two months ago Sanchez made a comparatively good living as a
farmer in this impoverished nation. On his 9 hectares (22 acres),
he grew crops and raised cows and pigs to sell in nearby towns.
	   Then Mitch came bringing furious rains.
	   On Oct. 30, mud thundered down the flanks of the volcano burying
the nearby villagers' land, their houses, their friends, their
relatives.
	   Many hundreds died at the volcano. Officials estimate the storm
killed about 3,000 people in Nicaragua and about 9,000 in the
region.
	   With many roads and bridges still cut, Honduran officials are
still reporting new deaths from starvation.
	   Sanchez's old village, called Rolando Rodriguez, is covered by a
gray expanse of dried mud, rocks and uprooted trees.
	   Wearing the stained shirt he wore when he fled, Sanchez gave an
eerie tour of the trampled world where he once lived.
	   ``Here was the school,'' he said, beside a rock twice his
height.
	   ``Here was the evangelical church. There was the house of Don
Felipe Diaz, who shut himself up in the house with his sons and
daughters, and they all died together when the mudslide destroyed
it.''
	   ``There was the bar of Adriana Munoz, who saved herself and her
daughters. Here was the children's dining hall. Last Christmas they
gave toys to the children. We don't know how many children died,''
he said.
	   From a hillside, Sanchez saw the avalanche, heard the deafening
roar. He raced to his house, rousted his family and ran back to the
hill, with other villagers running behind.
	   ``Like Lot's wife, I turned to look back and those who were
following me had disappeared. And to the east, where there had been
the fertile valley of Rolando Rodriguez, now there was nothing.''
	   The pall hanging over Christmas might have its deepest impact on
the children, who used to spend the holiday waiting for Santa to
deliver gifts.
	   Now many go to the highway, shoeless, dirty and semi-clothed to
beg coins from drivers.
	   ``This cannot be,'' Sanchez said. ``Our children are losing
their sense of shame.'' 	   
</TEXT>
