w2331 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-SierraLeone 1stLd-Writethru   12-24 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Sierra Leone, 1st Ld-Writethru,0319 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. concerned at intensified rebel attacks in Sierra Leone
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS two final grafs to UPDATE with government launching
assault near Freetown on Wednesday, capital quiet Thursday &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The U.N. Security Council has expressed
concern at intensified rebel attacks in Sierra Leone and urged all
countries to abide by an arms embargo against rebel forces and
neighboring Liberia.
	   ``The members of the council expressed how imperative it is that
the rebels put an end to their atrocities,'' the council said
Wednesday in a press statement read by Bahrain's U.N. Ambassador
Jassim Mohammed Buallay, the current council president.
	   The rebels are believed to have killed, maimed and raped
thousands of rural villagers in a revenge campaign to widen their
influence through fear.
	   Council members condemned the participation of foreign forces on
the rebel side and expressed ``serious concern at the large number
of armaments flowing into the hands of the rebels in an organized
manner.''
	   The council reaffirmed its support for the government of
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and for the Nigerian-led West African
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG.
	   Kabbah's government has been waging war against members of
Sierra Leone's ousted military junta and its rebel allies since
March, when ECOMOG troops drove Sierra Leone's military junta from
power to clear the way for Kabbah's return to power.
	   Kabbah had been ousted from power in a May 1997 coup.
	   In Sierra Leone, ECOMOG troops pounded the outskirts of the
capital, Freetown, with heavy artillery and air attacks Wednesday
amid fears of a rebel advance on the city. But the force later said
reports of the rebel attack were false.
	   The bombardment followed several days of fighting between ECOMOG
and rebels in towns surrounding Freetown. The capital was quiet
today.
</TEXT>
