<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 4th Ld-Writethru,0628 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethnic Albanians claim Serb forces launch attack on Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
stronghold &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with latest OSCE statement;
operation said over; EDITS to conform. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb forces backed by tanks and
artillery attacked a Kosovo rebel stronghold Thursday, burning
houses and killing at least one person, ethnic Albanian sources
said.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, close to the province's ethnic
Albanian leadership, said Serb police and military targeted six
villages near Podujevo, 30 kilometers (20 miles) north of the
provincial capital, Pristina, and had sealed off all roads to the
area.
	   Hysni Fazliu, a spokesman for the party of leading ethnic
Albanian politician Ibrahim Rugova, said rebels resisted the
attack. Kosovo is in southern Serbia, the main Yugoslav republic.
	   The violence threatens to revive the war between secessionist
ethnic Albanians and Serb security forces. From February to
October, 1,000 people were killed and 300,000 lost their homes.
	   Jorgen Grunnet, a spokesman for the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe, confirmed that shelling and machine-gun
fire in the area had killed one person.
	   Grunnet said a convoy of Yugoslav army vehicles, including
several Russian-built T-55 tanks, left bases in Pristina and
Podujevo early Thursday and swept through the area just west of
Podujevo.
	   He said Yugoslav authorities described the attack as a ``limited
search operation'' for suspects in Monday's killing of a Serb
policeman in the area.
	   The operation marks a significant setback to the already shaky
cease-fire agreement that ended the worst of the fighting. On
Wednesday, U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin warned of
the increasing violence.
	   ``A large-scale crackdown against the civilian population of
Kosovo would do nothing to improve the security situation and could
spark a cycle of violence that would seriously undermine the
cease-fire agreement,'' Rubin said in Washington.
	   The chief ethnic Albanian peace negotiator, Fehmi Agani, called
the Serb operation a ``very serious provocation'' and a ``a bold
challenge to NATO,'' which had threatened airstrikes in October to
halt the fighting.
	   According to the ethnic Albanian report, Serb tanks had entered
one of the villages, Lapastica, a stronghold of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, which is fighting for independence from Serbia.
	   The report said at least one ethnic Albanian villager was killed
and several houses were set ablaze. A later report by the ethnic
Albanian center said Serb snipers had taken up positions at
``strategic points'' in the area and were firing at civilians, who
were fleeing deeper into rebel territory.
	   There was no comment from Serb sources.
	   ``This offensive confirms our worst fears that the Serbian
regime planned to use the Christmas holidays to launch an action
aimed at ethnically cleansing the north of Kosovo,'' said Xemail
Mustafa, a spokesman for the province's ethnic Albanian leaders.
	   Mustafa urged foreign governments and international monitors of
Kosovo's two-month cease-fire to intervene with Yugoslav
authorities to halt the attacks.
	   On Wednesday, two top NATO officials warned both sides against
launching more attacks. The alliance's supreme commander for
Europe, Gen. Wesley Clark, complained of ``increasingly aggressive
Serb military and police activities.''
	   Clark said the stepped-up police activities did not conform to
Milosevic's pledges in the agreement. He reiterated that Milosevic
and top military commanders in Belgrade have been told they ``must
comply with their promises made to NATO.''
</TEXT>
