<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian parliament gives initial approval to 1999 budget
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS, UPDATES thruout with new details, quotes.
CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos MOSB101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNA DOLGOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Parliament gave quick initial approval to the
draft 1999 budget Thursday, stoking hopes that the hardliners who
dominate the legislature would cooperate with the government to
pull Russia out of its economic crisis.
	   In contrast with the rancor and commotion that have surrounded
the passage of past years' budgets, the lower house of parliament,
known as the State Duma, refrained from lambasting the government
Thursday and voted 303-65 to approve the 1999 budget after its
first reading.
	   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov rallied lawmakers' support in an
emotional speech before the vote, saying that Russia desperately
needs the budget to deal with the worst economic crisis since the
Soviet collapse.
	   ``The question is whether we're ready to undertake
responsibility for overcoming the crisis or will again sink into
debates, mutual recriminations and half-steps,'' Primakov said.
	   Last year, the Communists who dominate the Duma demanded more
spending on social programs and the dismissal of leading reformers
from the Cabinet as conditions for approving the budget.
	   Now, the severity of the economic crisis has made it clear to
all that the government doesn't have money for more social
spending. And Russia's new Cabinet, formed as a compromise with the
Communists, doesn't include radical reformers.
	   Primakov warned lawmakers before the vote that he would resign
along with his Cabinet if the budget were rejected.
	   A lean budget is essential for resolving the economic crisis. It
is also a key condition for getting new foreign loans, which Russia
desperately needs to help pay off its huge debts.
	   Many lawmakers said the budget was far from perfect, but argued
that the situation was too dire to put off approval.
	   ``The budget rejection or a significant delay in its passage
would bring our country to such a situation that the economic
crisis of August and September would seem like a time of economic
prosperity,'' Alexander Zhukov, the chairman of the Duma's budget
committee, told the session.
	   August and September were among the most painful months for many
Russians. Their wages and savings lost value by the day as the
ruble fell, banks froze individual accounts, and food all but
disappeared from some stores during a few days of panic-buying.
	   The draft budget is based on an average rate of 21.5 rubles to
the dollar and forecasts 30 percent inflation next year. But the
ruble has already fallen below 20 rubles to the dollar and
inflation this year is expected to top 70 percent.
	   ``Is there any single person who believes that forecast? No,
there is not,'' said prominent liberal lawmaker Grigory Yavlinsky,
an economist.
	   The budget also relies on dlrs 7.2 billion in foreign loans that
may not come, and counts on restructuring almost half of Russia's
dlrs 17.5 billion foreign debt _ something foreign lenders have yet
to agree to.
	   Russia's coffers are so bare that the entire 1999 budget calls
for government spending of just 575 billion rubles (dlrs 29
billion) and revenues of only 474 billion rubles (dlrs 24 billion).
	   By comparison, the United States government collects and spends
more than dlrs 30 billion in an average week.
	   The Duma must vote several more times on the budget in coming
weeks, and then send it to the upper house, the Federation Council.
The next Duma vote is unlikely to take place until next month at
the earliest.
	   (ad/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
