<HEADLINE>
OSCE reports violations in Kazak presidential race
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Multiple violations have marred the preparations
for a January presidential election in the Central Asian nation of
Kazakstan, international observers said Thursday.
	   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
criticized Kazakstan's government for barring two prominent
opposition leaders from the race, intimidating voters, and allowing
too little time for campaigning, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   Kazakstan's President Nursultan Nazarbayev is the overwhelming
favorite in the race in this former Soviet republic.
	   Nazarbayev's critics say he will not allow opposition candidates
to mount full-fledged campaigns against him.
	   Nazarbayev will face Communist Party leader Serkbolsyn Abdildin;
Engels Gabbasov, a teacher, writer and lawmaker; and Sany Kasymov,
head of Kazakstan's customs committee, in the Jan. 10 election.
	   Former Prime Minister Akezhan Kazhegeldin was barred from
running after attending a meeting of an unregistered political
group, and Asylbek Amantai, leader of an opposition political
movement, was shut out of the campaign because he was jailed nine
months ago for organizing an illegal meeting.
	   (ad/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
