<SLUG> BC-India-Rogue Elephants,0188 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wild elephants kill five in India's remote northeast
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GAUHATI, India (AP) _ A herd of wild elephants went on a rampage
in India's remote northeast, trampling to death at least five
people and critically injuring two others, a wildlife warden said
Thursday.
	   The attack took place Wednesday when nearly 50 wild Asiatic
elephants entered the village of Tingri, near the Ikhipathar
reserve forest where many elephants live, the warden said on
condition of anonymity.
	   An infant was among the dead in the stampede, which also
destroyed 50 mud huts.
	   Tingri is in Assam state, which has a population of nearly 5,000
elephants.
	   Another five people were killed in a similar elephant rampage
last week in Sonitpur area, 150 miles (240 kilometers) north of the
Assam capital of Gauhati.
	   Anwaruddin Chaudhary, a wildlife expert, said a shrinking
habitat and a disproportionate rise in the number of elephants in
the past 15 years have led to change in the elephants' behavior.
	   Wild elephants have killed nearly 400 people in Assam in the
past 10 years, Chaudhary said.
</TEXT>
