----APTN'S 1800 OUTLOOK FOR THURSDAY DECEMBER 24 1998----
----
CHRISTMAS EVE LIVE: ---------------
----
On Christmas Eve, APTN plans to have LIVE coverage - ON OUR LOCAL
ENDS ONLY - of the following:
----
- Midnight Mass in Bethlehem. APTN will have coverage from 2130 GMT
until 2245 GMT approximately. All material Palestinian TV  &QC;  No
Restrictions. Quality will be as incoming.
----
- Midnight Mass at the Vatican, where Pope John Paul the Second will
say the traditional Christmas Eve mass. APTN will have coverage from
2245 GMT until the end of the service. All material will be Vatican
TV  &QC;  No Restrictions.
----
THE LOCAL ENDS WILL BE VIDEO: VSSED V7/AUDIO: 22082 + 400034.
----
We will have comprehensive wraps of both events in our scheduled
news b-u-l-l-e-t-i-n-s following the end of the Christmas Eve
services.
----
NOTE: All given times are approximate and may change. In addition,
live transmissions may change due to reasons beyond APTN's control.
Clients wishing to use material live-to-air are advised to contact
APTN on +44 171 427 4100
----
EXPECTED:----
----
KUWAIT: TROOPS - APTN aims to have coverage of U-S troops deployed
in the Kuwaiti desert. (First Run Expected 2130 LatAm)
----
VENEZUELA: CHRISTMAS - Christmas would not be the same in Venezuela
without a traditional dish called hallaca - a fusion of Spanish,
African and indigenous cuisine.
APTN has the story. (First Run 1900 Latin America)
----
GEORGIA: DIPLOMAT - A Greek diplomat has been shot dead in his home
in the capital, Tblisi. (Timing To Be Confirmed)
-----
IRAQ: RALLY - Thousands of demonstrators have taken to the streets
to show their support for President Saddam Hussein following last
week's airstrikes by the U-S and Britain. (Timing To Be Confirmed)
-----
US: SOUP KITCHEN - New York City's largest soup kitchen offers
Christmas Eve dinner to more than one-thousand men, women and
children. (First Expected 1900 Latin America)
-----
US: OCTUPLETS - The father of the Texas octuplets has given a news
conference. APTN will have highlights. (First Expected 1900 Latin
America)
-----
RUNNING:----
------
KOSOVO: REFUGEES - Hundreds of ethnic Albanian refugees have taken
to the mountains around Pristina, after Serb forces struck at a
rebel stronghold. APTN has coverage of refugees walking to the
relative safety of the mountains, voxpops, footage of a civilian
killed in the fighting plus of KLA rebels in action. (First Run 1740
F-L-A-S-H)
----
TURKEY: BOMB - A Kurdish rebel has thrown herself in front of a
military bus in Van and ignited bombs strapped to her waist, killing
herself, a passerby and injuring 22 people. APTN has aftermath
coverage, footage of injured in hospital and comment from the local
police chief. (First Run 1600 Europe Late)
----
US: BUS CRASH - A bus carrying passengers from New York to Atlantic
City overturned on the Garden State Parkway, killing eight people.
This package wraps coverage of the rescue operation. (First Run 1740
F-l-a-s-h)
----
ANGOLA: UNITA - Government forces and UNITA rebels have been
fighting in the central highlands and aid workers say the army has
taken control of two rebel-held towns. APTN has coverage from
refugee camps, comment from some of those who fled the fighting and
of aid workers. (First Run 1600 Europe Late)
----
SPAIN: RELEASE - A comprehensive wrap of the release of ex-minister
Jose Barrionuevo and his ex-chief of state security Rafael Vera
who've been pardoned for their role in a ``dirty war'' against Basque
separatists. The footage shows both men walking free from jail and
receiving an emotional welcome from their supporters, plus comment
from Barrionuevo and file. (First Run 1600 Europe Late)
-----
IRAQ: CHRISTMAS - APTN has pictures of members of the peace group
'Voices in the Wilderness' dressed as Santas and helping Iraqi
children to celebrate Christmas in the wake of the US/British air
strikes. (First Run 1230 Europe Update)
----
RUSSIA: WRAP 2 - Russia's lower house of parliament gives the
government backing for its austere 1999 budget proposals aimed at
resolving the economic crisis that hit the country in the summer.
Earlier, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov threatened to resign had
the Duma not voted in favour of the proposals. (Both Elements ran
1600 Europe Late)
----
ISRAEL: POLITICS - Former Israeli general Amnon Lipkin Shahak gives
his first news conference since becoming a civilian and announcing
his entrance into Israeli politics while a former top model also
announces she's throwing her hat into the political ring. (Wrap
First Run 1600 Europe Late)
----
BETHLEHEM: PREPS - Hundreds of people, led by the top Roman Catholic
priest in the region, are preparing to celebrate Christmas in Manger
Square outside the Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem. (First Run
1600 Europe Late)
----
ROMANIA: VILLAGE - A European Union alternative energy project has
made it possible for homes in the most remote part of Romania to be
powered through electricity. It means this Christmas will be the
first under electric light for many villagers in northern
Transylvania. (First Run 1600 Europe Late)
----
FRANCE: TREES - Top designers in France have been getting into the
festive spirit by coming up with their own unique looks for the
traditional Christmas tree.  Big names such as Paco Rabanne and
Pierre Cardin are among those showing their designs at the Carrousel
du Louvre. (First Run 1600 Europe Late)
-----
US: COLD WEATHER - Freezing weather conditions have brought
Washington D-C to a standstill while New York's Central Park is
covered by several inches of snow. (First Run 1600 Europe Late)
----
HI-TECH: SANTA - A new website page created by North American
Aerospace Defence Command means Santa will be traced throughout
Christmas Eve as he delivers presents worldwide. Its operations
command centre plans to intercept and identify his sleigh using F-18
fighter planes. (First Run 1230 Europe Update)
----
MALAYSIA: ANWAR - Lawyers defending Malaysia's ousted deputy prime
minister Anwar Ibrahim have failed to win permission to play a tape
recording of a conversation they say points to a political
conspiracy against him. But the trial judge in the sex and
corruption case says he will allow the tape if defence lawyers can
point to inconsistencies in the week-long testimony of Ummi Hafilda
Ali - the prosecution's star witness. APTN has soundbites from
Anwar's wife and lawyers. (First Run 0900 Europe Morning)
----
JAPAN: BALLOON - We have pictures and comment as Richard Branson and
his team pass over Japan and head out over the Pacific toward North
America in their attempt to make the first non-stop voyage around
the world in a hot-air balloon. (First Run 0715 Asia Pacific Late)
----
CHINA: DISSIDENTS - APTN has a package which includes an interview
with a leading pro-democracy demonstrator after the recent crackdown
on dissidents in China. (First Run 0900 Europe Morning)
----
TAIWAN: DISSIDENT - Exiled Chinese dissident Wei Jingsheng has been
watching Taiwan's democratically elected legislature at work as he
continues his tour of the island. APTN has pictures and comment from
Wei. (First Run 0715 Asia Pacific Late)
----
NANJING: SKULLS - Pictures of skulls freshly discovered in Nanjing
reportedly provide evidence of chemical weapons use. The CCTV report
alleges that the traces of chemicals on the skulls prove that the
Japanese used Chinese prisoners as human guinea pigs for chemical
weapons experiments during World War Two. (First Run 0900 Europe
Morning)
----
