<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Lebanon-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egyptian minister: Apology not enough for killing civilians
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ An apology is not enough for the death of a
Lebanese women and six of her children killed in an Israeli air
raid on eastern Lebanon, the Egyptian foreign minister said
Thursday.
	   Amr Moussa also called on Israel to respect international laws
that forbid attacking civilian targets.
	   A Lebanese woman and six of her seven children were killed
Tuesday during an Israeli bombing raid on the eastern Lebanese
village of Nabi Sheet. The woman's husband and an 11-year-old son
were wounded in the attack.
	   The Israeli army later expressed regret for the loss of civilian
lives, saying its jets struck a civilian target by mistake while
trying to hit a guerrilla training facility and broadcast station.
	   ``Egypt condemns the killing and attacks against civilians, and
an apology is not enough,'' Moussa told reporters Thursday.
	   Lebanese guerrillas retaliated Wednesday by showering northern
Israeli settlements with Katyusha rockets, injuring 16 Israelis _
15 suffered from shock, and one suffered moderate wounds.
	   ``Israel should respect international laws and charters that
prohibit attacks on civilians,'' Moussa said, adding that Lebanese
and Palestinian people were as human as Israelis.
	   The latest violence threatened to undermine a U.S.-brokered
ceasefire agreement reached in April 1996 to spare civilians.
