w2405 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EditorialRoundup 1stAdd   12-24 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Editorial Roundup, 1st Add,0958 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: its opponents.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   La Vanguardia, Barcelona, Spain, on Mideast peace process:
	   The weaknesses of (Clinton, Netanyahu and Arafat) have condemned
the peace process. But not all three are equally to blame.
Netanyahu is a case on his own. He gained power after allying with
the Israeli sectors most opposed to withdrawal from the West Bank
although he maintained that the only thing he was concerned with
was Israel's security. But now, however, when his most extreme
allies have withdrawn their support, all has been laid bare: the
question was not one of security but rather opposition to any
substantial withdrawal from the West Bank. ... In the end,
Netanyahu has achieved part of his objective: early elections means
the peace process will be frozen for another four months. Then the
electorate will decide.
	    &UR; ___
	   Il Messaggero, Rome, on U.S. air strikes against Iraq:
	   The war stirred up by the United States and Britain against Iraq
did not produce winners.
	   The list of those defeated is very impressive: Bill Clinton and
Tony Blair, Russia and China, Arafat and the Palestinians, the
United Nations and Europe. Saddam Hussein should also appear on
this ``black list.''
	   Clinton was unable to explain the legitimacy of his decision,
arousing suspicion that the timing was in some way linked to the
impeachment process. Only Blair sided with him militarily: a
dishonorable sign of his historical, tactical and psychological
subjection.
	   Even Russia and China were not part of the American preventive
diplomacy dialogue, even if they are permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council.
	   The missiles on Baghdad annulled the success of Clinton's
historical visit to Palestinian territories, where, once again, the
``Stars and Stripes'' has been put to flames.
	   The United Nations' credibility has been destroyed by both
Clinton and Saddam, and Europe showed once again that it is unable
to find a common political voice. ...
	    &UR; ___
	   Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung, Frankfurt, on Iraq:
	   Everything is fine, but Saddam stays. This is how the political
result of the latest Middle East war against Iraq could be
summarized. It is disastrous. ... The latest military strike has
hurt Saddam (the population even more so), but it has increased the
dictator's standing among the Arab masses.
	   Washington has served word that it now intends to oust Saddam
Hussein from his throne in the long term. That is not realistic.
Nobody knows what would be supposed to happen after a coup in Iraq.
It also seems that no one has given it any serious thought. ... The
Americans are now helpless with Iraq, they don't know what to do
next.
	    &UR; ___'
	   The Straits Times, Singapore, on Clinton impeachment:
	   The impeachment of President Bill Clinton by the U.S. House of
Representatives goes far beyond the fortunes of a flawed man or the
careers of his vindictive opponents. It bears on issues of
governance that make it more difficult for proponents of the
American Way to spread their message across the globe. What stands
revealed is the hand of bloody-minded adversarial politics, which
divides a nation within and paralyzes its workings abroad just when
its leadership of the world is most needed. There are no heroes in
this story, only an array of small men taking turns to hold hostage
institutions intended to deliver the state from harm.
	   ...in its self-righteous zeal to bring him down, no matter what
it takes or how long it takes or whom it hurts or how badly it
hurts, Congress has made a mockery of its responsibilities to the
people who have elected it. Very many members of that institution
seem consumed by vengeance...
	    &UR; ___
	   The Jordan Times, Amman, Jordan, on France-Iraq:
	   All eyes are now focused on the French initiative that President
Jacques Chirac on Sunday said France would launch to deal more
reasonably with the Iraqi situation following the U.S. and British
attack on that country. President Chirac is already on record as
being opposed to any military action against Iraq without the
consent of the U.N. security Council.
	   This places Paris in a unique position to take an initiative
that can be acceptable to all sides especially Iraq. Russian and
Chinese solidarity lend valuable support to it within the U.N.
Security Council. There is a basic agreement between the three
major capitals that the case of Iraq must be returned to the
council as sine qua non to any meaningful, just and permanent
settlement of the decade_long crisis.
	   The Arab capitals have been caught off guard by the events of
last week and saw their mild and ineffective reactions overshadowed
by Russian, Chinese, and Vatican pronouncements. The Arab World
needs to get its act together by adopting a clear and coherent
stance on the Iraq situation and on how to deal with it in the
aftermath of last week's bombardments of the country.
	    &UR; ___
	   Clarin, Buenos Aires, on the bombardment of Iraq:
	   The end of the U.S.-British attack on Iraq raises more questions
than it answers. The military campaign, it would seem, has caused
important damage to strategic installations of Saddam Hussein's
regime ...
	   Hussein has made clear that from now on he will not allow more
U.N. weapons inspectors, arguing that the attack has destroyed the
object of those inspections.
	   It is impossible to tell if the missiles have met with such
success and it is very possible that chemical weapons arsenals
still survive or can be replenished ... As such, the outcome
heralds the start of a new stage of hard negotiation, or future
conflicts. Neither of the two alternatives promises an improvement
for world security.
	    &UR; ___
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
