<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Brazil-Kidnappers,0434 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hunger-striking kidnappers stop drinking water
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STAN LEHMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) _ Eight hunger-striking kidnappers on
Thursday stopped drinking water, underscoring their determination
to die if the Brazilian government doesn't release them.
	   The group is in prison for the 1989 kidnapping Abilio Diniz,
owner of Brazil's largest supermarket chain, demanding ransom in a
bid to fund Salvadoran rebels.
	   The five Chileans, two Argentines and one Brazilian stopped
eating on Nov. 16 to pressure the government to send the foreigners
home and pardon the Brazilian. Two Canadians also convicted in the
kidnapping, David Lamont and Christine Spencer, were transferred to
a Vancouver prison on Nov. 20.
	   Breno Altman, president of the Committee to Free Political
Prisoners, said the decision to stop drinking water was reached
``when it became clear that the government would not release the
prisoners after their sentences were reduced.''
	   Last week, a Sao Paulo court reduced the kidnappers' sentences
to between 15 and 18 years from 26 to 28 years, opening the way to
a possible paroled as early as February.
	   However, Sao Paulo Judge Otavio Augusto Machado do Barros said
that early release for those still in Brazil would depend on a
number of factors including their behavior while in prison.
	   ``They are not automatically entitled to anything,'' he said
last week. ``They have failed all their psychological evaluations
and have shown no remorse for their crime.''
	   The prisoners are hospitalized at Sao Paulo's Hospital das
Clinicas where doctors said that without water the prisoners could
die within five days.
	   Doctors said they would obey a court order to force-feed them
with a mixture of sodium, potassium and carbohydrates, once they
lose consciousness.
	   ``They (the prisoners) are fully aware of the consequences of
their decision,'' Altman said. ``Their fate is now in the hands of
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso who is the only one who can
authorize the expulsion and pardon.''
	   Cardoso on Thursday said Congress was expected to approve in
January prisoner transfer treaties with Chile and Argentina similar
to the one that befitted Spencer and Lamont.
	   ``This is the best solution to the impasse,'' Cardoso said,
urging the prisoners to stop their hunger strike.
	   The hunger strikers are: Ulisses Acevedo, Maria Marchi Badilla,
Pedro Lembach, Sergio Urtubia and Hector Ramon Tapia of Chile;
Humberto and Horacio Paz of Argentina; and Brazilian Raimundo
Freire.
</TEXT>
