<SLUG> BC-Georgia-Greece, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Greek diplomat shot and killed in Georgia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details of killing, speculation killing was
related to issuing of visas to Georgian workers. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) _ A Greek diplomat was killed by automatic
weapons-fire Thursday in the Georgian capital Tbilisi, police said.
	   Anastasius Mizitrasos, 37, had been working as a security
attache at Greece's embassy in Tbilisi since March 1997. He was
shot and killed by unidentified gunmen just inside the house where
he lived with his wife and child, said Demuri Beradze, duty officer
of the district police in the prestigious Vake neighborhood of the
capital.
	   The gunmen escaped in a car, and burned it, Russian media
reported.
	   Russia's ORT public television station reported speculation in
Tbilisi that the killing was tied to disputes over the issuing of
Greek visas to Georgian workers who provide ``cheap labor.''
However, Georgian police would not discuss possible motives for the
killing.
	   An investigation into the killing has been launched, Beradze
said.
	   (str/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
