<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Central Asia,0665 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU helps Central Asia reopen old trade routes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNA SATHIAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ At a time when the European Union is
opening its arms to eastern Europe, the five Central Asian
economies _ once trading hubs for merchants traveling the Silk Road
_ lobby for their share of EU support.
	   Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Turkmenistan and Tajikistan
_ former Soviet republics that broke with Moscow in 1991 _ are
counting on the EU to help them develop proper laws, managerial
know-how and reliable infrastructure.
	   ``They still have a long way to go,'' said Cees Wittebrood, an
official at the EU executive Commission who deals with relations
between the 15-nation bloc and Central Asia, the Caucasus and
Mongolia.
	   ``The way ahead of them is now getting bumpier, with the
economic impact of the Russian crisis and the political impact of
the civil war in Afghanistan.''
	   He said the EU's role is to ``give focus'' to the Central Asian
economies. ``They have a guiding light, which is integration into
European structures.''
	   The EU believes its political possibilities are limited in
Central Asia and that economic partnership is the best way to make
a difference and contribute to political stability in a volatile
region.
	   Central Asia lies at a strategic crossroads linking China,
Pakistan, Afghanistan, Iran and Turkey. Countries there,
particularly Tajikistan and Turkmenistan, are wide open to
fundamentalist influences from Afghanistan.
	   The EU tries to counter these through economic aid. Over the
1991-1997 period, it committed some dlrs 280 million to the five
Central Asian countries, out of a total dlrs 2 billion dollars for
all 15 ex-Soviet republics and Mongolia.
	   In a way, the EU seeks to open up again the Old Silk Road. ``We
want to rebuild the roads that in the old days were used to link
East and West,'' says Wittebrood.
	   Caravans of silk, gold and incense once journeyed through the
rugged landscape of Central Asia, and some believe the former
Soviet states could revive their old, mercantile tradition.
	   ``Traditionally, trade between the Far East and China transited
through our countries,'' says Uzbekistan's Ambassador to the EU
Alisher Faizullaev.
	   EU economic aid aims to help restore old pipelines and bring
countries in the region together to discuss options for new
pipeline routes. Turkey, Iran and Romania want those new pipelines
to run through their territory.
	   ``We do not take a position. We do not express a preference. It
is up to the Central Asian countries to decide,'' said Wittebrood.
	   Bazaars still dot the road once traveled by Marco Polo.
	   But instead of silk and spices, the Central Asians hope oil and
gas will flow along the old routes once they successfully shed the
burdensome economic legacy of Soviet rule.
	   Central Asia has enormous potential in oil, gas, and minerals.
European investors are already involved in major projects, with
Germany by far the biggest investor.
	   Turkmenistan has lots of oil and gas. So does Kazakhstan but it
also has gold, uranium, copper and other minerals. Uzbekistan has
gold and is a big producer of cotton. Kyrgyzstan banks on
hydroelectricity. Tajikistan has gold deposits, but not much else.
	   Central Asians view EU expansion talks with 10 East European
neighbors and Cyprus, that began in November, as a positive
development that could in turn benefit them.
	   ``Via enlargement, we'll be closer to Europe. A lot of good
things will come with EU expansion,'' says Faizullaev.
	   Wittebrood agrees.
	   Knowing that the road ahead of them is long and difficult, the
governments of these territories, once arbitrarily divided into
states by Josef Stalin, seek to build up their strength through
greater regional cooperation.
	   ``These countries do not want to entirely cut their links with
Russia, but certainly they want to reduce their dependence on
Moscow,'' says Wittebrood. 	   
</TEXT>
