w2462 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-OldEnemies'Eve     12-24 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Old Enemies' Eve </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In Italian town, World War II enemies meet for stories, soup and
</HEADLINE>
reconciliation &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ORTONA, Italy (AP) _ Fifty-five Christmases ago, they were
fighting each other house-to-house in the central Italian town of
Ortona, trying to kill rather than be killed themselves.
	   This Christmas Eve, the old German and Canadian soldiers who
managed to pull that off faced each other over tables in what had
then been Ortona's bombed-out church _ sharing a holiday meal
together; savoring their shared survival.
	   ``Fifty-five years ago I was burying our dead. Digging graves,''
said Bill Teleske, 79, of Edmonton, Canada, who was a 23-year-old
private during the 1943 battle for control of the Mediterranean.
	   ``Tonight, we had a good bowl of hot soup together, a good
supper, which is more than we had then,'' Teleske said.
	   ``There's no animosity,'' he said. ``The Germans say, `It was a
very good fight _ unfortunately, you won.'''
	   Donations from people at home helped pay for the trips for the
29 Canadian veterans here after Canada's Ministry of Veterans
Affairs turned down a request for funding.
	   The Canadians talked, ate and shared old photos with seven
German veterans _ like them, survivors of a Dec. 21-27 battle for
Ortona. The bloodiness, the tight quarters of the fight between
Canadian soldiers and German infantry and paratroopers earned it
the name of the ``Stalingrad of the West.''
	   German survivors of the battle returned home to ignominy.
Thursday night's dinner at Santa Maria di Costantiniopoli with
their old enemies at least gave the German veterans a chance to
talk with someone who understood and respected their ordeal, one
said.
	   ``Soldiers don't make war. Politicians make it. That is the
point,'' said Joseph Klein, 78, of Wolssburg, Germany.
	   ``It is very, very good,'' Klein said. ``We shook hands and we
had a really nice conciliation dinner.''
	   Italian hosts served the old soldiers vegetable soup, the town's
specialty; turkey; and strudel in a side room of the church after a
service led by an Italian priest. Then, they left them to talk.
	   ``There's lot of stories circulating. Where ever there's
soldiers, there's stories. Everyone has a story to tell,'' Teleske
said.
	   ``I can only put it this way: I wouldn't go through it again for
a million dollars _ but now I've gone through it and come out alive
I wouldn't miss this for a million dollars,'' he said. ``Tonight is
a wonderful night.''
	   (ek) 	   
</TEXT>
