u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Politics     12-24 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Barely into the political water, and Shahak sees sharks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RON KAMPEAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ All Israel's most recently-retired military
chief did Thursday was give back his uniform, declare an interest
in political life, and mouth a few pieties about hope and getting
along.
	   ``We need to make peace at home first, and then peace with our
neighbors,'' Lt. Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak said.
	   In the an elections year, peace with the Arabs may be easier.
	   ``Leftist'' bellowed hawks on the right, barely Shahak was out
the gate at military headquarters in Tel Aviv. ``Lawbreaker,'' they
threw in for good measure.
	   ``Lacks experience,'' countered the doves in opposition. And _
for the Israeli left, the equivalent of the atom bomb _ an
accusation Shahak was risking the legacy of his mentor, late
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
	   Like Colin Powell in the United States, Shahak is a successful
army man perceived by many as clean and remote enough from the
rough and tumble of politics to qualify for political leadership.
	   That has given him a lead in polls in the early elections for
prime minister.
	   A Maariv/Gallup poll published Thursday showed Shahak _ as head
of an as-yet unformed centrist party _ with the strongest chance to
beat Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in elections likely to take
place by the end of April.
	   Shahak did not declare himself a candidate for prime minister,
and only vaguely committed himself to any political role.
	   But the denuding process left so many Israeli generals before
him in the cold is just beginning _ and his opponents wasted no
time in attempts at denting his armor.
	   A cartoon in the Haaretz newspaper on Thursday showed Shahak _
who started his military career as a paratrooper _ floating into a
sea of sharks.
	   Most threatened is Netanyahu, who agreed to early elections
earlier this week after he failed to get parliamentary backing for
his hard-line peace policies.
	   Netanyahu's Likud party immediately issued a statement
describing Shahak as a ``known leftist.''
	   In 1993 Rabin ordered Shahak, then deputy chief-of-staff, to
negotiate details of the then-fresh Oslo peace process with the
Palestinians. He became closely identified with the process, and
was blamed by Netanyahu for what the right perceives as policies
that left Israel vulnerable.
	   Likud figures also accused Shahak of breaking a law separating
the military from the political arena by meeting political leaders
in recent months, although he refrained from any political
pronouncements.
	   ``There's more than just a technical formality'' broken, said
Likud legislator Uzi Landau. ``An army chief-of-staff should set a
good example.'' Shahak held the meetings while he was on leave,
after he stepped down as chief-of-staff last August.
	   On the left, Labor Party legislators said Shahak was an unknown
quantity, and was not ready for the top job.
	   ``He was doing things that perhaps were more important,'' than
politics, Labor legislator Yossi Beilin said, but ``he lacks
political experience completely.''
	   ``I completed basic training 36 years ago,'' Shahak quipped.
	   Labor Party leaders bristled at a newspaper report that Shahak
would not join them because they were too closely associated with
the left.
	   In a reference to Shahak, Labor party leader Ehud Barak _
Shahak's predecessor as chief of staff _ excoriated him for the
alleged remark.
	   ``We are proud (of being on the left) and we will continue to
follow it until we win in the elections,'' he told a Labor party
meeting. ``Whoever doesn't understand this connection shouldn't use
the name of Yitzhak Rabin.''
	   It won't be the first time a golden boy of the army got
tarnished in the political arena. Most recently, Barak has
alienated many in his own party by not mounting a more credible
opposition against Netanyahu, despite a propensity for the
Netanyahu government to stumble from crisis to crisis.
	   There's a long list of decorated Israeli generals who finished
their careers in undistinguished political posts. Some 121 of
Israel's cabinet ministers since its inception have been
senior-ranking officers.
	   But Israelis remember the successes _ Moshe Dayan, who
negotiated peace with the Egyptians; Rabin, who anchored the
breakthrough with the Palestinians.
	   One former general on the other side of the political fence _
Uri Saguy _ expressed a rare note of sympathy for Shahak.
	   ``All of us, including those who are just released from the
army, are human beings and not gods, with weaknesses and faults and
with advantages of course,'' Saguy, a Likud legislator, tols Israel
army radio. ``We should relate to things in their proper
proportion.''
	   (rk) 	   
</TEXT>
