<SLUG> BC-Russia-Helicopter </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ka-60 helicopter takes maiden flight
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A new military transport helicopter that has been
in development since the 1980s took its maiden flight on Thursday,
the Interfax news agency reported.
	   The Ka-60, designed by the Kamov firm, is a twin-engined general
purpose military transport helicopter capable of carrying 14 troops
and more than 2 tons of cargo. Its development has been stalled by
the military's desperate cash shortage.
	   Gen. Vitaly Pavlov, the head of the Army Aviation Department of
the Defense Ministry, said that the army was interested in
receiving the new helicopters, Interfax reported. He said that up
to 330 Ka-60 helicopters would be used for training in military
academies.
	   The helicopter's chief designer, Vyacheslav Krygin, said serial
production would begin after flight tests are completed, in about 1
1/2 years, Interfax reported.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
