<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cuba-Christmas,0473 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Forget Santa Claus. For Cubans, it's family dinner on Christmas
</HEADLINE>
eve &QL; 
 &UR; AP photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By ANITA SNOW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HAVANA (AP) _ Forget Santa Claus, Christmas trees and sleigh
bells in the snow. For Cubans, the family dinner on Christmas Eve
is the heart of the Christmas celebration.
	   Cubans crowded markets on Thursday to buy pork roasts and other
traditional foods for ``Noche Buena,'' which is especially festive
this year because of the declaration of Dec. 25 as a permanent
holiday.
	   ``I've never seen it this crowded this early,'' said Felicia
Margarita Baix, who arrived at the farmers' market in the Miramar
neighborhood to buy a pork leg at reduced government prices. ``This
is what it looks like for the New Year.''
	   The Dec. 24 tradition was lost or faded in importance for many
Cubans, especially after the Christmas holiday was abolished in
1969 by a government that was then officially atheist. The
government later declared itself a secular state and gradually
eased up on religious believers.
	   Interest in past Christmas traditions began to bloom last year
when the communist government granted a Christmas holiday as a
one-time favor to Pope John Paul II before his January 1998 visit
here. It was made permanent this year.
	   ``The Christmas feast is intimate, it is of the family, of the
heart,'' Roman Catholic Cardinal Jaime Ortega said earlier this
week. ``It is the love of the family gathered together.''
	   The New Year's Eve dinner, coinciding with the anniversary of
the revolution that brought Fidel Castro to power 40 years ago,
remains the most important holiday celebration in Cuba.
	   Both last and this year, there was a booming business in small
artificial Christmas trees selling for around dlrs 22 _ about twice
the average monthly government salary.
	   But the giving of gifts _ except for small children _ is not a
part of the celebration in a country that continues to suffer a
severe economic crisis. The figure of Santa Claus remains a mystery
to most Cubans, although he can be seen in the windows of a few
stores downtown.
	   Cubans prefer to spend their money on the family meal,
traditionally black beans and rice, a green salad with tomatoes,
perhaps yams, fried plantains or yucca, and the inevitable roast
pork.
	   On Thursday, there were long lines at the farmers market even
though some shoppers complained about the high prices. Dark rum and
beer _ the favorite Christmas drinks _ are available for pesos at
government stores.
	   But most other liquor, and imported candies like the ``turones''
from Spain that many Cubans like with their Christmas Eve meal, are
available only to about half the population who now have dollars to
purchase them in hard-currency stores. 	   
</TEXT>
