<SLUG> BC-Israel-Russia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel condemns comments of Russian Communist leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LAURIE COPANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ A Russian Communist Party boss who accused Jews
of causing ``mass impoverishment'' and ``extinction'' in the
country demonstrated how far his party was from the democratic
ideals it claimed to uphold, Israel said Thursday.
	   Communist Party chief Gennady Zyuganov, who finished second in
the 1996 presidential election, made the remarks Wednesday in
response to calls on him to denounce recent anti-Semitic comments
by others in the party.
	   ``The spread of Zionism in the state government in Russia is one
of the reasons for the current catastrophic condition of the
country, the mass impoverishment and the process of extinction of
its people,'' Zyuganov said in an open letter released.
	   The Israeli foreign ministry denounced Zyuganov's words in a
statement Thursday.
	   ``Israel severely condemns and expresses shock from these
anti-Semitic declarations that do not contribute to relations
between the Russian and Jewish peoples and the state of Israel,''
read the statement.
	   ``These statements are not consistent with (Zyuganov's) claims
that his party aims to build a democratic society in Russia,'' it
said.
	   It said it was clear that Zyuganov was drawing on an infamous
anti-Semitic forgery, ``The Protocols of the Elders of Zion.''
	   Under Zyuganov, the Communist party has taken on an increasingly
aggressive, nationalistic tone. Anti-Semitic rhetoric has grown
with the nation's economic troubles _ the traditional spark for
scapegoating.
	   ``Israel expresses hope that the Russian powers will find
appropriate ways to deal with this grave incident,'' read the
foreign ministry statement.
	   lc/rk 	   
</TEXT>
