<SLUG> BC-Israel-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru,0714 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Only a toe into Israel's political waters, and Shahak sees sharks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with reaction to Shahak entering
politics. &QL; 
 &UR; By RON KAMPEAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ The only thing Israel's former chief of staff
did on Thursday was give back his uniform, declare an interest in
political life, and mouth a few pieties about hope and getting
along.
	   In an election year, that's enough to spark a war.
	   ``We need to make peace at home first, and then peace with our
neighbors,'' said Lt. Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak as he formally ended
his military career. Shahak has been on leave since stepping down
as chief of staff in July.
	   ``Leftist,'' bellowed hawks on the right. ``Lawbreaker,'' they
threw in for good measure.
	   ``Lacks experience,'' countered the doves in opposition. Then
they dropped their version of the atom bomb: He's not worthy of the
legacy of slain Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
	   Like Colin Powell in the United States, Shahak is a successful
army veteran perceived by many as clean and remote enough from the
rough and tumble of politics to qualify for political leadership.
	   His reputation has already given him a lead in polls in the
early elections for prime minister.
	   A Maariv/Gallup poll published Thursday showed Shahak with the
strongest chance to beat Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in
elections likely to take place by the end of April.
	   That even though Shahak has not declared himself a candidate and
the centrist party everyone sees him leading doesn't even exist
yet.
	   By leaving the army, he not only became free for the first time
to talk politics _ and, many hope, run for prime minister _ he also
became free game for nervous rivals on all sides.
	   On Thursday Shahak only vaguely committed himself to any
political role, but his opponents wasted no time with a pre-emptive
strike.
	   A cartoon in the Haaretz newspaper showed Shahak _ who started
his military career as a paratrooper _ floating into a sea of
sharks.
	   Most threatened is Netanyahu, who agreed to early elections this
week after he failed to get parliamentary backing for his hard-line
peace policies.
	   Netanyahu's Likud party immediately issued a statement
describing Shahak as a ``known leftist.''
	   In 1993 Rabin ordered Shahak, then deputy chief of staff, to
negotiate details of the Oslo peace process with the Palestinians.
He became closely identified with the process, and was blamed by
the right for what it perceives as policies that left Israel
vulnerable.
	   Likud figures also accused Shahak on Thursday of breaking a law
separating the military from the political arena by meeting
political leaders in recent months, although he was on leave ahead
of his retirement and made no political statements.
	   Meanwhile, from the left, Labor party legislators said Shahak
was an unknown quantity, unready for the top job.
	   ``He was doing things that perhaps were more important,'' than
politics, Labor legislator Yossi Beilin said, but ``he lacks
political experience completely.''
	   ``I completed basic training 36 years ago,'' Shahak quipped in
response.
	   Labor leader Ehud Barak excoriated Shahak for a news report that
he was balking at joining Labor because it was too leftist.
	   ``We are proud (of being on the left) and we will continue to
follow it until we win in the elections,'' Barak told a Labor party
meeting. ``Whoever doesn't understand this connection shouldn't use
the name of Yitzhak Rabin.''
	   Barak _ Shahak's predecessor as chief of staff _ was also a
golden boy of the army who had troubles moving in to the political
arena. Many in his own party criticize him for not mounting a more
credible opposition against the crisis-ridden Netanyahu government.
	   Shahak is a long line of generals to move from the military to
politics _ some with more success than others.
	   One former general on the other side of the political fence _
Uri Saguy _ expressed a rare note of sympathy for Shahak.
	   ``All of us, including those who are just released from the
army, are human beings and not gods, with weaknesses and faults and
with advantages of course,'' Saguy, a Likud legislator, told Israel
army radio. 	   
</TEXT>
