<SLUG> BC-Britain-Sierra Leone-Evacuation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Westerners evacuated from Sierra Leone, Foreign Office says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Two British Royal Air Force Hercules military
transporter planes on Thursday evacuated 81 British and European
citizens - including nine Italian priests - from Sierra Leone, the
Foreign Office said, after an intensification of fighting between
government and rebel forces in the west African state.
	   The spokesman said that the evacuees, who were all uninjured,
were flown from Lungi airport near Sierra Leone's capital,
Freetown, to the capital of Senegal, Dakar.
	   ''A majority of them were British, some were from European
nations. There were also 9 Italian priests. That's all the people
that wanted to leave this evening,'' the spokesman, speaking on
terms of customary anonymity, said.
	   The spokesman said that the evacuation was a precautionary
measure, and that more flights may be arranged.
	   Refugees have poured into Sierra Leone's capital this week after
fighting intensified between rebel forces and Nigerian-led West
African intervention troops based in nearby towns.
	   Thousands of villagers have lost limbs and others have been
killed in attacks apparently carried out by the rebel troops,
seeking revenge for their ouster from Freetown by the West African
force in February.
	   That allowed elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah to return from
months in exile after Lt. Col. Johnny Paul Koroma took power in a
bloody May 1997 coup.
	   (rs) 	   
</TEXT>
