<HEADER>
w2606 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EditorialRoundup 2ndAdd   12-24 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Editorial Roundup, 2nd Add,1067 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: world security.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITS &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   The Evening Post, Wellington, New Zealand, on Clinton
impeachment:
	   The Clinton impeachment is the stuff of Shakespearean tragedy. A
talented and popular president, leader of the most powerful country
in the world, risks being brought down by his fondness for sexual
dalliance and his ill-judged attempts to cover his tracks by lying.
It is a tragedy of potentially epic scale: tragic not just for
Clinton personally, but for his country . . . and for the world
which desperately needs stability in the White House.
	   One thing must be said: President Clinton is a louse. He is a
sexual predator and prevaricator. But he has also been an effective
leader _ and since when were United States presidents required to
be as morally pure as the driven snow?
	   Yes, President Clinton behaved badly; but his misdemeanors
scarcely warrant impeachment. It is hard to escape the feeling that
the vote against him in the House of Representatives represents the
dark face of old-fashioned American Puritanism. It also represents
the dark face of American hypocrisy _ a fact dramatically
demonstrated by the shocking resignation of Bob Livingstone.
	   The question must be asked: how many politicians in Washington
can place their hands on their hearts and say they haven't cheated?
And where will the witch-hunt end?
	   At a time when the world desperately needs American leadership
on a range of pressing issues including world economic recovery,
peace in the Middle East and Saddam Hussein's Iraq, Washington is
preoccupied with its domestic imbroglio and Clinton is fighting for
his political survival.
	   It's a huge penalty to pay for a fleeting sexual encounter and
unfortunately it's not just President Clinton who will suffer.
	   Shakespeare would have loved it.
	    &UR; ___
	   The New York Times, on possible censure of President Clinton:
	   The Senate seems inclined to treat Bill Clinton's misconduct in
a fair and responsible way, provided the President will let it do
so. Though Senate sentiment has not yet coalesced around a specific
plan, both Republicans and Democrats are talking of censure as the
most appropriate punishment. For the last couple of days Mr.
Clinton and his aides have seemed in better touch with political
reality. They can help keep the Senate on a conciliatory course by
dispensing with the legal quibbling that has helped bring his
Presidency to the brink of destruction and by continuing to send
receptive signals about censure. ...
	    &UR; ___
	   The Washington Post, on freedom of speech in China:
	   So now we know the cost of speaking freely in China: 13 years
behind bars. That's the sentence handed down after a sham trial to
Xu Wenli, who tried to organize a Chinese Democratic Party. Fellow
democrats Wang Youcai and Qin Yongmin were sentenced to 11 and 12
years, respectively. None was allowed to mount a defense.
	   In October China's Communist rulers signed, to great
self-congratulation and international acclaim, a treaty that
recognizes freedom of speech and freedom of association as
universal rights. Mr. Xu and his colleagues have now been sent back
to the Chinese gulag for seeking to exercise them. ...
	    &UR; ___
	   The Daily Tidings, Ashland, Oregon, on Clinton impeachment:
	   President Clinton by now should realize that his chief legacy
will be impeachment.
	   The entire affair is a tragedy for America. Bill Clinton's
presidency is in tatters, and it's his own fault. He has shown
disrespect for the people of his country, his co-workers, his
family and others. He no longer deserves to be president.
	   No, the current scandal is not Watergate. That's a no-brainer.
But Bill Clinton apparently did lie under oath, intending to
mislead the prosecutor, the grand jury and the American people by
doing so.
	   Those abroad and at home who claim that this is still a sexual
inquisition do not get it: the President of the United States is
formally accused of lying under oath. If a police officer, a
teacher, a plumber, a nurse or a reporter did that _ and the
charges were proven _ he or she would go to prison. The president
must be held to the same standard we all are.
	   ... We do not know whether Bill Clinton will be convicted by the
Senate on these serious charges. But we are convinced that he
should face them, as the Constitution outlines. ...
	    &UR; ___
	   The Cincinnati Enquirer, on Clinton impeachment:
	   Historians may need to get professional help from psychologists
to analyze President Clinton's speech last Wednesday night,
justifying a surprise attack on Iraq. Words aimed like Tomahawk
missiles at Saddam Hussein boomeranged and blew up in the
president's face.
	   ``Instead of the inspectors disarming Saddam, Saddam disarmed
the inspectors,'' Mr. Clinton said _ unintentionally describing his
own strategy to block ``inspections'' of White House scandals.
	   He said Saddam was given ``one last chance,'' but ``failed to
seize it.'' How many chances at contrition and confession has Mr.
Clinton failed to seize with his insincere, carefully parsed
apologies?
	   His ``powerful message'' to Saddam was: ``If you act recklessly,
you will pay a heavy price'' _ exactly the powerful message to Mr.
Clinton of impeachment by the House yesterday.
	    &UR; ___
	   The Index-Journal, Greenwood, South Carolina, on Saddam Hussein:
	   Response from some nations critical of the American and British
action against Saddam Hussein is patently self-serving. That's
obvious, even as they so often pretend to be our friends.
	   Russia, China and France are among those who have disagreed with
steps taken to punish Saddam. Russia and China, in fact, have
``demanded'' that we stop.
	   That, of course, should surprise nobody. These three nations,
particularly, have been known to sell technology and military
equipment and jet fighters to Saddam. Even nuclear and germ warfare
materials have been shipped to him. ...
	   It's amazing how in times like these that some nations are quick
to lambaste the United States. Many of them are the same ones that
want _ expect _ us to provide them with security, food and all
kinds of aid.
	   It is one more indication why we should always keep our guard
up, and that means not letting our military and its equipment
decline. We've learned that lesson many times _ too many times.
</TEXT>
