w2607 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Palestinian-Christmas     12-24 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Palestinian-Christmas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Latin patriarch delivers political mass
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SAMAR ASSAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BETHLEHEM, West Bank (AP) _ In a sharply political Christmas
Mass, the Latin patriarch of Jerusalem recalled Palestinian
prisoners in Israeli jails and lashed out at the ``oppressor.''
	   Michel Sabbah, the top Roman Catholic official in the region,
also prayed for ``the suffering of the people of Iraq,'' days after
a U.S.-British bombardment of the country.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who attended the Mass, has
recently clashed with Israel over its refusal to release
Palestinians jailed for killing.
	   Sabbah said Palestinian-controlled Bethlehem was still unable to
enjoy peace _ an allusion to the stalled peace process.
	   Addressing Arafat as ``President'' _ a term rejected by Israel,
which considers intimations of Palestinian statehood a threat _
Sabbah said Arafat had as his motto, ``The message of the angels.''
	   ``May it bring forgiveness but also purification to those who
oppress ... when peace is in the heart, it will be possible to
establish it in the land.''
	   ``We pray for the people of Iraq in its continuous suffering,''
he said. Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions for eight years because
of President Saddam Hussein's refusal to cooperate with a program
to ensure the destruction of the country's weapons of mass
destruction.
	   ``We pray for the prisoners in our lands still suffering and
deprived of freedom of peace,'' he said, an allusion to the recent
dispute with Israel.
	   Arafat says Israel agreed to release the killers at
U.S.-brokered peace talks at Wye River, Maryland. Israel insists
that was never on the agenda.
	   Israel Television's Arabic service and Palestinian television
simultaneously broadcast the mass.
	   Messages were read in a succession of languages by monks after
the service.
	   One monk, speaking Arabic-accented Hebrew, prayed for ``peace in
in the hearts of leaders of our region.''
	   (sa/rk) 	   
</TEXT>
