<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Russia,0253 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel condemns anti-Semitic comments of Russian Communist leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LAURIE COPANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel denounced Russian Communist Party leader
Gennady Zyuganov Thursday for making ``anti-Semitic declarations''
and expressed hope that Russian authorities would find appropriate
ways to deal with his slurs.
	   Zyuganov, who finished second in the 1996 presidential election,
blamed Jews in the Russian government for helping to cause ``the
current catastrophic condition of the country, the mass
impoverishment and the process of extinction of its people.''
	   Zyuganov's remarks Wednesday were in response to calls on him to
denounce recent anti-Semitic comments by others in the party.
	   Israel's Foreign Ministry said Zyuganov's statement were not
consistent with his claims that the Communist Party ``aims to build
a democratic society in Russia.''
	   ``Israel severely condemns and expresses shock from these
anti-Semitic declarations that do not contribute to relations
between the Russian and Jewish peoples and the state of Israel,''
the ministry said in a statement.
	   ``Israel expresses hope that the Russian powers will find
appropriate ways to deal with this grave incident,'' it said.
	   Under Zyuganov, the Communist party has taken on an increasingly
aggressive, nationalistic tone. Anti-Semitic rhetoric has grown in
Russia since its economic troubles have deepened over the last
several months. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Israel-Russia; CT:i; 
