<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0759 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The Dow edged closer to new highs, but many
stocks sagged Thursday as holiday-bound investors nibbled at their
big gains from Tuesday's record-setting rally. The Dow Jones
industrial average extended its winning streak to six sessions, but
rose just 15.96 points _ or by 0.2 percent _ at 9,217.99 by the
early 1 p.m. (1800 GMT) close for Christmas Eve. Still, including
Wednesday's 157-point romp, the Dow has tacked on 427 points during
that streak, closing in on the Nov. 23 record of 9,374.27.
(US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Americans' personal income registered the
largest increase in nine months and unemployment applications hit a
17-month low, suggesting the U.S. economy will enter 1999 with
enough power to resist the drag from economic slumps abroad. Income
increased by a seasonally adjusted 0.5 percent in November, the
most since February, the Commerce Department said Thursday. This
follows respectable gains in September and October. Separately, the
Labor Department said the number of Americans seeking unemployment
benefits fell by 13,000 to a seasonally adjusted 287,000 last week,
the lowest since July 1997. ``The economy is ending 1998 on a
bright note for the consumer, with incomes rising comfortably and
unemployment low,'' said economist Bob Dederick of Northern Trust
Co. (US-ECONOMY)
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Sales at the newly merged automobile
giant DaimlerChrysler AG were 260 billion marks (dlrs 158 billion)
in 1998, a company spokesman said Thursday. That is about 13
percent higher than combined 1997 of Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler
Corp., which were around 229.3 billion marks. On Sunday,
DaimlerChrysler will release sales figures that should reveal a
``qualitative trend'' for 1998, the spokesman said. Further
earnings details will be published at the Detroit Auto Show during
the first week of January. Analysts expect DaimlerChrysler to post
a net profit of between 10 billion and 11 billion marks (dlrs 6
billion to dlrs 6.7 billion) in 1998, after a combined 8.04 billion
by the two separate companies in 1997. (GERMANY-DAIMLERCHRYSLER)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Parliament gave quick initial approval to the
draft 1999 budget Thursday, stoking hopes that the hardliners who
dominate the legislature would cooperate with the government to
pull Russia out of its economic crisis. In contrast with the rancor
and commotion that have surrounded the passage of past years'
budgets, the lower house of parliament, known as the State Duma,
refrained from lambasting the government Thursday and voted 303-65
to approve the 1999 budget after its first reading. Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov rallied lawmakers' support in an emotional speech
before the vote, saying that Russia desperately needs the budget to
deal with the worst economic crisis since the Soviet collapse.
(RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   PARIS (AP) _ French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn
reiterated his government's skepticism Thursday about the merits of
Europe-wide tax harmonization. ``I don't know if it's impossible,
but I wonder above all if it's really desirable'' to achieve a
general harmonization of tax and social security charges in Europe
in the medium term, Strauss-Kahn said in an interview with daily
newspaper Les Echos. Strauss-Kahn said the principle of giving
European Union states freedom in setting their own fiscal policy
remained important, particularly given the different quality of
social services they provide. However, he said the EU should go
ahead with harmonization in the areas of corporate and capital
gains taxation and hoped it would happen by mid-1999. (FRANCE-EU
TAXES)
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ The government and the Solidarity trade
union on Thursday signed an agreement promising to preserve early
retirement privileges for miners, who suspended an underground
protest a day earlier. ``We suspended our protest for humanitarian
reasons,'' said Solidarity mining leader Andrzej Kaczkowski in
reference to the observance of Christmas, one of the holiest
holidays in predominantly Catholic Poland. Under the agreement, the
government promised to keep the early retirement rule that allows
miners and others employed in dangerous conditions to retire, with
full pension, after 25 years of work, no matter their age.
(POLAND-MINERS)
</TEXT>
