<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0763 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Includes items on Elton John, Monica Lewinsky, O.J. Simpson,
Prince Charles and Mike Tyson &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Singer Elton John stunned Britain's soccer
establishment by criticizing Premier League players as lazy and
overpaid.
	   ``The cost of players is spiraling out of control,'' said John,
the pop star who is chairman of the Watford team, which is not in
the Premier League this season. ``Then you see the players'
attitudes _ they are paid so much money and they are just strolling
around the pitch.''
	   British media reacted as expected.
	   ``Premiership prima donnas keep on breaking Elton John's
heart,'' the Daily Telegraph reported. The Daily Express described
John's comments as a ``Rocket from the rocket man.''
	   Premier League spokesman Mike Lee said Wednesday that John was
entitled to his opinion but was missing the true picture.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   KHMELNYTSKY, Ukraine (AP) _ A Ukrainian candy factory is fond of
President Bill Clinton and real sweet on Monica.
	   On Thursday, the Khmelnytsky factory in its namesake town named
its newest chocolate confection after Monica Lewinsky, the former
White House intern who ... well, you know the rest.
	   The rectangular chocolates bearing the name Monica are intended
to show support for Clinton, plant officials said.
	   Clinton visited this former Soviet republic several years ago
and tasted its candies. He later wrote a letter of congratulations
after the plant won an international prize.
	   ``We keep this letter as a precious relic,'' factory director
Vasyl Liubovetsky said.
	   The plant is hoping its Monica chocolates will find a huge
market. Its Israeli partner has already ordered a large batch.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ O.J. Simpson has made plans for ``a normal
Christmas'' with his children despite an appeals court ruling that
threatens custody of his young son and daughter.
	   ``We're not letting it affect our lives,'' Simpson said
Wednesday. ``We're going to have a normal Christmas, opening gifts,
having friends stop by.''
	   Sydney, 13, and Justin, 10, still spend time with grandparents
Lou and Juditha Brown, who were the children's guardians while
Simpson was jailed and his main opponents in the custody fight.
	   Simpson was acquitted in the 1994 stabbing deaths of ex-wife
Nicole Brown Simpson and her friend Ronald Goldman. A wrongful
death trial jury found Simpson liable and awarded the victims'
families dlrs 33.5 million in damages.
	   A judge returned custody to Simpson in 1996 but an appeals court
reversed that ruling Nov. 10, criticizing the judge for failing to
consider evidence that Simpson might have killed his ex-wife.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LONDON (AP) _ A casual question at an informal meeting has drawn
Prince Charles into the debate on the medicinal properties of
cannabis.
	   During a private Christmas visit to a charity home in western
England, Charles told 36-year-old Karen Drake, who suffers from
multiple sclerosis, that he had heard the narcotic was good for
easing pain from the disease, according to British newspapers
Thursday.
	   ``He (the prince) asked me if I have tried taking cannabis,
saying that he understood that, under strict medial supervision, it
was one of the best things for it,'' The Guardian, a liberal
broadsheet, quoted Drake as saying.
	   The Sun, a conservative tabloid, quoted Drake as saying she was
``surprised'' by Charles' question, but wanted at least to try the
drug to discover if it could ease pain.
	   Campaigners supporting the use of cannabis for medical use
welcomed Charles' remarks.
	   A spokeswoman for Charles said it was a private visit and a
private conversation, but acknowledged it would be ``churlish'' to
deny cannabis was mentioned.
	   The spokeswoman, speaking on customary condition of anonymity,
said the prince was aware of the debate over the medical use of
marijuana.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PHOENIX (AP) _ Former heavyweight boxing champ Mike Tyson was
doing the talking _ and some troubled youths were listening.
	   The former heavyweight champion drew on his own criminal past
Wednesday to tell teen-agers in a tent prison to get their lives
together.
	   ``You're not here because somebody framed you even though we all
say we are,'' Tyson told about 15 prisoners. ``Even though I didn't
take anything from that girl, I put myself in that position.''
	   Tyson served more than three years in an Indiana prison after
being convicted of rape in 1991. He is training in Phoenix for his
Jan. 16 fight against Francois Botha.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-People and Places; CT:i; 
