<HEADER>
w2686 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Caribbean-Briefs     12-24 2456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Briefs,2503 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A Package of Caribbean News Briefs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; TRINIDAD: Minister angers Indo-Trinidadians, threatens to resign &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) _ A cabinet member who called
Indo-Trinidadians ``some of the most ignorant people on the
planet'' is accusing Trinidad's prime minister of creating a
``Hindu theocracy.''
	   Dr. Morgan Job, the minister in charge of affairs for the island
of Tobago, threatened to resign Wednesday, saying Prime Minister
Basdeo Panday was stoking racial conflict with attacks on news
media owned by people of African descent.
	   Panday and most supporters of his United National Congress are
descendants of East Indian laborers brought to Trinidad as
indentured laborers, while Job and the majority of Tobago residents
are black descendants of African slaves.
	   Two weeks ago, Job himself called Indo-Trinidadians who support
offering Hindu courses in schools ``ignorant idiots.''
	   ``The Indians here are some of the most ignorant people on the
planet that I know,'' Job said to reporters. ``The people who call
themselves Hindus and Indians in Trinidad are so ignorant it's
embarrassing.''
	   Trinidad and Tobago, an oil-rich Caribbean country off the coast
of Venezuela, has been marked by racial tension. The two ethnic
groups about evenly divide the population of 1.3 million.
	   Panday's party took power in the 1995 elections. All previous
governments since the country gained independence from Britain in
1962 have been dominated by Afro-Trinidadians.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Task force urges steps to promote democracy in Cuba
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ A draft report of an independent task force
wants the government to end limitations on cash transfers from the
United States to needy Cubans as part of a broader program to
promote ``rapid, peaceful democratic change on the island.''
	   At present, such transfers are restricted to dlrs 1,200 a year,
and the task force, sponsored by the Council on Foreign Relations,
says removing the limits would accelerate the process of creating
``a new group of Cubans'' independent of the state.
	   The co-authors of the report are Bernard W. Aronson and William
D. Rogers, both Democrats who made their marks in Republican
administrations. Aronson served as the top Latin America aide in
the State Department for President Bush, and Rogers held senior
State Department posts under President Ford.
	   A copy of the draft was obtained by The Associated Press. The
identities of other task force members were not available.
	   Beyond remittances, the report also advocates an increase in
family reunification efforts, scholarly and cultural exchanges,
direct mail service and allowing Cuban-Americans to claim relatives
on the island as dependents.
	   ``The success of the Cuban-American community is one of the most
powerful factors in promoting change in Cuba,'' the report says.
 &UR; JAMAICA: Aviation officials say Year 2000 problem to be fixed by
June
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Jamaica's aviation computers, charged
with guiding thousands of flights from North to South America,
should be immunized against year 2000 problems by June, officials
said Thursday.
	   The Civil Aviation Authority is waiting for a final dlrs 59,000
(Jamaican dlrs 2 million) appropriation from the government to
finish reprogramming, said chairman Thorrance Lewis.
	   Other funds are coming from the Interamerican Development Bank,
he said.
	   Jamaica's controllers are charged with guiding jetliners over
the western Caribbean Sea. So far in 1998, they have handled 16,100
flights, Lewis said.
	   Air traffic control agencies worldwide are rushing to fix an
error in older computers that could cause breakdowns when 2000
arrives.
	   Because controllers ``hand off'' airplanes as they travel from
region to region, each country's computers depends on other to
supply them with information about the flight.
	   The biggest problem may be in ensuring that nearby countries are
all in compliance, Lewis said.
	   ``We will only be as compliant in so far as the other regions
are also compliant,'' Lewis said. ``That is the major problem we
will have _ in coordinating with other states around us.''
 &UR; BAHAMAS: Residents complain of chilly reception at Atlantis resort
	   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) _ Feeling slighted, Bahamian residents and
their government are complaining about having to pay a fee to visit
attractions since the much-vaunted opening of Atlantis resort.
	   Islanders have sent letters of protest to Prime Minister Hubert
Ingraham, whose office in turn protested to Sun International Ltd.
on Tuesday, saying it was ``not acceptable, nor permissible, that
certain of the facilities at Altantis be closed to the general
public.''
	   The letter noted that the resort enjoys certain duty-free
privileges under the Hotels Encouragement Act, and that ``resorts
enjoying concessions under the act must make the facilities of the
hotel available to the general public.''
	   The resort's vice president J. Barrie Farrington said that
``obviously our desire is to accommodate the Bahamian community, it
is not to discourage or prevent access.''
	   But guests had complained of lack of privacy, he said, with
2,500 and more non-guests visiting on a busy day.
	   ``We created this very wonderful attraction at considerable
expense so we want to treat it more commercially ... and
justifiably so.''
	   The dlrs 450 million project, billed as the world's largest
island resort by creator Sol Kerzner, the South African
entrepreneur, opened two weeks ago.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Police to boost patrols after 22 killings in six days
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Reacting to 22 slayings in the past
six days, Puerto Rican police said Thursday they will increase
patrols in high-crime areas during the holidays.
	   Fifteen people were shot to death last weekend alone, officials
said. Investigators believe most were related to drug trafficking.
	   There were 50 men and 20 women killed in December, bringing the
total to 635 murders this year, down from 710 in 1997.
	   Police superintendent Pedro Toledo said Thursday he would also
send more police into public plazas, shopping centers and bar
districts to quell fights during holiday celebrations. He said
commanders had not yet decided how many extra agents they will
need.
	   The number of killings in Puerto Rico typically surges during
the holidays, when Christmas and year-end parties begin.
	   The cities with the most killings this year have been San Juan
with 195, Carolina with 114, Bayamon with 86 and Ponce with 85.
 &UR; ST. LUCIA: Leaders lament recent crimes
	   CASTRIES, St. Lucia (AP) _ In their Christmas addresses to
supporters, political leaders in St. Lucia lamented an outbreak of
crimes that have shaken this Caribbean island.
	   ``How sad that criminal elements will use this season of
celebration, this season of peace-making, to commit their acts of
terror,'' said Prime Minister Kenny Anthony. He said St. Lucians
``long for peace.''
	   Police have reported several armed robberies in recent weeks,
unusual for this country of 160,000 people. Last week, an assailant
broke into the home of 16-year-old Giselle Georges, then raped and
killed her.
	   Anthony pledged his government would ``work tirelessly for peace
and law and order, so that locals and visitors alike can be safe,
day or night, in their homes and on the streets.''
	   Former prime minister Sir John Compton, leader of the opposition
United Workers Party, urged St. Lucians to keep Christmas and
year-end celebrations peaceful.
 &UR; U.S. VIRGIN ISLANDS: Police want men who abandoned victim
	   CHRISTIANSTED, U.S. Virgin Islands, (AP) _ U.S. Virgin Islands
police are searching for two men who abandoned a dying man at a St.
Croix hospital.
	   The victim, 36-year-old Carl Decicco of Estate St. John, died
Thursday from head injuries.
	   Witnesses saw two men leave Decicco outside the door of the Juan
F. Luis Hospital Wednesday night. Police say Decicco appeared to
have been beaten, and they are calling his death a murder.
	   It is the 27th killing this year in the U.S. Virgin Islands, a
territory of 100,000 people.
 &UR; BARBADOS: Woman hefts 81 pounds of marijuana in luggage
	   BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) _ When 23-year-old Andonia Lynch
walked off the airplane in Barbados, customs officials were
impressed to see her managing a baby on one arm and an 81-pound
(36-kilogram) suitcase on the other.
	   They were even more impressed, however, by the luggage's
contents _ bags and bags of high-quality marijuana that had escaped
a recent police sweep of marijuana farms and processing huts on the
nearby island of St. Vincent.
	   Lynch, a St. Vincent native, was convicted Thursday of drug
trafficking and sentenced to three years in jail.
	   She was detained Monday night at the Bridgetown airport.
	   Magistrate Valton Bend ordered the 11-month-old baby into
government custody until family members in St. Vincent claim it.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Legal or not, relatives head to Cuba for Christmas
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Cuban exiles call it the
``Christmas disease'' _ a wave of ``serious'' illnesses that
relatives cite each year in requesting U.S. government permission
to visit loved ones in Cuba during the holidays.
	   Since Cuban President Fidel Castro decided to reinstate
Christmas, the epidemic has only become worse.
	   ``It's amazing how everyone gets sick around this time _ there
are more serious cases of sickness in Cuba than there are hospital
beds,'' said Raul Alzaga, one of three travel agents in Puerto Rico
licensed to arrange trips to Cuba.
	   The phenomenon seemed to intensify last year, after Castro
granted a one-time Christmas holiday as a favor to Pope John Paul
II and the United States moved to loosen travel restrictions,
Alzaga said.
	   This year, Castro decided to make the holiday permanent on the
communist island, and the number of Alzaga's customers traveling in
December to visit their supposedly sick relatives has risen by
about a third to 160, he said.
	   The U.S. Treasury Department, which regulates travel to Cuba,
does not track individual passengers visiting sick relatives unless
they make more than one trip per year. That makes it difficult to
estimate the number of travelers, an agency spokeswoman said.
	   However, Cuba claims about 70,000 emigrants in the United States
and elsewhere visited the island last year. It is unclear how many
entered to visit relatives.
 &UR; CUBA: Forget Santa Claus. For Cubans, it's family dinner on
Christmas eve
	   HAVANA (AP) _ Forget Santa Claus, Christmas trees and sleigh
bells in the snow. For Cubans, the family dinner on Christmas Eve
is the heart of the Christmas celebration.
	   Cubans crowded markets on Thursday to buy pork roasts and other
traditional foods for ``Noche Buena,'' which is especially festive
this year because of the declaration of Dec. 25 as a permanent
holiday.
	   ``I've never seen it this crowded this early,'' said Felicia
Margarita Baix, who arrived at the farmers' market in the Miramar
neighborhood to buy a pork leg at reduced government prices. ``This
is what it looks like for the New Year.''
	   The Dec. 24 tradition was lost or faded in importance for many
Cubans, especially after the Christmas holiday was abolished in
1969 by a government that was then officially atheist. The
government later declared itself a secular state and gradually
eased up on religious believers.
	   Interest in past Christmas traditions began to bloom last year
when the communist government granted a Christmas holiday as a
one-time favor to Pope John Paul II before his January 1998 visit
here. It was made permanent this year.
	   ``The Christmas feast is intimate, it is of the family, of the
heart,'' Roman Catholic Cardinal Jaime Ortega said earlier this
week. ``It is the love of the family gathered together.''
 &UR; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: Hurricane victims brace for bleak Christmas
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Rosario Ramos never
bothered with Christmas trees before. But this year, living in
government housing after Hurricane Georges destroyed her home, she
figured some holiday cheer couldn't hurt.
	   So she and her son decorated a tree, then carried it outside her
shack for the neighbors to enjoy. The blinking lights did little to
lift her spirits.
	   ``I can't go on like this'' Ramos, 41, said, staring into the
shadows cluttered with other hastily built shelters. ``This coming
year I have to do something.''
	   For a month, Ramos lived in an elementary school-turned-shelter.
Then the government moved her to temporary housing built in the
Perla Antillana area of eastern Santo Domingo.
	   Here, nearly 1,600 families _ some of whom lost children,
fathers or mothers in the storm _ live in cramped buildings while
they try to rebuild their homes and lives. Some 100,000 people are
doing the same around the country.
	   The site is loud, dusty and depressing. ``We have one bathroom
for every six people, and not everybody knows how to live together
as a community,'' Ramos said.
	   Georges killed 283 people, caused dlrs 1.7 billion in damage and
left more than 300,000 homeless when it raked this Caribbean
country on Sept. 22.
 &UR; VENEZUELA: In Venezuela, it isn't Christmas without contagious
Gaita music
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) _ When a radio disk jockey urged the
public to stop listening to ``Gaita'' music last Christmas because
he thought it was too rowdy, residents of the oil-rich city of
Maracaibo boycotted the station and scrawled pro-Gaita slogans on
their car windows.
	   The deejay quickly became persona non grata in Maracaibo,
birthplace of the hip-swinging, foot-stomping music that is as
basic to Christmas in Venezuela as ``Silent Night'' is in the
United States.
	   ``Christmas without Gaita isn't Christmas,'' said Hereberto
Molina, one of the kings of Gaita (GUY-tah) with 500 songs to his
credit.
	   Long confined to steamy Zulia state, Gaita is spreading
throughout Venezuela and to Colombia, Miami, Aruba and Puerto Rico.
Songs have been published in English, Italian, Portuguese and the
local Indian language of Guajira.
	   With its thundering African drums and irreverent lyrics, Gaita
developed over the last two centuries partly as homage to the
supposed apparition of the Virgin Mary near Lake Maracaibo.
	   Today, it's a craze among young and old alike. Teen-agers attend
Gaita concerts until sunrise. Their parents and grandparents dance
to the music on tape or in clubs.
	   ``We've got Gaita in our blood,'' said clothes salesman Henrique
Serrano, 24.
</TEXT>
