<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand-India </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jadeja will open for India
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IHITHISHAM KAMARDEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ India's cricket team received a
boost for Saturday's second test against New Zealand when opener
Ajay Jadeja was declared fit Friday.
	   The Indian vice-captain sprained his ankle before the washed out
first test and after days of hobbling was finally able to train
strongly.
	   ``Jadeja is fit and batted well at the nets. He came on the tour
as a first-choice opener and we have to respect that,'' coach
Aunshuman Gaekwad said Friday.
	   Gaekwad, emphasized on the importance of a good showing by his
team in the last two tests of the three-match series after the
first test in Dunedin was abandoned without a ball bowled.
	   India's last overseas series win was a 2-0 success over England
in 1986. Since beating Sri Lanka by 235 runs in Colombo in July
1993, India has failed to win a test abroad in 17 attempts.
	   ``We'll go in there tomorrow with a positive, aggressive
attitude because we have our pride to play for,'' Gaekwad vowed.
	   ``We've always been known as a team that wins tests at home. I
want to change that. In New Zealand we haven't won for a lone time,
and more the reason why we have to put a great deal into try and
win.''
	   India's 3-1 win here in 1967-68 remains its only series success
and it is yet to win a test since an eight-wicket victory in
Auckland in 1976.
	   A third seamer will be sacrificed to make room for controversial
off-spinner Harbhajan Singh after Trevor Jackson, the Basin Reserve
Turf manager said the wicket would take spin after the first couple
of days.
	   New Zealand too hasn't ruled out playing off spinner Paul
Wiseman alongside left-arm orthodox spinner Daniel Vettori,
although the first choice will be four seamers.
	   ``The pitch will have pace and carry. It might do something
during the first half hour, but my advice is to bat first. Come
third day, it will spin,'' Jackson said.
	   Singh's bowling action had come under close scrutiny since the
19-year old made his debut against Australia in March this year.
	   Although Singh has never been called for throwing, International
Cricket Council's match referees Ranjan Madugalle of Sri Lanka and
Peter van der Merwe of South Africa have questioned the legality of
his action.
	   New Zealand coach Steve Rixon said any irregularity in his
action was not blatant.
	   ``He isn't the sort of guy you would watch and say to yourself,
`He is a chucker' or `He has a dodgy' action','' Rixon said.
	   New Zealand (from): Stephen Fleming (captain), Matthew Horne,
Matthew Bell, Nathan Astle, Craig McMillan, Adam Parore, Chris
Cairns, Dion Nash, Daniel Vettori, Simon Doull, Geoff Allott and
Paul Wiseman.
	   India (from): Mohammad Azharuddin (captain), Navjot Sidhu, Ajay
Jadeja, Rahul Dravid, Sachin Tendulkar, Saurav Ganguly, Nayan
Mongia, Anil Kumble, Javagal Srinath, Venkatesh Prasad, Harbhajan
Singh, Debashish Mohanty.
	   Umpires: Evan Watkin (New Zealand), Eddie Nicholls (West
Indies). Television umpire: Steve Dunne
	   Match referee: Barry Jarman (Australia).
 &UR; (ik-tjh)
