<HEADLINE>
Report: Deal would give Murdoch, French TV biggest stake in Italy's
</HEADLINE>
pay TV &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ Telecom Italian has struck a deal to sell 80
percent of its pay TV unit to Rupert Murdoch's media empire and
France's TF1, Italy's ANSA news agency reported Thursday.
	   The accord has been long anticipated and much debated in Italy,
where some in government and media have argued against foreign
ownership of the pay TV industry. Murdoch is interested in the
lucrative soccer broadcast rights in Italy.
	   Italian investors have been scared off by the high investments
the operation would need in coming years.
	   Telecom owns 100 percent of the pay television unit, Stream. It
would retain an ``important role'' under the accord, including
technical distribution, ANSA said.
	   Lawyers still have to work out exact wording of the deal, ANSA
said.
	   The majority shareholder would be NewsEurope Corp., the Italian
branch of Murdoch's media holdings, ANSA said.
	   Murdoch's News Corp. owns the Twentieth Century Fox studio, Fox
network, the Los Angeles Dodgers, New York Post, the HarperCollins
book publisher and newspapers in Britain and Australia.
	   (ek) 	   
