<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Bridges of Paris,0610 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Disfigured by pollution and neglect, Paris bridges get a facelift
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos PAR101-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN PHILLIPS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Even by gargoyle standards, these were scary:
hollow eyes, crumbling foreheads, rotten noses.
	   But it wasn't only the gargoyles adorning Paris' famous Pont
Neuf bridge that were in trouble. The bridge itself, and many of
the others spanning the Seine, were falling apart.
	   Slabs of centuries-old stone had fallen from their arches. Their
facades were weather-beaten or blackened.
	   ``Something had to be done,'' said Pierre Bauda, in charge of a
15-year, multi-million dollar project to repair many of the Seine's
34 bridges. Work began in 1990 and is expected to be completed in
2005.
	   Walking under the Pont Neuf, which slices the tip of the Ile de
la Cite where Notre Dame stands, Bauda despairs: ``Look: it's
dirty, disgusting.''
	   Water had seeped through cracks in the stones, leaving festering
black stains. Under the moss-ridden arches, huge tourist boats,
which in the past have collided with bridges, plowed by. Heavy
traffic pounded overhead, taxing the bridge's foundations and
spewing exhaust.
	   ``The bridges of Paris face many threats. But air pollution is
especially hard to fight,'' said Christian Garoche, chief architect
at the Pont Neuf. ``If you cycle through Paris with a mask on, by
the end of the day it will be laced with dirt. So you can imagine
what it's like for the gargoyles and stone, sitting there for
centuries.''
	   Soot has penetrated the structures, making the stone porous and
vulnerable to erosion.
	   Much of the stone on the `petit bras' (small arm) of the Pont
Neuf, which links the Ile de la Cite to the Left Bank, has been
replaced. Each of the 12 arches could take up to a year to restore,
with stones cut to size and transported from quarries in northern
France.
	   The Pont Neuf, which means New Bridge, is actually the city's
oldest, dating to 1578. Its repairs will eat up at least a third of
the project's dlrs 114 million budget.
	   But there have been rewards already. After scraping away layers
of grime, workers discovered that one of the gargoyles was a female
face, alone among 383 males.
	   Two sculptors spent the summer swinging from supports on the
bridge to put the final touches on the gargoyles, half of which had
to be replaced entirely. The new ones were chiseled on the end of
slabs of stone weighing a ton and swung into their niches by a
crane.
	   ``When I'm concentrating, I feel transported out of time,'' said
37-year-old Witold Pyzik, one of the sculptors. ``But I'm brought
back to reality by the traffic, the police sirens and the tourists'
cameras.''
	   Other jobs have included improving the water-tightness of the
Pont de la Concorde. The bridge was built with stones retrieved
after the storming of the Bastille prison on July 14, 1789, setting
off the French Revolution that toppled King Louis XVI and put an
end to monarchy.
	   Every three years, divers plunge into the polluted Seine to
check on the foundations of the bridges.
	   In all, five of the bridges are listed monuments. Almost all
were built in the 1800s. Only three went up this century.
	   The newest addition, the pedestrian Passerelle Solferino, is
being built between the Musee d'Orsay and the Tuileries Gardens _ a
sleek, metallic structure between two classical bridges up to 300
years older.
	   ``The landscape of the river is constantly changing,'' said
Bauda. ``But the new must sit well with the old. These repairs will
guarantee that the old bridges last about another two centuries.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Bridges of Paris; CT:i; 
