<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Waiting for Bradley,0774 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In basketball and politics, Bradley passed before taking his shot
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITS to add photo number &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY120 &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURENCE ARNOLD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ There weren't many flaws in Bill Bradley's
game as a star basketball player at Princeton University, but coach
Butch van Breda Kolff pounced on one of them.
	   ``Bill is not hungry. At least 90 percent of the time, when he
gets the ball, he is looking for a pass,'' the coach lamented about
his star back in 1965.
	   Bradley never shook that habit, even as he moved to the National
Basketball Association and then into the U.S. Senate. Just as he
passed to others on the court, Bradley passed again and again when
urged to test his ideas in a race for the White House.
	   In 1988, fresh off his signature accomplishment in Congress, the
1986 overhaul of the income tax code, the New Jersey senator
decided he wasn't ready to run for president. He sat out again in
1992. And he quit when his third term ended in 1996 to travel the
country teaching, writing, and advising.
	   Now Bradley, 55, is making his move. He has formed a
presidential exploratory committee and says he is preparing to run
in 2000.
	   But some say he weakened his chances by passing so long before
taking his shot.
	   There are many questions. Can his style succeed in a national
campaign environment of rapid response and sound bites? Have two
years out of politics improved his campaign skills or weakened his
ties to his party?
	   In a clumsy 1990 re-election campaign that he almost lost,
Bradley seemed out of touch with New Jersey voters, refusing to
comment on controversial tax increases imposed by Democratic Gov.
Jim Florio.
	   Bradley himself said he ``put the crowd to sleep'' in a speech
to the 1988 Democratic convention and that his keynote at the 1992
convention _ held at New York's Madison Square Garden, scene of his
pro basketball triumphs _ was ``wooden.''
	   He also irritated fellow Democrats when he left the Senate
complaining that ``neither political party speaks to people where
they live their lives.''
	   William Warren Bradley has always followed his own path.
	   ``He was particularly resentful of people always telling him
what he should do,'' said a friend of two decades, Tom Hartmann, a
retired journalism professor at Rutgers University.
	   Upon graduating from Princeton, billed as the ``great white
hope'' for professional basketball, Bradley instead spent two years
as a Rhodes scholar at Oxford. Explaining that decision in his 1976
book, ``Life on the Run,'' Bradley wrote: ``The greater the acclaim
became, the more certain it was that the public appetite could
never be satisfied.''
	   He returned to a successful 10-year career with the New York
Knicks. Then, ignoring those who thought he should pay his dues
first, he ran for the Senate and won.
	   There was always speculation on the sports pages that this
cerebral athlete might be president someday. And his Knick
teammates called him both ``Dollar Bill,'' a play on his
tightfisted ways, and ``Mr. President.''
	   Political supporters have long seen potential in Bradley.
	   ``He could be a real unifying source for the country,'' said
Peter Burke, treasurer for Bradley's first two Senate campaigns.
``He's so strong on race relations, moderate on financial matters,
and he's got such a good grasp of the world economy. He'll do well
among women, and moderate Republicans over the years have voted for
him in New Jersey and will be attracted to him now.''
	   Bradley was long wary of a national candidacy because of the
loss of privacy, which he worked hard to protect. In that first
Senate run in 1978, he kept his home address a secret even from
volunteer drivers, meeting them at a local gas station to start the
day.
	   ``The public has a right to know if you're a crook, but they do
not need to know if you're a sinner, since we all are,'' he wrote
in his 1996 memoirs.
	   Bradley says he is thankful he did not run in 1992 because his
wife Ernestine was diagnosed with breast cancer later that year.
Bradley was by her side as she recovered from surgery and
chemotherapy.
	   Their daughter, Theresa Anne, was then in high school; she is
now a junior at New York University.
	   A week after declaring himself a likely candidate, Bradley told
some New Jersey Democrats that running for president is ``a
decision I have circled for about 10 years.''
	   ``You don't know if it's the right thing until after you've made
up your mind,'' he said, adding: ``I have never felt more right
about a decision in my entire life.''
</TEXT>
