<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pope-Christmas, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Celebrating Christmas, John Paul looks forward to new millennium
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Pope-Christmas-Text
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT in lead that Christmas is John
Paul's 21st, sted 20th, ADDS date of start of his papacy in 13th
graf, `Thousands listened ...' &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; ELLEN KNICKMEYER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ A stooped, slowed Pope John Paul II
celebrated the 21st Christmas of his papacy with his mind on the
next one, looking forward to the jubilee year that will begin
Christianity's third millennium.
	   John Paul delivered his Christmas Eve homily in a floodlit St.
Peter's Basilica. From there, on Dec. 24, 1999, the pope will
launch celebrations for 2000 with the symbolic opening of a door
that is sealed during all but church anniversary years.
	   ``My thoughts already turn to Christmas next year, when, God
willing, the church shall inaugurate the great jubilee with the
opening of the holy door,'' John Paul said in a midnight Mass
televised in about 40 countries.
	   The phrase was a slight change in wording from his prepared text
_ in the original, the pope said he himself would inaugurate the
jubilee.
	   Increasingly frail at 78, the pope had kept his schedule light
for days to rest for the midnight Mass.
	   Flu and a fever had forced him to cancel some events last week.
	   John Paul walked slowly up the long aisle of the nearly 4-acre
basilica. At times when he had to stand in the more than 1 1/2-hour
service, he often clutched his silver staff with both hands, the
rod higher than his own bent figure.
	   But he smiled when children came forward to the altar to present
ceremonial gifts. Leaning forward, he patted their heads.
	   Walking back down the aisle after the Mass, John Paul crossed
slowly back and forth from one side to the other, shaking hands
with the faithful stretching their arms out to him.
	   John Paul has devoted much of his papacy toward preparing the
church for the third millennium. ``It will be a truly great holy
year,'' he said Thursday.
	   ``For in a completely unique way, it will celebrate the 2000th
anniversary of the event and mystery of the incarnation in which
humanity reached the apex of its calling. God became man in order
to give man a share in his own divinity.
	   ``This is the good news of salvation. This is the message of
Christmas! The church proclaims it tonight by means of my words,
too, for the peoples and nations of the whole Earth to hear. Christ
is born for us. Come, let us adore him!''
	   Thousands listened inside the basilica. Many more lingered
outside in St. Peter's Square, where lights on the season's
nativity scene and giant fir tree were lit for the first time
earlier in the night. John Paul introduced both customs to the
Vatican after becoming pontiff in October 1978.
	   At midnight, church bells rang across Rome to mark the coming of
Christmas.
	   The pope no longer celebrates Mass on Christmas morning in St.
Peter's Basilica to allow himself more time to rest up from the
midnight Mass.
	   He is scheduled to keep up his tradition of appearing before
tourists and pilgrims in the square at noon on Christmas Day, when
he reads a Christmas message and gives holiday greetings in dozens
of languages.
	   After Christmas, the pope plans to have his usual few days of
rest at the papal residence in a town outside Rome.
	   (ek)
</TEXT>
