<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Bin Laden,0672 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bin Laden renews call for attacks on United States and Israel
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Recaps pvs and updates with quotes from ABC television
interview. &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Osama bin Laden, accused of
masterminding the bombings of two U.S. embassies, renewed his call
for attacks on the United States and Israel, a U.S. television
network reported.
	   ``We are confident that the Muslim nation would rid Islamic
countries of the Americans and the Jews,'' bin Laden told ABC News
on Thursday night, speaking through an interpreter.
	   ABC broadcast brief excerpts from an interview with the Saudi
millionaire, which it said was conducted Wednesday night in a tent
in the wilderness of Afghanistan under heavy security. Bin Laden,
bearded and wearing a loose robe, appeared healthy and alert.
	   He stopped short of denying that he tried to develop chemical
and nuclear weapons, according to ABC.
	   ``If I seek to acquire such weapons, this is a religious duty.
How we use them is up to us,'' he said.
	   Bin Laden, who has been living in exile in Afghanistan, denied
he was involved in the August bombings of the embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania but supported the attacks and said he knew some of the
suspects who have been charged, according to ABC.
	   ``These are true men whom we respect and hold in the highest
esteem,'' he said.
	   A U.S. court has indicted bin Laden for the two bombings, which
killed 224 people and injured hundreds of others, and Washington
has demanded he be extradited.
	   Bin Laden said he was not in his camps when U.S. missiles struck
on Aug. 21, in retaliation for the bombings. The United States said
the camps were used for training terrorists, but the Taliban
religious army, which controls most of Afghanistan, said the 26
people killed were merely religious students.
	   Bin Laden said he survived an assassination plot ordered and
financed by a Saudi prince, ABC reported, without giving the date
of the plot or identifying the prince.
	   ``They were offered large sums of money in return for
assassinating me. But I was not hurt,'' bin Laden said.
	   The Taliban has refused to hand over bin Laden, saying he is an
honored guest and will be protected in keeping with Afghan
tradition.
	   The Taliban's Supreme Court held an inquiry last month into U.S.
charges that bin Laden led an international terrorist organization
targeting American interests worldwide and exonerated him. The
court berated the United States for failing to provide evidence of
his guilt.
	   But the Taliban promised that no one, including bin Laden, would
use Afghan territory as a terrorist base.
	   They also said that bin Laden gave a written guarantee to the
Taliban's supreme leader Mullah Mohammed Omar that he would not
participate in any terrorist activity while in Afghanistan.
	   ``I am leading my life under the rules and regulations of Mullah
Omar,'' bin Laden said in a separate interview earlier Thursday
with the independent Pakistani news agency, News Network
International.
	   The Taliban said that means that bin Laden is not training,
financing or encouraging terrorist activity from his base in
southern Afghanistan.
	   ABC said its producer in Pakistan was hastily summoned to the
tent in the wilderness on Wednesday.
	   Bin Laden's campaign against the United States is aimed at
forcing Washington to withdraw troops from Saudi Arabia, home to
Islam's two holiest sites, Medina and Mecca. Bin Laden also has
criticized Saudi Arabia for allowing U.S. troops to remain there
and has vowed to overthrow the monarchy.
	   The United States also suspects bin Laden of financing the June
1996 bombing of a U.S. military apartment complex in the Saudi
Arabian city of Dhahran. Nineteen U.S. servicemen were killed and
about 500 people were injured.
	   The Saudi government expelled bin Laden nearly a decade ago. He
sought asylum in Sudan before relocating to Afghanistan along with
an estimated 300 followers. 	   
</TEXT>
