<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0304 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Ecuador and Puerto Rico. &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) _ Ecuador's Supreme Court has rejected
former President Abdala Bucaram's appeal of a two-year prison
sentence for slander and ordered his arrest if he returns to the
country, the court's president said Thursday.
	   Bucaram, who was known as ``El Loco'' or ``The Crazy One'' for
his eccentric behavior, was removed from power in February 1997 by
Congress for ``mental incapacity'' amid massive street protests and
corruption charges.
	   He fled to Panama, where he still lives, and in June an Ecuador
court sentenced him to two years in prison for slandering
opposition legislators Jaime Nebot and Alexandra Vela during his
six-month rule.
	   Bucaram also faces three charges of corruption and misuse of
state funds in Ecuador. He has denied the charges, saying he is the
victim of ``political persecution.''
	   The populist Bucaram was known for his scathing attacks on his
political opponents and wild campaign rallies in which he sometimes
sang rock songs accompanied by scantily clad dancers. He has vowed
to return to Ecuadorean politics.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Reacting to 22 slayings in the past
six days, Puerto Rican police said Thursday they will increase
patrols in high-crime areas during the holidays.
	   Fifteen people were shot to death last weekend alone, officials
said. Investigators believe most of the killings were related to
drug trafficking.
	   Seventy people were killed in December, bringing the total to
635 this year. There were 710 murders in 1997.
	   Police superintendent Pedro Toledo said Thursday he would also
send more police into public plazas, shopping centers and bar
districts to quell fights during holiday celebrations.
</TEXT>
