<HEADLINE>
Specifications of SS United States
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-FEA-US-Liner for Sale &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Size: 17 stories tall, 990 feet (302 meters) long. (The RMS
Queen Mary is 29 feet (8.8 meters longer.)
	   Service: 1952-1969
	   Architect: William Francis Gibbs
	   Accommodations: 1,972 passengers in 695 state rooms; 1,044 crew.
	   Features: Three dining saloons; 26 public rooms; three passenger
bars; two theaters; heated seawater pool; 19 elevators; more than
seven miles (11 kilometers) of walkways; more than five acres of
open deck space.
	   Propulsion: Geared steam turbine; oil fuel.
	   Maximum official speed: 38.32 knots (44 mph or 70 kph); Top
unofficial speed: 44 knots (51 mph or 82 kph); Cruising speed 32
knots.
	   North Atlantic speed record: 3 days, 10 hours, 40 minutes
(maiden voyage)
	   Present location: Pier 82, Philadelphia
	   Owner: Edward Cantor, Cantor Affiliated Interests, Linden, New
Jersey.
	   Paint: More than 92,000 gallons (348,256 liters) in more than
100 colors
	   Famous passengers: John Wayne, Princess Grace, Jimmy Stewart,
President and Mrs. Kennedy, Katharine Hepburn, Laurence Olivier,
Red Skelton, Shirley MacLaine, painter Salvador Dali, conductor
Leopold Stokowski, conductor Leonard Bernstein, Irving Berlin,
gospel singer Mahalia Jackson, Cary Grant, Jane Wyman, Tennessee
Williams, Marlon Brando, Bob Hope, King Edward VIII, Rita Hayworth,
statesman George C. Marshall, Billy Graham, Sean Connery and Bill
Clinton.
	   Other firsts: Last super-passenger ocean liner built in the
United States; first ocean liner with air conditioning in all
passenger spaces; first ocean liner with ship-to-shore telephones
in all state rooms; first ocean liner built to Navy standards.
</TEXT>
