<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Antarctic-Christmas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ice trekkers spend Christmas at place humans have never been
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RAY LILLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ Three adventurers on an ice trek
across Antarctica to the South Pole and back could claim the most
isolated Christmas on Earth _ in a blizzard-blasted tent pitched
where no human has gone before.
	   Their only contact with the outside world Friday from their icy
campsite 306 miles (490 kms) from the South Pole will be by Iridium
satellite phone, so long as the Antarctic blizzard allows the
connection.
	   New Zealander Peter Hillary and his team, Australians Jon Muir
and Eric Philips, are trying to recreate English explorer Robert
Falcon Scott's ill-fated 1911 expedition.
	   They are attempting to ski nearly 1,875 miles (3,000 kms) from
New Zealand's Antarctic Scott Base to the South Pole and back with
no outside assistance.
	   If successful, the trip will be the longest unsupported ice trek
this century.
	   Since departing Scott base Nov. 4 the three have covered 555
miles (889 kms), but failed to reach their hoped-for Christmas
destination _ the South Pole _ because bad weather this week has
again slowed progress.
	   In a Christmas message on Dec. 23, Hillary said the team was
excited about crossing the previously untraversed Shackleton
Glacier.
	   ``I guess we just about had our Christmas today, we got the top
of the Shackleton Glacier, and its certainly the best present any
of us could get,'' Hillary said.
	   ``But we've got the Titan Dome and the polar plateau still
ahead, so we'll be out there over Christmas.
	   ``While we're out there may all of you have a wonderful
Christmas Day with your family, and we'll be thinking of you.''
	   A blizzard began to blow soon after the message was sent. The
trio's families were hopeful of receiving a further transmission on
Friday.
	   Before the blizzard, the adventurers were making steady but slow
progress of 12 to 15 miles (20 to 25 kms) a day, hauling sleds
laden with supplies across the frozen landscape.
	   With no room for luxury supplies, the three will have a strictly
nontraditional Christmas dinner, sticking to their usual 6,000-plus
calories a day diet of high-energy muesli floating in a mixture of
cooking oil and butter.
	   They did have one yuletide surprise _ a handful of lollipops
stashed in one of their three sleds by Hillary's wife Yvonne.
	   A small Camembert cheese and miniature bottle of Scotch whisky
will be shared on Dec. 26 to celebrate Hillary's birthday.
	   Yvonne and Hillary's son Alexander will share Christmas dinner
with Hillary's father, Mount Everest conqueror and Antarctic
explorer Sir Edmund Hillary.
	   Having completed the ascent of Shackleton Glacier, the team will
now trek across the colder polar plateau where temperatures can
drop as low as -50 Celsius (-58 Fahrenheit).
	   The team aims to complete Scott's failed mission to manhaul to
the South Pole and back.
	   Scott and his team of four men, who set out with ponies and
sled-dogs, died of starvation and weakness only a few miles from a
supply dump, and just days from journey's end. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-New Zealand-Antarctic-Christmas; CT:i; 
