r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-BadLoans     12-24 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bad Loans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: Bad loans at Japan banks exceed previous estimates
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's 19 largest banks have problem loans 15
percent larger than the banks themselves had reported, inspections
by the Financial Supervisory Agency show, newspapers said Friday.
	   At the end of March, the banks held 57 trillion yen (dlrs 491.38
billion) in bad loans, the Nihon Keizai newspaper, Japan's top
business daily, quoted the agency survey as showing.
	   An agency spokeswoman refused to comment on the media reports,
saying that a senior agency official was to hold a briefing on the
inspections later Friday.
	   Based on their own assessments, the banks had reported a total
of 50.2 trillion yen (dlrs 432.76 billion) in bad debts.
	   The agency's survey, however, classified about 7 trillion yen
(dlrs 60.34 billion) in loans to the banks' related firms as
unrecoverable or high-risk, the Nihon Keizai said. The agency
conducted inspections of the 19 banks from July through November.
	   A mountain of problem loans left from the collapse of real
estate prices early this decade has threatened the health of
Japan's financial system.
	   Earlier this year Japan's Parliament approved laws aimed at
revitalizing the financial system and lifting the country out of
its worst recession in half a century.
	   The legislation, which went into effect in October, opened a
line of 60 trillion yen (dlrs 515 billion) in public money to the
banking industry.
	   The government can use the money to bail out weak banks or help
healthy ones rid themselves of a crushing burden of bad loans.
	   Under the new restructuring measures, the government has already
nationalized two major lenders _ the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
and Nippon Credit Bank Ltd.
	   The two banks were found to have liabilities exceeding assets,
with combined bad debts running more than 1.6 trillion yen (dlrs
13.79 billion) higher than they had previously disclosed, the Nihon
Keizai said.
 &UR; (kgo-km)
</TEXT>
