<SLUG> BC-FEA-World Symposium '99, 1st Add,0942 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: growing drugs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ___
 &UR; Asia
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
	   TOKYO _ Asian nations are struggling to turn around their
crippled economies with hopes of curtailing the growing
unemployment, poverty and, in Indonesia, stirring social unrest.
	   But many hope to turn the corner toward recovery. Key to that
would be fixing the financial systems throughout Asia that are
still in shambles.
	   The Japanese economy, which could potentially serve as an engine
for regional growth, is likely to continue to shrink, wallowing in
its worst recession in a half century.
	   Voter impatience with Japan's governing party is likely to come
to the fore if parliamentary elections are held during 1999, as
some expect.
	   More serious is the turmoil in Indonesia that threatens to
explode ahead of general elections in June and the choosing of a
new president that follows. Instability is sure to keep foreign
investors away from the once booming nation and keep its economy
spiraling downward.
	   Unemployment will likely persist in many spots, including
Indonesia, Singapore, Hong Kong, South Korea and mainland China.
	   In Taiwan, which has escaped the worst of the economic crisis,
parties will choose candidates for the presidential election in
March 2000. Rhetoric in recent campaigns questioning whether the
island should reunite with China at some point has kept Taiwan's
relations with Beijing tense.
	   Next December, Macau will revert to Chinese rule after nearly
450 years under Portuguese administration. Although Macau will
retain its political and economic system, tackling the Chinese
gangs entrenched in the enclave is a sensitive issue.
	   The major challenge in South Korea is to clean up, under a new
president, the bloated, debt-ridden business conglomerates that
thrived on cozy relations with past military governments.
	   ___
 &UR; Africa
 &UR; By ANDREW SELSKY &QC; 
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Primal issues _ securing life and
liberty _ will dominate affairs in Africa, with efforts to forge an
``African renaissance'' undermined by dictatorships, wars and
corruption.
	   Two elections hold promise for building and consolidating
democracy in two of Africa's giants: Nigeria and South Africa.
	   Nigeria, ruled by military dictatorships during 20 of its 38
years of independence, holds presidential elections in February.
Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, who took power in June following the
death of Gen. Sani Abacha, has vowed to step down and hand power to
a civilian government in May.
	   South Africa will hold its second-ever all-race election around
mid-year. Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, leader of the ruling
African National Congress, is expected to succeed President Nelson
Mandela. He will have the challenge of dismantling economic
apartheid, a legacy of white rule that left most of the nation's
wealth in the hands of whites.
	   Wars continue to fester and sap the continent's resources.
	   Efforts will continue to end fighting in Congo that has
destabilized central Africa and involves troops from at least seven
countries. Uganda and Rwanda back rebels seeking President Laurent
Kabila's overthrow. Troops from Zimbabwe, Namibia, Angola and Chad
are helping Kabila.
	   Patching up Angola's peace process will be even more difficult
after government and rebel forces resumed fighting in December,
using artillery and warplanes. The renwed fighting ended a
four-year peace pact.
	   In northern Africa, Ethiopia and Eritrea are poised to resume
clashes that killed hundreds in 1998.
	   And no end is in sight to the civil war in Sudan, which enters
its 16th year and is Africa's longest. An estimated 1.5 million
people have died in the war between the government in the Arab and
Islamic north and rebels of the Christian and animist south.
	   ___
 &UR; Russia and CIS
 &UR; By BARRY RENFREW &QC; 
	   MOSCOW _ Just as it started to look like things were getting
better after years of decline, Russia is gripped by its worst
economic crisis since the collapse of the Soviet Union.
	   Hopes of an economic turnaround have evaporated since the
country was hit by the global crisis in developing markets. With
much of the nation already resembling a disaster zone after decades
of stagnation, the government has no real strategy for dealing with
the country's problems.
	   Millions of people will continue to go without pay or pensions;
those who do get paid will be able to buy less and less as the
ruble plummets and inflation soars. While fears of famine appear
unjustified, life is likely to get even grimmer in a country where
many now live in poverty.
	   Among the few bits of good news, a majority of Russians continue
to back democracy. And after decades of decline and disaster, many
Russians are hardy survivalists who greeted the latest crisis by
resolving to get through it.
	   One of the few certainties will be the failing health of
President Boris Yeltsin, who is likely to spend more and more time
out of sight. But Yeltsin has been largely written off in Russia,
and if he steps down early or dies he almost certainly will be
replaced by an elected successor.
	   There is no clear successor to Yeltsin. The Communists should do
well in parliamentary voting next December, but are not likely to
win the presidency, which will be up for grabs in 2000 if Yeltsin
serves out his full term.
	   Things look bleak across the rest of the former Soviet Union as
economies buckle. Autocratic leaders are entrenching their rule in
Belarus and Central Asia. Ukraine will hold a presidential election
in 1999 that is expected to be a bitter contest.
	   ___
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
