<SLUG> BC-FEA-World Symposium '99, 2nd Add,0871 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: bitter contest.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ___
 &UR; Australia and Pacific
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
	   SYDNEY, Australia _ Australians face two momentous changes in
1999 _ one affecting their national psyche, the other their
pocketbooks.
	   Late in the year, they are holding a referendum on whether to
cut their last colonial link by dumping Britain's Queen Elizabeth
II as head of state, making the nation _ founded in 1901 _ a
republic.
	   Meanwhile, Prime Minister John Howard, who was re-elected in
October by promising to cut income taxes by imposing a 10 percent
goods-and-services tax, will battle to get that plan through the
Senate, where his party is not in the majority.
	   New Zealand heads to a national election of its own some time
before November, with conservative Prime Minister Jenny Shipley of
the National Party trailing in opinion polls behind the Labor
Party's Helen Clark.
	   The smaller South Pacific nations, represented by the Pacific
Forum, will step up their lobbying to urge major coal-burning
nations like India and China to reduce greenhouse gas emissions
before some island states are lost under rising sea levels.
	   The Federated States of Micronesia are worried about
renegotiating their semi-independent status with the United States
under a compact that expires in 2001. They fear Washington will be
less generous with aid than during the Cold War, when the islands
were considered strategic assets.
	   All the smaller Pacific island nations will be preoccupied in
1999 with the need to reform, restructure and reduce their
governments and civil service as well as privatize state
enterprises. After years of giving lip service to the idea, they
now see it as the only way to salvage their economies, and also
realize foreign donors are making reform a condition for further
aid.
	   Countries close to the International Date Line will spend the
year squabbling over which island is the best vantage point for
watching the first sunrise of the new millennium. Most hotel rooms
on Fiji, Tonga, Kirabati and Samoa are already booked.
	   ___
 &UR; Caribbean
 &UR; By MICHELLE FAUL &QC; 
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ Decolonization, drug-related crime and a
trade dispute with Washington are preoccupying the Caribbean
nations.
	   Puerto Rico's Gov. Pedro Rossello also vows to pursue his
crusade to make the U.S. colony the 51st state, despite losing a
December referendum. Rossello has friends in Washington who say
Congress is weary of supporting the Spanish-speaking island at a
cost of dlrs 10 billion a year for which Puerto Ricans pay no
federal taxes.
	   Former British colonies led by Trinidad and Jamaica plan to
scrap London's Privy Council as their highest court of appeal and
set up a Caribbean supreme court in 1999 _ part of moves to
overcome international opposition to the death sentence that
leaders want to use to fight increasing drug-related crimes.
	   Barbados wants a referendum to end the British monarch being the
ceremonial head of state, a move that could encourage similar
actions by other former British colonies.
	   Grenada and Trinidad plan elections a year early amid
allegations of government corruption and, in Trinidad, growing
racial tension between those of East Indian descent and blacks who
had dominated politics until the 1995 election of the first
Indo-Trinidadian leader. Similar black-Indo rivalries could explode
into renewed violence in Guyana, on the shoulder of South America.
	   Haiti enters 1999 mired in a power struggle that has left the
hemisphere's poorest country without a functioning government since
June 1997.
	   Several islands will lobby to retain their protected and vital
banana trade with Europe, in a row that could take over trade talks
between the European Union and the United States in March.
Washington is threatening sanctions unless Europe imports more
bananas from U.S.-owned producers in Central America.
	   ___
 &UR; United Nations
 &UR; By EDITH M. LEDERER &QC; 
	   UNITED NATIONS _ The United Nations enters the new year facing a
double challenge _ the global financial crisis and conflicts and
crises from Africa to Afghanistan, with Iraq again at the top of
the list.
	   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan paints a grim picture of the
world at the start of 1999: More wars in Africa, neighboring
nations embroiled in conflicts in Congo and Afghanistan, failed
peace efforts in Angola, political chaos in Haiti and famine and
civil war in Sudan.
	   The U.N. chief warns that unless efforts to find peaceful
solutions are redoubled in hotspots, ``we have every reason to fear
the worst in 1999.''
	   And unless the underlying distortions and imbalances in the
global economy are tackled, ``we must expect more conflicts and
even more intractable ones,'' he adds.
	   As Annan knows well, every global problem ends up at the United
Nations and he laments that crises are all-consuming and leave
little time for the organization's critical work in trying to
alleviate poverty.
	   But the results of U.N. peacemaking efforts are often
disappointing, partly because the world body is perennially short
of resources, and must serve the interests of its members who are
often at odds.
</TEXT>
