<HEADER>
w2752 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-US-SavingYiddish     12-24 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Saving Yiddish,0862 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Destroying a book so it will live forever'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY365-366 &QL; 
 &UR; By TRUDY TYNAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMHERST, Massachusetts (AP) _ Armed with little more than a
carton of discarded books and a dream, Aaron Lansky was a
23-year-old graduate student when he set about saving the remnants
of Yiddish literature.
	   Nearly 20 years and 35,000 titles later, he is about to give it
a permanent home in cyberspace.
	   Starting in January, the National Yiddish Book Center that
Lansky created will begin a two-year project to digitize its
contents.
	   Once the books are scanned into computers, people will be able
to order copies from an Internet web site. New books then will be
printed electronically on acid-free paper with a soft-cover
binding.
	   The cost of production, excluding the scanning, is about dlrs 6
per book, Lansky said. The printing time: 30 seconds per book.
	   ``That means we can sell them at a price that anyone, not just
scholars, can afford,'' Lansky said. ``It is the fulfillment of a
dream.''
	   Less than a year after he began checking out scanning processes,
Lansky has raised half of the dlrs 2.2 million needed to complete
the project. A dlrs 500,000 gift arrived recently from filmmaker
Steven Spielberg, after whom the digital library will be named.
	   ``Yiddish will be the first literature to be 100 percent
digitized,'' Lansky said. ``It will pave the way.''
	   It is, he observes, another strange twist in the history of a
modern literature, itself rich in ironies.
	   Yiddish literature dates to the mid-1800s when, during a secular
revival, Jewish writers published the first books in the Germanic
language that had been spoken for centuries by the Jewish
communities of Europe.
	   It was crippled by the Nazi Holocaust. Now, says Lansky,
technological advances have come just in time to rescue it from
decomposing on the acid paper on which it was printed.
	   ``This is all crumbling around us. In 50 years all these books
will be gone,'' said the curly-haired dynamo, waving his hands at
the dlrs 8 million library and cultural center he has built on the
rural, western Massachusetts campus of Hampshire College.
	   It was as a student at the young, nontraditional liberal arts
school far from the traditional centers of Jewry that Lansky first
learned to read Yiddish and conceived his dream.
	   He started his quest out of frustration at not finding a book he
needed for a graduate class at McGill University. At that time
barely a half-dozen libraries in North America had Yiddish books,
and scholars estimated that no more than 70,000 books survived.
	   Once he began amassing books that had escaped the ravages of
Hitler and Stalin, and the disdain of a younger generation that did
not read Yiddish, Lansky began distributing extra copies to
libraries around the world.
	   Even though books still come to his center at a rate of 1,000 a
week, only a few copies _ sometimes just one copy _ of some rarer
volumes survive.
	   ``You would think with 1.5 million books it would be enough
already,'' Lansky said. ``But just think of the cultural crisis if
only three copies of Dickens existed in the whole world.''
	   Now, the center has established collections at more than 400
libraries in 20 countries from Japan to Israel. And as interest
rises in the literature, more and more libraries are clamoring for
books, he said.
	   ``Every time we send out a book, we make hundreds of librarians
mad at us, because they want it,'' he said.
	   The scanning process developed by the Danka Inc., a Kodak
spin-off, requires the spines to be cut off the books, so initially
only those volumes with multiple copies will be scanned.
	   ``In two years we may have a better way,'' he said. ``Still, we
are destroying a book so it will live forever.''
	   It is, Lansky says, something of a vindication to be able to
hold a newly printed book in the 1,000-year-old language that gave
rise to the works of humorist Sholem Aleichem and Nobel Prize
winner Isaac Bashevis Singer.
	   ``When I was 23 years old everyone told me I was too late,''
Lansky recalled. Today, fewer than 1 percent of Jews read Yiddish.
	   Still, he said, it may have been just the right time as a new
generation became interested in Yiddish culture and literature
through college and other classes.
	   Lansky is one of them.
	   A native of the northeastern state of Massachusetts, he had
little connection with his Jewish heritage as a child. Growing up
in New Bedford, he considered Yiddish a ``secret language'' spoken
by his mother and grandmother when they wanted to keep something
from the children.
	   It wasn't until he took one of the first courses ever to be
offered on the Holocaust as a student at Hampshire College that he
became interested in Yiddish culture.
	   When he learned to read Yiddish, at 21, ``it was like a whole,
wonderful new universe opened up,'' he said.
	   He began scrounging Yiddish books in the old Jewish
neighborhoods of Montreal and Toronto for his graduate classes.
Before long he had abandoned graduate school in a single-minded
scramble to save the books.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-US-Saving Yiddish; CT:i; 
