<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/24/1998 21:29:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2753 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-US-SavingYiddish 1stAdd   12-24 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Saving Yiddish, 1st Add,0273 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMHERST: the books.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Every major Jewish organization told him it couldn't be done and
refused funding.
	   But, against all odds, more books turned out to exist in print
than anyone had imagined.
	   Some private libraries were lovingly presented, one book at a
time, over a glass of tea. Others, discarded by children and
grandchildren who did not read Yiddish, were literally snatched
from the trash as garbage trucks approached.
	   After one midnight phone call from New York City, Lansky and his
cohort of long-haired young ``zamlers,'' or gleaners, pulled 8,000
books from a trash container on 16th Street.
	   Books weren't all they saved.
	   A warehouse beneath the Brooklyn Bridge yielded 75,000 folios of
Yiddish sheet music in mint condition.
	   And suddenly the dream didn't seem so impossible.
	   A decade after he began collecting in 1980, Lansky not only had
the books, but had raised dlrs 8 million to build the center to
house them.
	   Under his leadership, the center has assembled an international
contributing membership of about 30,000 and has snared grants from
a variety of foundations. In 1989, Lansky received a dlrs 250,000
``genius grant'' from the MacArthur Foundation.
	   The center now has a paid staff of 20 people and an annual
operating budget of about dlrs 2 million.
	   Still, as he makes his way through the offices and the
computers, he will sometimes pause to pull open one of the boxes of
books spilling in unruly waves from the loading dock.
	   ``Each box is a treasure,'' he said. ``You never know what you
will find when you open them.''
</TEXT>
