<SLUG> BC-Gulf-US-Christmas,0550 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. carrier drops anchor for Christmas
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous to CORRECT date of movie to 1946, sted 1942. &QL; 
 &UR; By ADNAN MALIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ABOARD THE USS CARL VINSON (AP) _ Some 72 planes, including 46
fighter jets, were chained down Thursday as this gigantic aircraft
carrier dropped anchor to prepare for Christmas celebrations.
	   But the partial stand-down did not alter the state of alertness
on the 97,000-ton carrier where most of its 5,000 crews worked the
normal 12 hours.
	   The USS Carl Vinson, which leads an eight-ship battle group,
took charge from the USS Enterprise, which sailed out of the Gulf
Wednesday. Several warplanes that took off from the Enterprise had
been engaged in four days of air strikes on Iraq.
	   ``We have a partial stand-down for Christmas, but at the same
time... we are having our main engines at the ready, aircraft are
on alert and ready to go to the countries' bidding whenever called
to do so,'' said Capt. David Crocker, the commanding officer of the
Carl Vinson.
	   The carrier arrived in the Gulf on Dec. 19.
	   Earlier Thursday, aircraft aboard the carrier flew some 60
sorties, including ``a couple no-fly zone missions and mainly
training missions related to proficiency flying,'' said Crocker.
	   He said the aircraft ``picked up some signals from the Iraqi air
defense encampments, but none of them were threatening.''
	   Meanwhile, about 200 men and women were busy servicing or
rearranging the fighter jets _ 46 of the 72 aircraft on the carrier
are warplanes, the rest are support planes.
	   Some sorted out thousands of kilograms (pounds) of mail as the
carrier swung into a festive Christmas mood.
	   Some 25,900 kilograms (57,000 pounds) of mail arrived Thursday,
adding to some 22,730 kilograms (50,000 pounds) that arrived a day
earlier from around the United States.
	   ``It's a crazy operation,'' said Senior Chief Manuel Mendonza,
who is in charge of handling the incoming mail on the carrier as
several sailors came to pick up their mail.
	   I'm glad I took mine out earlier,'' said Mendonza, 49, of El
Paso, Texas.
	   Entertainment on the carrier ranged from an appearance of Santa
Claus from an FA-18 Hornet fighter jet to Christmas carols and
Christmas dinner to cheer up homesick sailors.
	   Several movies, including the 1946 classic ``It's a Wonderful
Life,'' were shown Thursday.
	   Still, everyone wanted to be home.
	   ``Not one of these people would not like to be home with the
family, including me,'' said Crocker, of Fargo, North Dakota.
	   ``I miss my mom's clam chowder. I wish I could be home,'' said
Petty Officer Kristina Manicke, 20, of Raymond, Washington.
	   ``It's my first Christmas away from family,'' said a tearful
Manicke, an aviation electronics technician.
	   Petty Officer Shelby Cornelius who works on an explosive
ordinance disposal team, said he was spending his first Christmas
away from his family in 12 years.
	   ``It's very unfortunate, but we don't have a choice. We have a
job to do,'' said Cornelius as he read his letter from his wife,
Patricia.
	   ``I will open the presents on Christmas day,'' said Cornelius,
whose wife is expecting a baby.
	   Normal operations, including reconnaissance flights are to
resume Saturday.
</TEXT>
