<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Taylor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taylor indicates desire to play on
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Australian cricket captain Mark
Taylor has given the clearest signal yet that he wants to remain in
charge beyond the current Ashes series against England.
	   There was speculation before this series that Taylor was
preparing to retire following the Ashes contest, although he never
suggested it was correct.
	   As Taylor prepared for Saturday's fourth test in the five-match
series, he indicated he wants to keep playing.
	   Australia tours the West Indies for a four-test series starting
in March and Taylor said he would like to play there again.
	   ``I'm fairly sure I'll go to the West Indies if the selectors
pick me,'' Taylor said Friday. ``I'm still enjoying playing and the
side is playing well with me as captain so provided those two
things are maintained I will keep playing.''
	   Taylor led Australia to a series victory on his previous tour of
the West Indies, but was unhappy with his batting form.
	   ``The one side I haven't played well against is the West Indies,
they have been the one bogey side,'' Taylor said.
	   ``I'll be going over there if selected, just trying to relax and
play the way I would play against any other side.''
	   Taylor, 34, has led Australia to 25 victories from 48 tests
since taking over from Allan Border in 1994, a winning rate among
the best in the sport's history.
	   During his aggressive and insightful reign, Australia has
stamped itself as the best test playing team in the world.
	   He made it clear his career was not set for a finish in the
fifth test at the SCG starting Jan. 2.
	   ``Whether it's my last Boxing Day test match I don't know, a
year is too long,'' Taylor said of the traditional Dec. 26 match in
Melbourne.
	   ``There's too many games between now and then, I'll just see
what happens in the next six months. I'll stop playing when I'm out
in the middle and things aren't happening for me with the bat, as a
captain or in the field or I'm standing out there one day thinking
'what the hell am I doing out here.' That will be the reason I stop
playing.''
 &UR; (tjh)
