<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Christmas Traffic </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Central Singapore snarled in huge traffic jam on Christmas Eve
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Christmas comes once a year, and that's how
about how rare huge traffic jams are in Singapore.
	   The city-state's main shopping district, Orchard Road, was
jammed with hundreds of thousands of people and bumper-to-bumper
cars from late Christmas Eve until until the wee hours of Christmas
morning.
	   It took about two hours for a bus to travel the road's length of
3 kilometers (1.86 miles). The street is lined with stalls
decorated with Warner Bros. cartoon characters and glittering
garlands in the trees.
	   Many shops stayed open late. But even when they closed, crowds _
from families to groups of teen-agers _ sat on stone planters and
benches enjoying temperatures of 30 degrees Centigrade (86 degrees
Fahrenheit).
	   The weather was relatively cool for tropical Singapore, located
just north of the equator. Hundreds of kids and adults wore red
Santa hats with blinking pompoms.
	   Less than 13 percent of Singapore's 3.1 million people are
Christian. But the multi-racial country emphasizes tolerance.
	   Christmas Day is a holiday, with the focus on shopping and
gift-giving. People of all faiths called out Merry Christmas to
each other under the palm trees. 	   
</TEXT>
