<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bahamas-Atlantis,0436 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bahamas residents complain of chilly reception at Atlantis resort
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DEBY NASH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) _ Feeling slighted, Bahamian residents and
their government are complaining about having to pay a fee to visit
attractions since the much-vaunted opening of the Atlantis resort
built by South African entrepreneur Sol Kerzner.
	   Islanders have sent letters of protest to Prime Minister Hubert
Ingraham. His office in turn protested to Sun International Ltd. on
Tuesday, saying it was ``not acceptable, nor permissible, that
certain of the facilities at Altantis be closed to the general
public.''
	   The dlrs 450 million project, billed as the world's largest
island resort, opened two weeks ago.
	   This week, it started charging visitors dlrs 25 and Bahamian
residents dlrs 12 to visit attractions such as a marine exhibit
with 30,000 to 40,000 species, and a see-through tunnel that
propels riders through lagoon filled with sharks and barracudas.
	   The letter from the prime minister's office noted that the
resort enjoys certain duty-free privileges under the Hotels
Encouragement Act, and that ``resorts enjoying concessions under
the act must make the facilities of the hotel available to the
general public.''
	   The resort's vice president J. Barrie Farrington said that
``obviously our desire is to accommodate the Bahamian community, it
is not to discourage or prevent access.''
	   But guests had complained of lack of privacy, he said, with
2,500 and more non-guests visiting on a busy day.
	   ``We created this very wonderful attraction at considerable
expense so we want to treat it more commercially ... and
justifiably so,'' he said.
	   On Thursday, the resort promised that ``in an effort to continue
our positive relationship with the Bahamian community, the company
will provide the Bahamian public with even greater access to the
features of Atlantis.''
	   Farrington said that meant Bahamians could tour the gardens and
refurbished facilities of the resort's original two hotels for
free, as well as the lobby of the new 23-story Royal Towers, the
highest buildings in the Bahamas. But he said they would have to
pay the dlrs 12 to visit the other new attractions.
	   That is unlikely to appease Bahamians, as indicated by an
editorial Thursday in The Nassau Guardian, which said: ``When
compared to similar attractions elsewhere, and recognizing the
amount of money that went into its creation, dlrs 12 is not an
unreasonable sum to pay ... But that is the deal.''
</TEXT>
