<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Trinidad-Racial Tension,0313 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Minister angers Indo-Trinidadians, threatens to resign
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT HOFFMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) _ A cabinet member who called
Indo-Trinidadians ``some of the most ignorant people on the
planet'' is accusing Trinidad's prime minister of creating a
``Hindu theocracy.''
	   Dr. Morgan Job, the minister in charge of affairs for the island
of Tobago, threatened to resign Wednesday, saying Prime Minister
Basdeo Panday was stoking racial conflict with attacks on news
media owned by people of African descent.
	   Panday and most supporters of his United National Congress are
descendants of East Indians brought to Trinidad as indentured
laborers, while Job and the majority of Tobago residents are black
descendants of African slaves.
	   Two weeks ago, Job himself called Indo-Trinidadians who support
offering Hindu courses in schools ``ignorant idiots.''
	   ``The Indians here are some of the most ignorant people on the
planet that I know,'' Job said. ``The people who call themselves
Hindus and Indians in Trinidad are so ignorant it's embarrassing.''
	   Trinidad and Tobago, an oil-rich Caribbean country off the coast
of Venezuela, has been marked by racial tension. The two ethnic
groups about evenly divide the population of 1.3 million.
	   Panday's party took power in the 1995 elections. All previous
governments since the country gained independence from Britain in
1962 have been dominated by Afro-Trinidadians.
	   The prime minister has had a running battle with the primarily
black-owned media, and his supporters physically assaulted
journalists during a party rally in November.
	   Panday did not react to Job's comments Wednesday, but Satnarayan
Maharaj, general secretary of the Hindu association Sanatan Dharma
Maha Sabha, called the Job ``mentally unstable'' and ``sub-human.''
</TEXT>
