<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Industrial Output </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's industrial output drops further than expected
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Industrial output at Japan's factories and mines in
November fell a larger-than-expected 2 percent compared to the
previous month, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry
said Friday.
	   With production down for the second month in a row, MITI
characterized the situation as remaining ``stagnant.''
	   ``Despite progress in inventory adjustment, the inventory to
shipments ratio is still at a high level, mainly due to weakness in
shipments,'' a ministry official told reporters.
	   The fall was considerably larger than the average forecast in a
survey of economists, who projected a 1.1 percent decline in
seasonally-adjusted production. The survey was conducted by Dow
Jones Newswires.
	   The government had predicted a 1.5 percent drop.
	   In October, the fall in output had been less than expected,
coming in at 1.2 percent.
	   Dragging down production in November was a plunge in the
manufacture of transportation equipment and general machinery, MITI
said.
	   Despite the drop, the ministry said output would rebound in
coming months, predicting a rise of 0.3 percent in December from
November, followed by a 1.3 percent rise in January.
	   ``Production will pick up on the back of higher output in
certain industries,'' the official said. ``But there still isn't
enough data to indicate that the economy has hit bottom.''
	   The ministry also announced Friday that retail sales fell for
the seventh month in a row.
	   Sales at Japan's major department stores and supermarkets in
November dropped 1.5 percent to 1.960 trillion yen (dlrs 16.9
billion) on the year, MITI announced, predicting another decline
next month.
 &UR; (gp-dj)
</TEXT>
