w2794 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BalloonQuest     12-24 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest,0573 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Balloonists face most difficult obstacle in round-the-world trip
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous to UPDATE with crew saying they are entering a
critical time for the mission; latest position. &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT SEELY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ With more than half the adventure completed, three
men attempting to become the first to circumnavigate the globe by
balloon faced a critical point in their journey Friday as they
crossed the Pacific Ocean.
	   British tycoon Richard Branson, American millionaire Steve
Fossett and Per Lindstrand of Sweden entered a weather depression
over the ocean that project manager David Partridge said threatened
to pull their balloon out of the jet stream, and reverse its
direction.
	   ``They are right now in the low pressure trough. If they track
north, they go towards the jetstream. If they go south they head
towards Hawaii,'' said Partridge.
	   Comparing the jet stream to ``a river of fast moving air in the
sky,'' Partridge said the balloon needed to stay in the jet stream
to have any hope of completing its mission.
	   ``The jetstream gives us the best possible speed. If we fly low
it would take too long to get around. We would run out of fuel,''
he said.
	   The crew, planning to fly at 28,000 to 31,000 feet (8,500 to
9,500 meters) in a pressurized capsule, was expected to reach North
America sometime Christmas Day, most likely in the evening over
southern Canada or Washington state.
	   The balloon passed the halfway mark Thursday on an eastward
circuit of the globe about 1,500 miles (2,400 km) east of Japan.
The journey began in Marrakech, Morocco, on Dec. 18.
	   At 0200 GMT Friday, Partidge said that the 272-foot-high
(83-meter-high) ICO Global hot and helium balloon was about 700
miles (1,100 kms) northwest of Hawaii and was flying at about the
same altitude as a jumbo jet.
	   Provided all went well, Partridge said that the crew would
celebrate Christmas with boil-in-the-bag turkey meals, and would
make decorations out of paper printouts of messages sent from
London.
	   ``The suggestion has been to cut those to make party hats,''
said Partridge.
	   The trip was expected to last an additional eight days to three
weeks and finish in Western Europe at the end of the 24,000-mile
(38,000 kms) flight.
	   The London-based support team said it was concerned by the low
frequency of shipping in the Pacific, which would make a rescue
difficult. On Friday, they were tracking the position of all ships
that would be under the balloon in the Pacific.
	   Balloon pilots navigate by changing the lift of the balloon to
ascend or descend into different wind systems, and cannot plan
their courses and speeds precisely.
	   Long-distance balloon attempts are often attempted in winter,
Partridge said, because the jet streams, which run from west to
east, tend to be more stable and strong than at other times of the
year.
	   The team secured permission from 97 countries for overflights
and initially had only four refusals _ Iran, Iraq, Russia and North
Korea.
	   China had said the balloonists could cross their territory below
26 degrees north latitude. But the trio drifted further north
Monday after navigating around Mediterranean storms and closed
airspace over Iraq, Iran and Russia.
	   With the help of British diplomats, the balloonists won Chinese
permission to continue if they got out of the country as quickly as
possible. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Balloon Quest; CT:i; 
