w2809 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Cease-fir     12-24 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Cease-fire </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Communist rebels declare Christmas holiday cease-fire
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Communist rebels have declared a
Christmas holiday ceasefire, the leftwing umbrella National
Democratic Front said in a statement Friday.
	   The ceasefire took effect at midnight Dec. 23 and will end at
midnight Jan. 3.
	   The rebel New People's Army, however, will remain ready ``to
defend itself, its guerrilla areas and the people'' against
government assaults, the front said.
	   The government earlier declared a Dec. 15-Jan. 20 cease-fire
against the communist rebels.
	   The government said the cease-fire will not cover law
enforcement and security functions and defense of government
installations against rebel attacks.
	   In a separate statement to mark the 30th anniversary Saturday of
the founding of the Communist Party of the Philippines, party
chairman Armando Liwanag said ``the objective conditions are
growing ever more favorable for people's war.''
	   Liwanag said the party now has ``tens of thousands'' of members
from a few score when it was established in 1968. Its guerrilla
army has thousands of fighters ``equivalent to several regiments''
operating on 60 guerrilla fronts in ``substantial portions'' of the
country, he added.
	   The military, however, estimates that the rebels, which had a
peak strength of about 27,000 in the late 1980s, now number only
about 8,000.
	   Liwanag accused the government of President Joseph Estrada of
trying to terminate the peace talks to escape its obligations to
implement an agreement on human rights, including compensating
victims of abuse under late dictator Ferdinand Marcos and the
release of political prisoners.
	   The talks began in 1992 under then President Fidel Ramos.
	   Liwanag also said the communist rebels' ``informal, friendly and
cooperative'' ties are now developing into a formal alliance with
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front rebel group in the southern
Philippines.
	   The MILF is the largest of two Muslim rebel groups fighting for
a separate Islamic state in the southern Philippines.
	   The government has a cease-fire agreement with the MILF, which
began peace negotiations in 1997.
	   A larger Muslim rebel group, the Moro National Liberation Front,
signed a peace accord in 1996. Some of its guerrillas have been
recruited into the regular armed forces. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Philippines-Cease-fire; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
